(47, 'Botswana', 'Botswana is a landlocked country in Southern Africa. The Kalahari Desert and the Okavango Delta cover the majority of its territory, and provide animals with lush vegetation during seasonal floods. The huge Central Kalahari Game Reserve, with its dry fossil valleys and rolling grasslands, is home to many species including giraffes, cheetahs, hyenas and wild dogs. Safaris are a popular activity in Botswana .', 'botswana', 'A country of slightly over 2.3 million people,[16] Botswana is one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world. It is essentially the nation state of the Tswana, who make up 79% of the population.[17] About 11.6 percent of the population lives in the capital and largest city, Gaborone. Formerly one of the world\'s poorest countries—with a GDP per capita of about US$70 per year in the late 1960s—it has since transformed itself into an upper-middle-income country, with one of the world\'s fastest-growing economies.[18]\r\n\r\nModern-day humans first inhabited the country over 200,000 years ago. The Tswana ethnic group were descended mainly from Bantu-speaking tribes who migrated southward of Africa to modern Botswana around 600 AD, living in tribal enclaves as farmers and herders. In 1885, the British colonised the area and declared a protectorate under the name of Bechuanaland. As decolonisation occurred, Bechuanaland became an independent Commonwealth republic under its current name on 30 September 1966.[19] Since then, it has been a representative republic, with a consistent record of uninterrupted democratic elections and the lowest perceived corruption ranking in Africa since at least 1998 .', 'The economy of Botswana is currently one of the world\'s fastest growing economies,[18] averaging about 5% per annum over the past decade.[18] Growth in private sector employment averaged about 10% per annum during the first 30 years of the country\'s independence. After a period of stagnation at the turn of the 21st century, Botswana\'s economy registered strong levels of growth, with GDP growth exceeding 6-7% targets. Botswana has been praised by the African Development Bank for sustaining one of the world\'s longest economic booms.Economic growth since the late 1960s has been on par with some of Asia\'s largest economies. The government has consistently maintained budget surpluses and has extensive foreign-exchange reserves.\r\n\r\nBotswana\'s impressive economic record compared to some of its neighbors has been built on a foundation of diamond mining, prudent fiscal policies, and a cautious foreign policy.Botswana\'s economy is mostly dependent on diamond mining. Diamond mining contributes to 50% of the government revenue mainly through its 50:50 joint venture with De Beers in the Debswana Diamond Company. It is rated as the least corrupt country in Africa in the Corruption Perceptions Index by international corruption watchdog Transparency International. It has the fourth highest gross national income per capita in purchasing power in Africa and above the world average .', 'Politics in Botswana is framed by a presidential system of republican representative democracy, in which the President of Botswana is both head of state and government, within a multi-party system. Executive power is vested in the government. Legislative power evolves in the government and parliament of Botswana. Since the country\'s independence, the party system has been dominated by the Botswana Democratic Party (BDP). The judiciary is independent of the executive and the legislature.\r\n\r\nBotswana is a multi-party constitutional democracy. Every election since independence in September 1966 has been free and timely. The white minority as well as other minorities in the country participate freely in the democratic process. There are two main parties as well as several minor parties. However, Botswana is also a state dominated by a major party, the BDP which has never lost power since independence. It is claimed that the country\'s openness and political system have been the determining factors in Botswana\'s stability and economic growth. General elections are held every 5 years.', 'At the end of the 19th century, hostilities broke out between the Tswanas, living in Botswana, and the Ndebele tribes migrating to this territory from the Kalahari Desert. Tensions also rise a notch with the Boer settlers coming from the Transvaal. After requests for assistance made by the Botswana rulers Khama III, Bathoen and Sebele, the British government placed Bechuanaland under its protection on March 31, 1885. The northern part of this territory came under direct administration as a protectorate of Bechuanaland, forming present-day Botswana. The southern part of the territory is integrated into the Cape Colony, and is now part of the North West Province of South Africa. The majority of Setswana-speaking people today live in South Africa.\r\n\r\nWhen the Union of South Africa was formed in 1910, encompassing the main British colonies in the region, the protectorate of Bechuanaland, Basutoland (now Lesotho) and Swaziland (now Eswatini) - the High Commission Territories - were not not included, but future incorporation is planned. However, the British Empire vaguely undertakes to consult the inhabitants of these territories beforehand. Although successive governments of South Africa have repeatedly sought to integrate these territories, the United Kingdom continues to delay its decision, and this integration never took place. In 1948, the National Party was elected to government and established apartheid in South Africa. He withdrew from the Commonwealth community in 1961, thus ending any prospect of integrating these territories into South Africa.', 'uploads/lova002.png', 'Besides referring to the language of the dominant people groups in Botswana, Setswana is the adjective used to describe the rich cultural traditions of the Batswana - whether construed as members of the Setswana ethnic groups or of all citizens of Botswana.[citation needed] the Batswana believe in the rich culture of Botho-Ubuntu, ‘‘People are not individuals, living in a state of independence, but part of a community, living in relationships and interdependence.’[1] Batswana believe in working together and in being united.\r\n\r\nThe name Batswana is used as a nationality for the people of Botswana and as an ethnicity for people who practice the same culture and speak the same language in neighbouring South Africa.There are different ethnic groups in the country Botswana among them are the Tswana (Barolong, Bakwena, Bangwato, Batlokwa, Bakgatla, Baphuthing, Bataung, Bangwaketse, Batawana, Bahurutshe, Balete); BaKalanga (BaLilima, Baperi, BaWumbe, BaNambya); Ovaherero (Baherero, Ovambanderu); Wayei, Bambukushu; Veekuhane (Basubiya in Setswana); Khoe & San groups; Batswapong and Batshweneng.[2] All these tribes believe in different customs however because of living together & inter-marrying for more than a century, they have now developed some similarities which are seen in the changing or developing languages in the country as well as shared cultures . The languages differ significantly from one area to the other or by the ethnic dialects but they are all regarded as Botswana languages. Some Tswana people are based in the Northwest Province of the Republic of South Africa, and Botswana.', 'uploads/download (32).jpg'),
(48, 'Burundi', 'Burundi (pronounced: /bu.ʁun.di/; in Kirundi: /βu.ɾǔː.ndi/), in long form the Republic of Burundi (in Kirundi: Republika y\'Uburundi), is a country in East Africa. \'Is without access to the sea but possessing a large shoreline on Lake Tanganyika, located in the Great Lakes region and bordered to the west by the Democratic Republic of the Congo, to the north by Rwanda and to the east and south by Tanzania. Since February 4, 2019, its political capital has been Gitega. Bujumbura, the former political and economic capital and the most populous city in the country, is the economic capital .', 'burundi', 'The first inhabitants of the region were the ancestors of the Twa, who represent less than 1% of the current population. The other demographic groups in the country are the Tutsi and the Hutu who constitute 15% and 85% of the population respectively. The Kingdom of Burundi was established in 1680 and ruled by Tutsi kings who imposed a caste system on the Hutu majority. The territory was colonized in 1885 by the German Empire before becoming part of the Belgian colony of Ruanda-Urundi following the First World War. Both Germany and Belgium continue the pre-colonial pro-Tutsi policy through the monarchy.\r\n\r\nAfter the country\'s independence in 1962, the monarchy was overthrown in a coup in 1966 and a republican government was established. Over the next 27 years, the country was ruled by a series of Tutsi dictators in a one-party system and experienced two more coups as well as a genocide of Hutu in 1972. Multipartyism was instituted in 1993. assassination of the first Hutu president in October 1993 after only three months in power provoked a genocide of the Tutsi as well as a civil war which lasted twelve years. Since the end of the war in 2005, the dominant party has been the National Council for the Defense of Democracy – Forces for the Defense of Democracy (CNDD-FDD), a former faction in the Hutu-dominated civil war. The country is still plagued by political instability linked to persistent tensions between the Tutsi and the Hutu, including several coup attempts.', 'Abstract: Ranked 187th on the HDI (out of 191 ranked countries), Burundi is one of the poorest countries in the world. However, since the accession in May 2020, of Evariste Ndayishimiye to the head of state after fifteen years in the shadow of Pierre Nkurunziza, the prospects are improving for Burundi with the lifting of sanctions. A rapprochement with the international community, illustrated by the return of bilateral and multilateral donors, has nevertheless been observed since May 2020, with an IMF program concluded in July 2023. An essential support to bring the country out of its political, economic and financial isolation.After narrowing in 2021, from 6.3% of GDP in 2020 to 5.3% due to improved revenue collection thanks to the fight against fraud and an increase in grants, Burundi\'s budget deficit is expected to widen again in 2022 to 12.1% of GDP due to a significant increase in investment spending (+104.6% between 2021 and 2022). For 2023, the IMF nevertheless forecasts a marked improvement in the public deficit, to -4.6% of GDP, driven by a drop in investment spending.', 'Politics in Burundi is based on the country\'s political system, which is a multi-party republic with a presidential system where the president is the head of state and the prime minister is the head of government. Executive power rests with the government, while the two chambers of parliament (the Senate and the National Assembly) share legislative power with the government.In recent years, the political landscape in Burundi has been dominated by the civil war that broke out in 1993 until 2005, and by a long process of peace and transition to democracy.', 'This article presents highlights of the history of Burundi, an East African country located in the Great Lakes region and surrounded today by the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the west, Rwanda to the north and Tanzania to the east and south. Its political capital is Gitega, its economic capital is Bujumbura.\r\n\r\nThe Kingdom of Burundi, probably founded in the 17th century, nominally became a component of German East Africa in 1890. After the First World War, it came under the domination of the Belgian Colonial Empire, within the province of Ruanda -Urundi, itself integrated into the Belgian Congo in 1925. Burundi became independent on July 1, 1962, under the regime of the constitutional monarchy.\r\n\r\nThe country then experienced lasting political instability, marked by coups d\'etat, inter-community massacres, then a civil war from 1993. This ended in 2000 with the Arusha Accords, opening a period of precarious peace. Since 2010, tensions have again been particularly high.', 'uploads/lova7.jpg', 'The culture of Burundi (East Africa) primarily refers to the observable cultural practices of its 11,000,000 inhabitants.The main languages spoken in the Burundian republic are Kirundi, French (both official) and Swahili. It is the second most densely populated country on the African mainland (after Rwanda). The vast majority of people are Christians (75%), around 20% Burundians follow African religions with a few percent of people being Muslim. The major ethnic groups are Hutu (84%), Tutsi (14%) and Twa (1%).\r\n\r\nThe traditional clothing is a cloth wraparound called a pagne. In rural areas women, girls and elderly men still wear them over dresses, blouses or shirts. Women also wear scarves over their heads. Men always wear long pants as shorts are just worn by young children and schoolboys .', 'uploads/download (33).jpg'),
(49, 'Camerron', 'Cameroon (/ka.mə.ʁun/ or /kam.ʁun/), in a long form the Republic of Cameroon (in English: Cameroon and Republic of Cameroon), is an African Center-West State located between Nigeria In North-North West, Chad in North-North-East, the Central African Republic in the East, the Republic of Congo in the Southeast, Gabon in the south, Equatorial Guinea in the Southwest and the Gulf of Guinea at the South West. Official languages are French and English for a country with a multitude of local languages.', 'camerron', 'Before the colonial period, the inhabitants did not form a single homogeneous group and presented several forms of social organization ranging from structured kingdoms to nomadic ethnic groups. The former kingdoms (Bamoun, Bonjongo, Adamaoua, Garoua) were followed in the 19th century by German colonization, which placed Cameroon under a protectorate. At the end of the First World War, Cameroon was placed under a mandate from the League of Nations and entrusted to the administration of France for its eastern part and of the United Kingdom for its western part. In the aftermath of the Second World War, it was placed under the supervision of the UN, which reallocated its administration to the two countries. The former trusteeship of the UN under French administration gained independence under the name of Republic of Cameroon on January 1, 1960 with President Ahmadou Ahidjo. It was joined by Southern Cameroons (part of the territory under British administration) on October 1, 1961 to form the Federal Republic of Cameroon which, on May 20, 1972, was renamed United Republic of Cameroon, then Republic of Cameroon in 1984. Since the Ahidjo\'s resignation in 1982, Paul Biya serves as the country\'s president. As with most states in Africa, the current borders of the country are the result of European colonization which separated the same ethnic groups such as the Fang-Beti who are found in Cameroon and Gabon.\r\n\r\nCameroon is now a full member of the International Organization of La Francophonie, the Commonwealth and the Organization of Islamic Cooperation.\r\n\r\nCameroon is nicknamed \"Africa in miniature\" because of its climatological, mining, geographical, human, linguistic and cultural diversity. The country stretches north to Lake Chad, linking Equatorial Africa to West Africa and forming a bridge between West and Central Africa. The south-west of the country has an important volcanic chain dominated by Mount Cameroon, which is the highest point in Central Africa at 4,100 m.', 'Cameroon is richly endowed with natural (oil and gas, minerals and precious wood) and agricultural (coffee, cotton, cocoa, corn and cassava) resources. The first regional elections were held in December 2020 .Cameroon\'s economy is the most diversified in Central Africa, not only thanks to numerous foreign establishments but also to numerous national groups. There are very varied activities in the country, particularly in the forestry and agricultural sectors (cash and food crops), hydrocarbons, the beverage industry, sugar mills, oil mills, soap factories, flour mills, aluminium, cement, metallurgy, first wood processing, etc.\r\n\r\nIn the early 1980s, Cameroon was among the most economically successful African countries. Indeed, until 1985 and during two decades of steady growth, the Cameroonian economy recorded real growth rates of the order of 7%, up to double digits between 1977 and 1980. The following years were marked by a deep recession. One of the causes is the fall in the prices of coffee, cocoa and oil, which led to a deterioration in the terms of trade.', 'Cameroon is a presidential republic. Power is concentrated in the hands of the President of the Republic recognized by the constitution as the one who \"define the policy of the nation\" (Title II, Chapter 1, article 5, paragraph 231).\r\n\r\n\r\nPaul Biya one-on-one with the President of the National Assembly MKavayé Yégué Dibril.\r\nLegislative power is exercised by Parliament. It is composed of two chambers, the National Assembly (where there are 180 deputies) and the Senate (composed of 100 senators), the Senate has been in place since May 14, 2013.\r\n\r\n\r\nPresident Paul Biya face to face with opponent Jean-Jacques Ekindi.\r\nThe regime is often referred to as a “democracy” insofar as Cameroon\'s political system is more akin to a procedural democracy; behind the institutions functioning a priori democratically, the reality of the exercise of power is that of a dictatorship which forcefully represses any hint of political or social protest. Imprisonments of journalists, writers, trade unionists and activists are frequent.\r\n\r\nOn April 10, 2008, the National Assembly adopted the bill on the constitutional revision with 157 votes for, 5 against and 15 not voting. This adopted project is highly criticized by the opposition political parties since it allows Paul Biya to claim a fourth term at the end of his term in 2011.\r\n\r\n\r\nMaurice Kamto, Cameroonian opponent.\r\nOn October 9, 2011, Paul Biya was re-elected through presidential elections in the first round of voting and with 77.99% of the votes. On December 9, 2011, there is a new government headed by Prime Minister Philémon Yang, who succeeds himself. On January 4, 2019, Joseph Dion Ngute was appointed Prime Minister.', 'The first inhabitants of Cameroon are probably the Baka hunter-gatherers, pygmy nomads. But from the first millennium BC. J.-C. develop sedentary societies of farmers-breeders, perhaps from the Sahara then in the process of desertification, and the Baka are pushed back into the forests of the southern and eastern provinces where they are still found . Among the sedentary people, those of the south-west of present-day Cameroon and the south-east of Nigeria are the oldest attested as using Bantu languages. These languages ​​then spread through most of western sub-Saharan Africa, as far as South Africa, probably at the same time as agriculture. The first historical mention of the Cameroonian coasts could be found in the story known as the Periplus of Hanno, in a much-discussed Greek text. In the fifth century BC. J.-C., this Carthaginian reached Mount Cameroon which he baptized the Chariot of the Gods. But this text is controversial for its rough translation from Phoenician and especially because there is no archaeological evidence that the Carthaginians went south from Essaouira.', 'uploads/lova8.jpg', 'Cameroon is a secular state with a diversity of religions, whose followers cohabit peacefully together. Christianity and Islam are the two most common religions, about 70% Christian; 20.9% Muslim; 5.6% animists and 3.2% free thinkers .\r\nThe culture of Cameroon, a country in Central Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its inhabitants (24,000,000, 2017 estimate). Cameroonian culture is characterized by a very great diversity, linked to its ethnic diversity and by a great influence of French and English-speaking cultures. Cameroon has hundreds of traditional kingdoms (Bodjongo\'a Mbèdi, Akwa-Nord, Bali-nyonga, Bafut, Bafoussam, Foumban...) mostly concentrated near the coast, as well as in the North and West of the country . Bodjongo\'a Mbèdi, on the coast, is an exception because its royal dynasty dates back beyond the tenth century, while most of the others were founded in the sixteenth century. These kingdoms are organized around the emblematic figure of the chief who exercises his power within the framework of a very hierarchical system, where gravitate wives, assistants, notables who make children aware of ancestral rites, accompanied by dignitaries who harvest herbs and roots. in the sacred forests for the secret societies, devoted servants, painters, sculptors and groups of adolescents who constitute structured guards. These entities have an essential and fundamental role in the cultural, political and social life of the country .', 'uploads/1637130-2203433.jpg'),
(41, 'South Africa', 'South Africa has 57.72 million inhabitants4,5 in 2018 broken down into 80.2% Blacks, 8.8% Coloureds, 8.4% Whites and 2.5% Asians (sub- Indian continent)4. A nation with very varied phenotypes, South Africa is thus the country in Africa with the largest portion of so-called colored, white and Asian populations. It is often referred to as the \"rainbow nation\", a concept coined by the Anglican Archbishop and South African human rights activist Desmond Tutu to designate the diversity of the South African nation and which has replaced the concept of plural society previously employed by apartheid theorists (1948-1991).\r\n\r\nIncome equality between different population groups has not improved since the end of apartheid and South Africa has one of the highest rates of inequality in the world6. It is, however, a reference power for the African continent6 with one of the most developed economies on the continent and modern infrastructures covering the whole country. It is the second economic power in Africa behind Nigeria7,8. The country is also characterized by a large population of European origin (Afrikaners, Anglo-South Africans) and by significant mineral wealth (gold, diamonds, coal, etc.) which made it an indispensable ally of Western countries during the cold War.\r\n\r\nThe denomination \"Republic of South Africa\" ​​N 1 succeeded that of \"Union of South Africa\" ​​on May 31, 1961, when the country ceased to be a constitutional monarchy to become a republic.', 'south-africa', 'South Africa, in long form the Republic of South Africa, is a country in southern Africa. Its administrative capital is Pretoria. It borders to the west-northwest with Namibia, to the north and north-northeast with Botswana, to the northeast with Zimbabwe, and to the east-northeast with Mozambique and the \'Eswatini. Lesotho is a landlocked state within South African territory.', 'South Africa\'s economy is a two-speed economy: one part is on par with the industrialized countries and the other has dire needs for basic infrastructure. South Africa is the second largest economy in Africa in terms of GDP5, however the country is considered the most industrialized and with the most advanced technologies on the continent. Although the natural resource extraction industry (including chrome, manganese, gold and platinum) remains one of the largest in the country with an annual GDP contribution of $13.5 billion, South Africa\'s economy has diversified since the end of apartheid, particularly in services. In 2019, the financial industry contributed $41.4 billion to South Africa\'s GDP8. In 2021, financial institutions based in South Africa managed over $1.41 trillion in assets9. As of October 2021, the total market capitalization of the Johannesburg Stock Exchange is $1.28 trillion.\r\n\r\nAccording to the Human Development Index (HDI) of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), South Africa fell 36 places in their ranking between 1990 and 2021, noting the general impoverishment of the population. In Zimbabwe and Côte d\'Ivoire, the latter generated waves of immigration to South Africa. Many Africans immigrate to South Africa to earn more money than in their home countries.\r\n\r\nIn 2023, South Africa faces persistent electricity supply constraints, poor governance of state-owned enterprises and a slowing global economy. Ongoing difficulties in rail freight transport, such as frequent derailments, a shortage of locomotives and cable thefts are also penalizing the economy. The trade deficit worsened due to lower export prices and higher import prices.', 'Since that date, the political life of the country has been dominated by the ANC (57.5% during the legislative elections of May 8, 2019). The former dominant party, the National Party, which established apartheid and dominated the country\'s political life between 1948 and 1994, disappeared from the political scene after its merger with the ANC in 2005 . The main lines of South African foreign policy were inherited from the struggle against apartheid, which ended in 1994, in particular the promotion of human rights and the right of peoples to self-determination.\r\n\r\nSouth Africa has abstained on all UN General Assembly resolutions regarding Russian aggression in Ukraine.\r\n\r\nSouth Africa took over the BRICS presidency on January 1, 2023. A summit is planned in this context in Pretoria in 2023.', 'South Africa is one of the cradles of humanity, since since prehistoric times the region was populated by hominids. South African researchers have discovered Australopithecus skeletons, dating back 3.3 million years, in the Sterkfontein Caves, an hour\'s drive from Pretoria or Johannesburg. But history retains that the San populations populated the region before the Khoi-Khoi. These two ethnic groups are part of the same Khoisan linguistic group and are the oldest peoples of southern Africa.\r\nBetween the 8th and 16th centuries, the progressive migration of Bantu-speaking populations from Central and Eastern Africa to the south took place. The Zulu, Xhosa, Swazi, Ndebele, Sotho, Tswana and Venda ethnic groups populating today\'s South Africa are the descendants of these Bantu migrants from the north.', 'uploads/lova01.jpg', 'South African culture is one of the country\'s major attractions and attracts history buffs from all over the world. Imbued with diversity and mixed to the extreme, it is expressed through languages, cuisine and music. At Tropicalement Vôtre, we loved immersing ourselves in the local culture and meeting the different communities. Take part in cultural events, taste local specialties, retrace the country\'s history through cultural visits... Here are some ways to immerse yourself in a South Africa deeply attached to its history and traditions. To help you in this process, let us share with you our discoveries about the peoples, religions, cultural life, gastronomy and history of the country.', 'uploads/image.jpg'),
(42, 'Algeria', 'Located in the heart of the Maghreb, between Morocco and Tunisia, Algeria is in contact with two major geographical areas. Mediterranean to the north, it is Saharan to the south. Largest country in Africa, Algeria is four times larger than France .', 'algeria', 'Algeria (/al.ʒe.ʁi/ Listen; Arabic: الجزائر (al-jazā\'ir); and Algerian Arabic: دزاير (Dzayer) or الجزاير (djazaïr); in Tamazight ⴷⵣⴰⵢⵔ (dzayer)) is a country of North Africa forming part of the Maghreb. Since 1962, it is named in long form Democratic and Popular Algerian Republic, abbreviated in (RADP) (in Arabic الجمهورية الجزائرية الديمقراطية الشعبية; in Tamazight: ⵜⴰ Its capital is Algiers, the city of most populated country, in the North, on the Mediterranean coast.\r\n\r\nAs of January 1, 2021, the resident Algerian population had reached 44.6 million. With an area of ​​2,381,741 km2, it is simultaneously the largest country in Africa, the Arab world and the Mediterranean basin. It shares over 6,385 km of land borders, with Tunisia to the northeast, Libya to the east, Niger to the southeast, Mali to the southwest, Mauritania and Western Sahara to the west. , and finally Morocco to the northwest.', 'From 1962, the Algerian government opted for a highly centralized planned economy, the first objectives were to give Algeria economic independence, in particular by recovering national wealth. A series of nationalizations was carried out in this regard, affecting in particular foreign companies. Subsequently, a considerable effort of industrialization is deployed. The oil counter-shock of 1986 sounded the death knell for this period of socialist planning, the State no longer being able to support during this period the financial investment it made for the benefit of national companies, nor being able to respond favorably to the new wave of job applications which have greatly increased with the demographic increase that the country has experienced since independence. Algeria resorted from 1988 to the IMF in order to carry out a structural adjustment, a vast program of reforms was undertaken in order to ensure a transition from the socialist economy to a market economy.\r\n\r\nCharacterized by a strong dependence on hydrocarbons, the economic situation of Algeria seems favorable until 2014 both internally and externally. Following in particular the very sustained increase in oil prices, the country\'s economic growth is following a constant and stable progression, rising from 2.1% in 2001 to 5.3% in 2005, with a peak of 6.8 % in 2003. Despite the presence of excess liquidity linked to the abundance of oil resources, inflation during this period remained under control thanks to the strict control exercised by the Bank of Algeria, the inflation rate at the end of 2005 was 1.5% against 3.6% for 2004. The unemployment rate fell throughout the 2000s, even though the youth unemployment rate remained high. In 2021, the industrial sector represents 5 to 6% of Algerian GDP.\r\n\r\nEconomic growth was achieved first by the construction and public works sector (+7.1%), followed by that of hydrocarbons (+5.8%) and services (+5.6%), while that agriculture grew by only 1.9%.', 'Politically, Algeria has adopted a republican regime since the advent of its independence in 1962199. Its current constitution gives the head of state a central role in the management of the country\'s affairs, thus under its articles, the President of the Republic is the Chief Executive and Supreme Head of the Armed Forces. The Head of State also has the power to appoint his Prime Minister and the members of the government on the latter\'s proposal. He chairs the Council of Ministers. The election of the President of the Republic is by direct universal suffrage, every five years.\r\n\r\nThe current President of the Republic is Abdelmadjid Tebboune, who took office on December 19, 2019. Tebboune succeeds interim Head of State Abdelkader Bensalah, who himself succeeds President Abdelaziz Bouteflika, who was forced to resignation in April 2019 by mass protests against the regime. Abdelmadjid Tebboune won the presidential election of December 12, 2019 in the first round, but the course of this election was marked by massive Hirak demonstrations and record abstention .', 'The history of Algeria is part of the broader history of the Maghreb and goes back millennia. In antiquity, the Algerian territory experienced the formation of the Numidian kingdoms considered the first Algerian state in history, before passing under the partial domination of the Romans, the Vandals, the Byzantines and the independent Berber principalities (notably the kingdom of \'Altava and the Kingdom of the Moors and Romans).\r\n\r\nThe seventh century marked the beginning of Islamization and then the partial Arabization of the population. The central Maghreb then experienced several local dynasties: Rostemides (767-909), Zirids (972-1148), Hammadids (1014-1152), Zianids (1235-1556) and periods of integration into larger imperial groups: Umayyads (in the 8th century), Fatimids (in the 10th century), Almoravids (in the 11th century), and the Almohades (in the 12th century).\r\n\r\nContemporary Algeria begins to constitute itself territorially at the beginning of the regency of Algiers, that is to say in the sixteenth century. French colonization upsets the existing social formation and causes the destruction of a large part of the religious heritage. The emergence, at the beginning of the 20th century, of a national movement led to the outbreak of the Algerian war in 1954, an armed insurrection which ended with the independence of the country in 1962, and the constitution of the State -current nation.', 'uploads/lova001.jpg.png', 'Algerian culture is marked by its diversity, its richness, thanks in particular to its different regions, borrowings from other peoples, as well as by its diffusion and throughout the world. Each region, each city or oasis constitutes a particular cultural space. Kabylie, Aures, Algiers, the High Plateaux, the Mzab Valley, Gourara, Hoggar, Saoura, Oranie are each regions with cultural and sometimes linguistic particularities.\r\n\r\nThe first cultural manifestations on the territory of present-day Algeria are thousands of years old, such as the fascinating testimonies of rock art of the tassili n\'Ajjer, through all the beautiful buildings erected throughout the history of this country, arriving at craftsmanship which is still very present and extremely wealthy. Algerian art reflects the chapters of history that this country has gone through and the different influences it has had.\r\n\r\nMuseums dedicated to a wide variety of themes, including the National Museum of Fine Arts, rich libraries, such as the National Library of Algeria, and a whole heritage of real estate, crafts and industry, testify to the development of Algerian culture.', 'uploads/Sbiba_Festival.jpg'),
(43, 'Angola', 'Angola is a South African country with a very varied geography. You can admire the tropical beaches on the Atlantic, a labyrinth of rivers and rivers and also a sub-Saharan desert that extends to Namibia. The country\'s colonial history is reflected in the Portuguese-influenced cuisine and its iconic sites like the São Miguel Fortress, a building built in 1576 by the Portuguese to defend the capital, Luanda.', 'angola', 'Angola has been inhabited since the Paleolithic Age. Its formation as a nation-state originates from Portuguese colonisation, which initially began with coastal settlements and trading posts founded in the 16th century. In the 19th century, European settlers gradually began to establish themselves in the interior. The Portuguese colony that became Angola did not have its present borders until the early 20th century, owing to resistance by native groups such as the Cuamato, the Kwanyama and the Mbunda.\r\n\r\nAfter a protracted anti-colonial struggle, Angola achieved independence in 1975 as a Marxist–Leninist one-party Republic. The country descended into a devastating civil war the same year, between the ruling People\'s Movement for the Liberation of Angola (MPLA), backed by the Soviet Union and Cuba, the insurgent National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, an originally Maoist and later anti-communist group supported by the United States and South Africa, and the militant organization National Liberation Front of Angola, backed by Zaire. The country has been governed by MPLA ever since its independence in 1975. Following the end of the war in 2002, Angola emerged as a relatively stable unitary, presidential constitutional republic.', 'Angola\'s economy is very dependent on the exploitation and export of raw materials: oil and minerals.\r\n\r\nAfter four decades of wars (independence and civil), economic growth soared between 2002 and 2016: the growth rate was 9% on average between 2002 and 2008. In 2018, Angola once again became the 6th economic power in Africa respectively behind Nigeria, South Africa, Egypt, Algeria and Morocco with a GDP in nominal parity of 105.75 billion dollars1. On January 1, 2007, Angola entered OPEC as a full member.\r\n\r\nIn 2016, hit hard by the collapse in oil prices, Angola resigned itself to appealing to the International Monetary Fund (IMF). At $39 a barrel, the state coffers are empty. Petrodollars no longer fill the coffers of the Central Bank. The decrease in foreign currency liquidity and the economic slowdown are increasingly weighing on the banking system, which is highly dependent on the oil sector. Bankruptcies, especially in the latter, are on the rise. The growth rate was positive in 2016 (2%), but much lower than the 20.2% growth in 2006, the 24.4% in 2007 and the 17% in 2008. The economy then entered into recession.', 'Angola is a republic with a multi-party presidential regime, where the president serves as both head of state and head of government. Angola transitioned from the People\'s Republic of Angola, a Marxist-Leninist one-party regime ruled by the MPLA (Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola) to a multi-party regime following the constitutional review and elections of 1992. President José Eduardo dos Santos Joaquim won the first round with 49% of the vote against Jonas Savimbi (40%). There was no second round and the civil war resumed.\r\n\r\nThe civil war, which lasted 26 years, undermined the country\'s political and social institutions. The UN estimates the number of internally displaced people at 1.8 million, and the total number of victims at 4 million. The favorable economic situation would make it possible to support social institutions, but in fact hospitals and schools lack equipment, and the State does not provide its employees with the necessary means to carry out their tasks. João Lourenço, born in Lobito on March 5, 1954, is an Angolan general officer and statesman. He has been President of the Republic since September 2017 and President of the Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola (MPLA) since September 2018.', 'The history of Angola begins with the Khoisan-speaking peoples before continuing with the immigration and occupation of the future Angolan territory by the Bantu-speaking peoples after 1000.\r\n\r\nA former Portuguese colony, it is the second Portuguese-speaking country by its size and the third by its population. The Angolan State was born in 1975. The current borders result from European colonization. Most of the population has since developed a national social identity, but African ethnic groups have at the same time maintained their specific social identities .The first inhabitants of Angola are khoisan living by hunting and gathering, knowing neither metal nor agriculture. Their societies, few in number, were (and still are not) not hierarchical, but egalitarian. Around 1482, the Portuguese explorer Diogo Cão reached Cap du Loup at the mouth of the Congo River. The Portuguese land and engrave the coat of arms of Portugal on the rock of Matadi (in the Democratic Republic of Congo) and erect a cross on the Angolan coast (padrão). The Portuguese first take advantage of the amazement of Africans seeing for the first time white men with unknown firearms, the mani-kongo is literate and converted while Jesuit colleges are built. The Portuguese also train stonemasons (probably to build churches), Mbanza Kongo is renamed São Salvador (Holy Savior) of Kongo. Most of the population nevertheless saw Christianity as an additional magic of the nobles.', 'uploads/lova02.jpg', 'The mixture of Portuguese and African culture has made urban Angola, especially the Luanda region, more like a Latin American than an African country. Its nightclubs, restaurants, and annual Carnival might seem at home in Brazil had not war and security measures made this sort of social life difficult.', 'uploads/angola.jpg.jpg'),
(50, 'Central Africa Republic', 'The Central African Republic, commonly known as the Central African Republica or designated by the acronym RCA (in Sango Ködörösêse tî Bêafrîka /kōdōrōsésè tí bé.àfríkà/) is a developing state in Central Africa, with an estimated population of 4,500 000 inhabitants in 2020, for an area of ​​approximately 623,000 km2. It is landlocked by Cameroon to the west, Chad to the northwest, Sudan to the northeast, South Sudan to the east, the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the southeast, and the Republic of the Congo to the south. -west. The country is a member of the African Union, the Economic and Monetary Community of Central Africa (CEMAC), the Economic Community of Central African States (ECCAS) and the Community of Sahel-Saharan States (CEN -SAD) University Agency of La Francophonie (AUF).', 'central-africa-republic', 'The country is divided between savannahs and equatorial forest (in the south), and essentially experiences a tropical climate. The Central African Republic also has many natural resources, including uranium, gold, diamonds, wood, oil, etc.\r\n\r\nThe territory of the Central African Republic corresponds to that of the French colony of Oubangui-Chari, which was part of French Equatorial Africa from 1910 to 1960. After independence, the country was led by various authoritarian regimes, notably that of Jean-Bedel Bokassa, president, then self-proclaimed emperor. France, a former colonial power, continues to play an important role. The first free elections with a multiparty system took place in 1993. They brought to power Ange-Félix Patassé, overthrown in 2003 by François Bozizé. The latter, re-elected in 2005 and 2010, was in turn overthrown in 2013 by the Seleka, an alliance of militias led by Michel Am-Nondokro Djotodia, during the second Central African civil war. In 2016, Faustin-Archange Touadéra was elected President of the Republic, then re-elected in 2020. Despite several ceasefires, a civil war has been going on since 2004 and the central government controls only a limited part of the national territory, fluctuating depending on the offensives of the different factions.', 'In the Central African Republic, per capita income was $446 in 2012. Agriculture accounted for 55% of GDP in 2001. The country has developed a mining industry, often artisanal, with deposits of aluminium, copper, gold , diamond, uranium and oil wells. The trade balance deficit deteriorated slightly from -8.1% to -8.3% of GDP between 2010\r\nand 2011. Two reasons for this deficit: the increase in the value of imports, with the increase in the bill\r\noil, but also the highest volumes of imported everyday consumer goods. Exports have\r\nexperienced an increase in value, from 15.5% of GDP in 2010 to 16.6% of GDP, driven mainly by the\r\nrecovery in production and global demand for diamonds and timber. The current cash balance has\r\nimproved thanks to the evolution of the balances of services and current transfers.\r\nThe overall external position remained fragile in 2011, notably due to the suspension of several\r\nexternal support and the slowdown in capital inflows due to delays and postponements of the main .', 'Politics in Cape Verde is characterized by a state model of a semi-presidential democratic republic where the president is the head of state and the prime minister is the head of government. The constitution of Cape Verde, approved for the first time in 1980 and substantially revised in 1992, defines the bases of the governmental organization. It declares that the government is \"the body which defines, conducts and executes the general internal and external policy of the country\" and is responsible to the National Assembly. The Prime Minister is the head of government and in doing so appoints the other ministers and secretaries of state. Members of the National Assembly are elected by universal suffrage for a five-year term. The Prime Minister is appointed by the National Assembly and his office is conferred on him by the President. The President is the head of state and is elected by universal suffrage for a five-year term, renewable once.\r\n\r\nThe judicial system is composed of a Supreme Court of Justice, whose members are appointed by the President, the National Assembly and the Superior Council of the Judiciary, and regional courts of justice. Misdemeanors and crimes are not judged by the same courts. Appeal to the Supreme Court is possible.\r\nThe Central African Republic is one of the poorest countries in the world. The country has been rocked by unrest for decades, but the coup led by Seleka rebels in March 2013 to oust the President plunged the already vulnerable population into crisis.\r\nAll citizens of Cape Verde aged 18 and over have the right to vote.', 'Cut stones dating at least from the 9th millennium BC have been found during excavations carried out in the Central African Republic. However, the absence of associated human remains prevents the attribution of these tools to a specific population (pygmies or other indigenous people). Subsequently, the transition from the Paleolithic to the Neolithic in the region was a gradual process without a sudden cultural break.From the 3rd millennium BC, the establishment and vigorous expansion on Central African soil of populations speaking the languages ​​of the Adamaoua-Oubangui group opposed the Bantu expansion which then found an outlet towards the South and the East. East of the mainland. The original geographical core of the Adamaoua-Oubangui language populations would be very close because it is located in the Adamaoua massif on the borders of present-day Cameroon, Nigeria, Chad and the Central African Republic. On the other side of the western foothills of the Adamaoua (which culminates at 3,400 m at Tchabal Mbabo in the Gotel Mountains) was located, on the Cross River, the original core of the Bantu populations. The two groups of populations will experience, in the 3rd millennium, a simultaneous expansion following the domestication of the yam and the oil palm.', 'uploads/lova10.jpg', 'Central African culture is diverse between peoples and ethnic groups.\r\n\r\n\r\nAka woman dancing in the forest.\r\n\r\nCentral African style.\r\nMost Central Africans (80%) speak languages ​​of the Adamaoua-Oubanguien group of the Niger-Congolese family.\r\n\r\nIn the north of the country live populations speaking Nilo-Saharan languages ​​(the Sara for example). In the savannah regions of the CAR are scattered different communities of nomadic Fulani (Mbororo). The vast majority of Central Africans are therefore not of Bantu culture.\r\n\r\nSome minority ethnic groups, living in the south-west of the country, are however Bantus, peoples common to Congo and Cameroon.\r\n\r\nThe Central African population is subdivided into a myriad of populations. Thus, each \"big\" city has its people, its language and a recent history linked to the political personalities and men of power who came from there.\r\n\r\nThe Pygmies are a visibly different people, by their size, and their culture of people of the forest. Long and massively considered as second-class humans, they have preserved their habits and maintain themselves in their environment, without access to the minimal \"social progress\" that the country has seen.\r\n\r\nFinally, with arbitrary and porous borders, we find all the groups of neighboring countries. Thus, a growing part of the population, in particular on the north-south axis running from Chad to the capital, is attached to the Muslim culture.', 'uploads/centreafrk.jpeg');
