(51, 'Democratic Republic of Congo', 'The Democratic Republic of Congoa Listen (in Kikongo ya leta: Repubilika ya Kôngo ya Dimokalasi, in Swahili: Jamhuri ya Kidemokrasia ya Kongo, in Lingala: Republíki ya Kongó Demokratíki, in Tshiluba: Ditunga dia Kongu wa Mungalaata), also called more simply DRC , Congo, DR Congo or informally Congo-Kinshasa (to distinguish it from Congo-Brazzaville), is a country in Central Africa. It is the third most populous country in Africa (behind Nigeria and Ethiopia), as well as the most populous French-speaking country.', 'dem-rep-of-congo', 'The DRC is the second largest country in Africa after Algeria. It stretches from the Atlantic Ocean to the Eastern Plateau and corresponds to most of the Congo River Basin. The north of the country is one of the largest areas of equatorial forest in the world, the east of the country borders the great East African rift, an area of ​​mountains, hills, the Great Lakes but also volcanoes. The south and the center, a domain of wooded savannahs, form a high plateau rich in minerals. In the far west, about thirty kilometers north of the mouth of the Congo River, stretches a coast on the Atlantic Ocean. The country shares its borders with the enclave of Cabinda (Angola) to the west-southwest, the Republic of Congo to the west, the Central African Republic to the north, South Sudan to the northeast, Uganda to the east-northeast, Rwanda and Burundi to the east, Tanzania to the east-southeast, Zambia to the south-southeast and Angola to the southwest. The DRC has been a member of the International Organization of La Francophonie since 1977.', 'GDP thus posted growth of 8.5% in 2022 according to the IMF (after 6.2% in 2021) - the initial forecasts having been raised - and this, despite a difficult external environment with the repercussions in particular of the war in Ukraine. The economy of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), after a period of relative economic dynamism, suffered a severe depression between the mid-1980s and the mid-2000s, linked to the civil wars that ravaged the country. With economic growth of 8.2% in 2008 and 2.7% in 2009, the DRC was then one of the African countries most affected by the 2008-2009 crisis.\r\n\r\nBetween 2010 and 2015, the country experienced average growth of 7.9% with a peak of 9.2% in 2014 and inflation largely under control. With the fall in commodity prices and the political crisis in 2016, the growth rate was only 2.4% before rising to 3.4% in 2017. Despite this, the DRC is modernizing rapidly and displays a positive development in the development of the HDI in 2016. Many projects have strengthened the health system, particularly maternal and child health, improved access to electricity and water supply, particularly as part of rehabilitation programs urban and social.\r\n\r\nAgriculture remains the main sector of the economy, representing 57.9% of GDP in 1997, and employed 66% of the working population', 'The Republic of Congo is a multiparty republic with a presidential system, where the president is both head of state and head of government. Executive power is in the hands of the government while legislative power is shared between the government and the two chambers of Parliament: the National Assembly and the Senate. From 1970 to 1992, the country, officially called the People\'s Republic of Congo, was governed under a one-party system. After the adoption of a new constitution in 1992 and until the civil war in 1997, the country\'s system of government was similar to the French system. Having taken power, Denis Sassou-Nguesso suspended the 1992 constitution. The constitution, adopted by referendum in 2002, returns to a presidential regime, with a seven-year term for the head of state and a bicameral parliament. The constitution, adopted by referendum in 2015, returns to presidential rule, with a five-year term for the head of state.', 'The oldest traces of settlement in the Congo are associated with a pre-Acheulean, discovered on the archaeological sites of Mulundwa in Katanga, Katanda 2 and Sanga 5 in Kivu. The cut pebbles or choppers have an estimated age of more than 200,000 years, without it being possible to be more precise today.\r\n\r\nThe territory of the Democratic Republic of the Congo was formerly populated only by hunter-gatherers, perhaps partly the ancestors of the current Pygmy peoples. Between the traces of a pre-Acheulean and the arrival of the first villagers, the Congo will always be occupied by nomadic groups, hunter-gatherers, stonemasons, from different cultures.\r\n\r\nThe Acheulean is attested by numerous isolated discoveries of bifaces and cleavers as well as by the site of La Kamoa in Katanga.\r\n\r\nDuring the second millennium BC. J.-C., the north of equatorial Africa saw a wave of migrations of producing populations, Neolithic people, speaking for some of the Bantu languages. Between –3500 and –2000, a first village occupation whose home was in southern Cameroon, led to the installation of a Neolithic mode of production in the north and west of Central Africa. In Congo, the first traces of these populations materialize around -2600 by the so-called \"Imbonga tradition\" near Mbandaka and Lake Tumba, and by the \"Ngovo tradition\" in lower Congo from -2300. On the other side of the country, in Kivu, villages of the “Urewe tradition” are appearing. These villages are only the western extension of food-producing communities, metallurgists, settled especially in Uganda, Rwanda, Burundi, western Kenya and Tanzania; the oldest traces there are dated to –2600.', 'uploads/lova12.jpg', 'The culture of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (about 105,000,000 people) reflects the diversity of the hundreds of ethnic groups inhabiting the country and their customs. The mouths of the river (Kongo-Central) are followed by a dense forest in the Congo River basin (formerly Orientale and Equateur provinces), and a savannah on the central plateaus (Kasaï), the most densely populated region of the country outside of the urban area of ​​Kinshasa. Since the late 19th century, traditional ways of life have been altered as a result of colonization, struggles for independence and more recently the First and Second Congo Wars. Despite these influences, the traditional customs and cultures of the Congo remain largely preserved.', 'uploads/images (10).jpg'),
(52, 'Ivory Coast', 'Ivory Coast, in long form Republic of Côte d\'Ivoire (RCI), is a state located in Africa, in the western part of the Gulf of Guinea. It is roughly in the shape of a square with a side of around 560 km7. Covering an area of ​​322,462 km2, it is bordered to the northwest by Mali, to the northeast by Burkina Faso, to the east by Ghana, to the southwest by Liberia, to the west northwest by Guinea and to the south by the Atlantic Ocean. The population is estimated at 29,389,150 in 2021', 'cote-ivoire', 'Ivory Coast political and administrative capital is Yamoussoukro, but almost all the institutions are located in Abidjan, its main economic center. Its official language is French, but some 70 languages ​​and dialects are spoken on a daily basis. Its currency is the CFA franc. The country is part of ECOWAS, the African Union and the Organization of Islamic Cooperation.\r\n\r\nFirst a French protectorate10 in 1843, then a French colony on March 10, 1893, the country gained its independence on August 7, 1960, under the leadership of Félix Houphouët-Boigny, the first President of the Republic. The economy, essentially based on agriculture, in particular the production of coffee and cocoa, experienced exceptional growth during the first two decades. In 1990, the country went through, in addition to the economic crisis that occurred at the end of the 1970s, periods of social and political turbulence. These problems were exacerbated by the death of Félix Houphouët-Boigny in 1993. The adoption of a new constitution and the organization of the presidential election which, in 2000, brought Laurent Gbagbo to power, did not ease the tensions social and political, which led to the outbreak of a politico-military crisis on September 19, 2002. After several peace agreements, the presidential election of 2010 saw the victory of Alassane Ouattara against his opponent Laurent Gbagbo. Re-elected in 2015, Alassane Ouattara revived economic growth through a liberal and interventionist policy while being criticized for his management of the army and justice. In 2016, a new constitution was adopted, marking the advent of the Third Republic.', 'Growth was driven by private consumption, supported by public investment and wage increases in the civil service. Inflation averaged 5.2% in 2022, the highest in a decade, due to rising food, transport and energy prices. \r\nThe economy of Côte d\'Ivoire, with a GDP per capita of USD 2,286 in 20194, is part of the developing economies. The poverty index reached 37.2% in 2018.\r\n\r\nSince the establishment of triangular trade during the first contacts with European explorers, the economy has been dominated by the export of so-called cash products; in particular, coffee and cocoa, whose cultivation was introduced at the beginning of the 20th century, strongly contributed to the \"Ivorian boom\" of the 1960s and 1970s (Côte d\'Ivoire is still the world\'s leading producer and exporter of cocoa ). While the Ivorian economy is based primarily on the agricultural sector, which is favored by a hot and humid climate, the contribution of industry to GDP is estimated at 20% and that of the tertiary sector at 50%. Côte d\'Ivoire also has some significant oil reserves for its economy. It also has some mining resources but whose production remains very minor. It also produces electricity, part of which is sold to neighboring countries.', 'Ivory Coast is a multi-party presidential republic, where the president is head of state. The executive power is in the hands of the government while the legislative power is held by the parliament. The administrative capital has been Yamoussoukro since 1983. The president is elected for 5 years by universal suffrage. The 1959 constitution gives it strong prerogatives; he is commander-in-chief of the armed forces, can negotiate and ratify international treaties, can propose a law to the National Assembly or submit it to a referendum. He is assisted by a vice-president appointed by the president with validation by Parliament. He appoints the Prime Minister and the members of the government, who answer politically for their acts before him. In the event of a vacancy due to death, resignation or absolute impediment, he is replaced by the vice-president, until the end of the current mandate, or by the Prime Minister, in the event of the vacancy of the post of vice-president.\r\n\r\nFollowing the death of Amadou Gon Coulibaly on July 8, 2020, the post of Prime Minister is vacant. President Alassane Ouattara appoints Defense Minister Hamed Bakayoko as interim prime minister. After the death of the latter, Patrick Achi was appointed Prime Minister, first by interim on March 8, 2021 and then by right.\r\n\r\nThe resignation of Daniel Kablan Duncan, Vice-Chairman appointed on January 10, 2017, is publicly announced on July 13, 2020, with effect from July 8.', 'The history of Ivory Coast prior to the first contacts with Europeans is almost unknown to the general public. These first contacts remained limited with only a few European missionaries in the 16th century. A Neolithic culture did exist, however, but is poorly known due to a lack of archaeological finds.The settlement of the south is attested from the threshold of our era even if the search for its traces is made difficult by the humid climate. The territory was dotted with peoples of Sudanese languages, divided into numerous chiefdoms.\r\n\r\nAmong the oldest populations, there are the Mandé of the south (Gouro, Gban and Yacouba) in the west and in the center-west, the Krous in the South-West as well as the Sénoufos in the North-East. The north of the country will be under the influence of the Sahelian kingdoms (Songhai, Ghana). It is in this context that Islam will take root, spread either by traders, notably Dioula peddlers, or by jihad led by armies on horseback. Trading towns like Kong or Bondoukou would later become veritable city-states, links between the savannah and the forest. However, the populations were unaware of private property and did not seek to demarcate their territory. Their cultures were marked by a theatrical, oral, musical, dance tradition and belief in magic.', 'uploads/lova13.jpg', 'The culture of Ivory Coast , one of the countries of West Africa, first refers to all the cultural practices and cultures of the many ethnic groups that make up its population estimated at 29,389,150 inhabitants in 2021.The official language is French, also in its French variant from Côte d\'Ivoire. But Ivorians are generally multilingual. The most spoken languages ​​are the Mandinka language (70%), Senufo (Gour language), Baoulé (Akan language), Bété (Krou/Kru language).', 'uploads/download (36).jpg'),
(53, 'Djibouti', 'Djibouti, in long form the Republic of Djibouti (in Arabic: جمهورية جيبوتي, Jībūtī; in Somali: Jabuuti and Jamhuuriyadda Jabuuti; in Afar: Gabuutih Ummuuno) is a state in the Horn of Africa, located on the western coast of the outlet southern Red Sea. It borders Somalia (Somaliland) to the southeast, Ethiopia to the south and west, Eritrea to the north and has, across the Bab-el-Mandeb strait, a maritime border with the Yemen. Its population in 2022 is estimated at around 1 million Djiboutians .', 'djibouti', 'The city of Tadjourah seems to have constituted, fairly early on, one of the rare permanent agglomerations, undoubtedly linked to the sultanate of Ifat, then of Adal between the 13th and 16th centuries. But the territory corresponding to the current Djibouti was mainly constituted over the extension of the French occupation from 1885: Territory of Obock and dependencies until 1896, then French Coast of Somalis (CFS) until in 1967, then French Territory of the Afars and Issas (TFAI), before becoming independent on June 27, 1977, under the name \"Republic of Djibouti\".', ' What is the economy of Djibouti?\r\nIts economy is based on a port complex which is among the most modern in the world. Trade through the port of Djibouti is expected to grow rapidly, alongside the economic expansion of Ethiopia, the country\'s main neighbor and trading partner. The gross domestic product per capita is around 3,200 euros/year (2008 estimate), well above the African average.\r\n\r\nDjibouti\'s economy is largely dependent on its tertiary sector (82% of GDP). The main industrial activity is the port of Djibouti, and now its extension to Doraleh. In 2015, the use of Djiboutian ports by landlocked Ethiopia generated significant resources (80% of Ethiopian imports and exports passed through Djibouti in 2015). The country is poor in industrial (15% of GDP) and especially agricultural (3% of GDP) activities.\r\n\r\nFor its food needs, Djibouti gets its supplies from its neighbors (Ethiopia, Somalia and Yemen) and, for manufactured products, mainly from France.\r\n\r\nThe state is the country\'s main employer, but the country officially has a very high unemployment rate (70% of workers).\r\n\r\nThe rents paid by several countries for the establishment of military bases and, since the beginning of the 21st century, the arrival of American soldiers and the arrival of new banks represent a significant share of GDP.\r\n\r\nThe country also receives international assistance. France provides economic aid to the country and participates in many infrastructures, including the Joseph-Kessel high school in central Djibouti in 1991.\r\n\r\nThe Republic of Djibouti has the only currency board (Currency Board) on the African continent since 1949. The fixed exchange rate of the national currency against the US dollar has not changed since. During its long existence, the performance and uniqueness of this regime have never been questioned.\r\n\r\nThree quarters of Djiboutians live on less than three dollars a day .', 'Djibouti has been a republic since its independence in 1977, it organized its first legislative and presidential elections in 1981. It had a single party until 1992, when a controlled and partial multiparty system was recognized. It follows the “principle” of separation of powers: legislative, executive and judicial. However, the Djiboutian political system is still considered to be very authoritarian and leaves very little room for the civic engagement of citizens.\r\n\r\nThe country has not known any political alternation since its independence. Most of the power is held by the same family: the current president, Ismaïl Omar Guelleh, is the nephew of his predecessor, Hassan Gouled Aptidon. Djibouti has been a republic since its independence in 1977, it organized its first legislative and presidential elections in 1981. It had a single party until 1992, when a controlled and partial multiparty system was recognized.', 'The Djibouti area has been inhabited since at least the Neolithic period. According to some linguists, the first Afro-Asian populations arrived in the region during this period from the family\'s proposed urheimat (\"original homeland\") in the Nile Valley or the Near East, while others researchers propose that the Afro-Asiatic family developed in situ in the Horn, and that its speakers subsequently dispersed.', 'uploads/lova14.jpg', 'The culture of Djibouti, a small country in the Horn of Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 820,000 inhabitants (in 2017). Djiboutians are charming, respectful and very hospitable people, a characteristic that has its origins in the traditional nomadic culture of the two main ethnic groups, the Afars and the Issas. Despite an increasingly sedentary way of life, most Djiboutians living in cities remain strongly attached to their nomadic past.\r\nOne of the most striking elements of life in Djibouti is the ubiquity of qat (a leaf that is chewed for its stimulating power). The existence of most adult men seems to revolve almost entirely around the consumption of this mild narcotic. Every day, they find their circle of friends in dedicated places, the mabraz, to “graze”. It is estimated that only 10% of women regularly consume this plant.\r\nDjibouti has 900,000 inhabitants, of which 35% are Afars and 60% Issas. Both of these groups are Muslim. The rest of the population is made up of Arabs and Europeans. The Issas are the majority in the south of the country and the Afars in the north. Ethnic tensions between the two communities came to a head in 1991, when Afar rebels sparked a civil war in the north. A peace agreement was negotiated in 1994 but resentment has not been completely appeased.', 'uploads/download (37).jpg'),
(54, 'Egypt', 'Egypt Listen (Arabic: مصر / miṣr; Egyptian Arabic: مصر / maṣr masˤɾ), in long form the Arab Republic of Egypt (Arabic: جمهورية مصر العربية?) / jumhuriyat misr al arabiya, is a transcontinental country found in Northeast Africa and, for the Sinai Peninsula, in West Asia. Located on the southern coast of the eastern Mediterranean, the Levantine Basin, the country has land borders with Libya to the west, Sudan to the south, the Red Sea to the east, and Israel and the Gaza Strip to the Palestine to the northeast. The capital, and the most populous city in the country, is Cairo. With more than 102 million inhabitants in 2020, Egypt is the third most populous country in Africa behind Nigeria and Ethiopia. The surface of the country is largely covered by the Sahara and the population is highly concentrated on the coasts of the Nile.', 'egypt', 'Egypt has one of the longest histories of any country. The cradle of civilization, ancient Egypt saw the earliest developments in writing, agriculture, centralized government, and organized religion over more than three millennia BC. AD. Iconic monuments such as the Sphinx of Giza, the Pyramids of Giza and the Valley of the Kings reflect this heritage and remain important sources of scientific and popular interest. During the period of Roman rule, Egypt became one of the first centers of Christianity before being Islamized by the Arab conquests of the seventh century. Egypt remains a predominantly Muslim country with a large Christian minority.\r\n\r\nEgypt is governed as an Ottoman province and conquered by the Ottoman sultan Selim I, the country remains under Ottoman domination between the sixteenth century and the nineteenth century before obtaining autonomy in 1806 under the reign of Mehemet Ali. During World War I, the country briefly became a British protectorate before gaining independence in 1922 as a kingdom. Mehemet Ali\'s dynasty was overthrown by a coup in 1952 and the republic was proclaimed. Since then, the country has experienced a recurring pattern of political instability, religious and social conflicts and dictatorial excesses; several conflicts with Israel took place before the Camp David Accords in 1978.', 'In 2017, Egypt is the 1st economic power on the African continent in terms of GDP PPP and the 3rd if we take the nominal GDP, just behind South Africa and Nigeria. Given the country\'s desert climate, most human and economic activity is concentrated along the Nile. Egypt has a diversified economy, unlike many African countries. Thus, in 2015, 16% of GDP was due to the manufacturing sectors, 12% to the extractive sectors (including the exploitation of natural resources such as oil), 13% to wholesale and retail trade, etc. The government has undertaken reforms for 40 years to reduce the strong centralization inherited from President Gamal Abdel Nasser.\r\n\r\nThe policy of reforms and economic openness undertaken by Egypt between 2006 and 2008 enabled record high growth rates of 7% per annum, and this could probably have continued over a longer period had it not been for the hadn\'t had the subprime crisis. Despite everything, a large part of the population (40%) remained below the poverty line, which led to an unstable political and civil situation and a revolution.', 'On April 2, 2018, President Sisi was re-elected for a four-year term. The approval by referendum, last April, of the revision of the Egyptian Constitution, extends the current mandate of the president until 2024, and authorizes him to run for a third term in the presidential elections of 2024. A constitutional referendum takes place in January 2014.\r\n\r\nThe organization of legislative elections takes place between February and March 2014, as well as the presidential election at the beginning of the summer of the same year, the interim power exercising its prerogatives until then. At the end of 2013, the new military power was in turn the target of protests, in particular because of the repression of demonstrations and the arrest of democratic activists.', 'The history of Egypt is first marked by the invaluable testimonies bequeathed by ancient Egypt, which have fascinated since Antiquity. It is also particularly striking outside of Egypt, among the Jews, in black Africa, in the Hellenistic world, among the Arabs and in Islam, and in Europe. After the Ptolemaic period, Egypt was, for several centuries, only a province of the vast empires that were the Roman Empire, the Byzantine Empire, the Sassanid Empire, the Arab Empire then the Empire Ottoman. It only regained a certain autonomy in the 19th century and its independence in 1922. After authoritarian regimes, it experienced a difficult democratization with the 2011 revolution. Writing ancient history is still relatively difficult as the documentation is fragmentary and incomplete. In particular, the era change dates given below can only be approximate, as opinions differ on this subject.', 'uploads/lova15.jpg', 'Egyptian culture is strongly steeped in local traditions, religion and custom. The Egyptians are rich in a popular culture which was built around a very old civilization but little present in the daily life of the population.\r\n\r\nHere are some explanations about music, dance, literature and cinema in Egypt.', 'uploads/download (38).jpg'),
(55, 'Eritrea', 'Eritrea, in long form the State of Eritrea (in Tigrinya: ኤርትራ, Ertra and ሃገረ ኤርትራ, Hagere Ertra; in Arabic: إرتريا, Iritrīyā and دولة إرتريا, D awlat Iritriya) is a sovereign state located in East Africa East. It is the northernmost country in the Horn of Africa. The country has 1,840 km long land borders with Djibouti to the southeast, Ethiopia to the south and Sudan to the west, to which are added the maritime borders with Saudi Arabia and Yemen, in addition to those with Djibouti and Sudan.', 'eritrea', 'Eritrea is, de jure, a unitary one-party republic but is, de facto, a totalitarian dictatorship. Its capital is Asmara and its official languages ​​are Tigrigna, Arabic and English and as vernacular national languages, Tigrigna, Tigray, Arabic, Afar, Saho, Bilen, Bedja, Kunama and the nara. Its currency has been the Eritrean nakfa since 1997.\r\n\r\nThe first occurrences of the term \"Eritrea\" come from the ancient Greek Ερυθραία / Eruthraía meaning \"red\" and Latinized Erythræa. This term, originally designating all the coasts of the Red Sea, will be given to the current territory in 1890 by King Humbert I of Italy just after having made it an Italian colony.\r\n\r\nEritrea has a history in its own right from the 12th century BC. AD with the kingdom of Sheba; two centuries later, the D\'mt kingdom was established in the center of the current territory over a period of five centuries. It is with the empire of Aksum, from the 1st century BC. J.-C., that the beginnings of an Eritrean territory see the light of day in a territorial space spreading from the south-east of present-day Egypt to present-day Somaliland. The territory was subsequently attached to the Ethiopian Empire until the arrival of the Italians in East Africa. Following the purchase by the Italians of the bay of Assab from the local sultan in 1869, then their occupation of Massawa in 1885, Eritrea was incorporated in 1890 as a special territory. After the Italian defeat during the Second World War, the UN decided in 1952 to federate Eritrea with Ethiopia, which annexed it in 1962.', 'Eritrea has experienced significant economic growth in recent years, with gross domestic product (GDP) increasing by 8.7% in 2011 and 7.5% in 2012. The Economist Intelligence Unit forecasts a growth rate of 8 .5% in 2013.\r\n\r\nRemittances from the diaspora of Eritrean emigrants is the country\'s main source of income. Agriculture provides 11% of gross domestic product.\r\n\r\nEritrea has many natural resources, such as copper, gold, silver, granite, marble, potassium, zinc, salt and iron and some gas and oil sources in its waters. The country exports cattle, meat and gum arabic.', 'Eritrea is a one-party presidential republic, where the President is both head of state and head of government. The Popular Front for Democracy and Justice (FPDJ) alone holds power. Eritrea is a one-party presidential republic, where the President is both head of state and head of government. The Popular Front for Democracy and Justice (FPDJ) alone holds power. The National Assembly, formed in 1993 shortly after independence, has 150 seats and elected President Issayas Afewerki.\r\n\r\nOn May 19, 1993, shortly after the referendum on the independence of the Autonomous Region of Eritrea, held on April 23-24, 1993, the Provisional Government announced a reorganization of government and a four-year transitional period during which a new constitution, a law on political parties, a law on the press as well as the election of a constitutional government would be put in place. In March 1994, the provisional government set up a constituent commission to draft a new constitution. The constitution was promulgated in 1997 but did not materially enter into force and the elections were postponed. A National Assembly composed exclusively of PFDJ members took office as a transitional legislature. Elections were postponed indefinitely after the start of the territorial dispute with Ethiopia.\r\n\r\nUnder the leadership of President Afewerki, Eritrea is considered one of the most brutal dictatorships in the world, as several international reports attest.', 'Eritrea is a country in the Horn of Africa, long an Ethiopian province (it was annexed by Ethiopia in 1962). The country gained its independence from Ethiopia on May 24, 1993, after a long conflict from 1961 to 1991, followed by a new conflict with Ethiopia from 1998 to 2000. Eritrea has been known in history for a very long time. The Eritrean coasts are considered, with those of Somalia and Sudan, as the country called Punt or Ta Netjeru (Land of the Gods) by the inhabitants of ancient Egypt. The first mention dates back to the 25th century BC. The oldest known reference to the sea of ​​Eritrea is attributed to Aeschylus (Fragment 67), who designates it as \"the jewel of Ethiopia\" (Ethiopia then designated the part of Africa located at the southern Egypt).\r\n\r\nAround the eighth century BC. AD, a kingdom known as D\'mt was established in northern Eritrea and Ethiopia, with Yeha as its capital. It is followed by the Kingdom of Aksum, in the 1st century BC. AD, although the continuities remain unclear.\r\n\r\nThe Periplus of the Eritrean Sea, a text from the 2nd century, specifies that there was a trade route in East Africa which linked the Roman world to China1.\r\n\r\nThe peoples of central Eritrea and northern Ethiopia share a common historical and cultural heritage, stemming from the Kingdom of Aksum and subsequent dynasties throughout the 1st millennium BC. BC and the Ge\'ez language. Tigrinya and Amharic, official languages ​​in Eritrea and Ethiopia respectively, are cousin languages ​​of Ge\'ez, the liturgical language of the Ethiopian Monophysite Orthodox Church, as well as of the Church of Eritrea which evolved from it. detached at the independence of the country.', 'uploads/lova16.jpg', 'The culture of Eritrea, a country in the Horn of Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 6,500,000 inhabitants (in 2017). Even if we often speak of \"Eritrean culture\", there is not just one, but several, quite diverse. Officially there are nine ethnic groups, and if you count the Illiit as a separate group, and also think of the \"Tukrir\" or Hausa who live in Keren and Tesseney, there are more. But often we tend to confuse the Habesha culture of the highlands with the culture of Eritrea, since the Habesha are the dominant group in Eritrea. They are mostly Orthodox Christians (see image of the famous monastery of Debre Bizen) and Tigrinya speakers, speaking Tigrinnya like their Ethiopian neighbors in Tigray.', 'uploads/eritra.jpg'),
(56, 'Ethiopia', 'Ethiopia, in long form the Federal Democratic Republic of Ethiopia (in Amharic: ኢትዮጵያ, Ītyōṗṗyā Listen and የኢትዮጵያ ፌዴራላዊ ዲሞክራሲያዊ ሪፐብ ሊክ ye-Ītyōṗṗyā Fēdēralāwī Dīmōkrāsīyāwī Rīpeblīk Listen) is a state in the Horn of Africa. Ethiopia has common borders with Eritrea (former province) to the north, Somalia to the east-southeast, Sudan to the northwest, South Sudan to the west-southwest, Kenya to the south and the Republic of Djibouti to the northeast. Since the independence of Eritrea in 1993, Ethiopia no longer has access to the sea.', 'ethiopie', 'Within Africa, Ethiopia is characterized as one of the countries to have retained its sovereignty during the partition of Africa in the 19th century: as a result, its colors often symbolize Africa and have been adopted by several other African states, in different configurations.\r\n\r\nEthiopia, now constitutionally secular, is a country where many beliefs coexist. After Armenia, it is the second oldest Christian nation in the world, Christianity having been established there around the year 330. Today there are Eastern Orthodox, Catholics and Protestants. In addition, a third of its inhabitants are Muslim and religious minorities such as the Jewish Beta Israel or animists also live there.\r\n\r\nOn the international level, Ethiopia is a signatory of the United Nations declaration since 1942 and becomes one of the 51 founding member states of the UN. Addis Ababa is now the headquarters of the Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) and the African Union.', 'Per capita GDP (USD 995 in 2021) remains constrained by the country\'s strong demographic growth (2.6% on average). The poverty rate (<1.90 USD/day) stood, according to the World Bank (WB) at 30.8% in 2016 and the country is ranked 173rd out of 180 in the 2020 HDI. Ethiopia has an essentially agricultural economy, weakened by droughts, food shortages and political conflicts, however it is currently transiting towards an industrial and exporting economy. Since the 2000s and until 2018, its GDP growth has been one of the highest in the world at around 10% per year (10.9% in 2017). This enabled a good part of the population to escape from extreme poverty, going from 55.5% of the population in 1999 to 26.7% in 2016 (threshold $1.90). It is not a member of the World Trade Organization but a membership procedure was launched in 2003 .', 'Ethiopians currently enjoy the greatest political freedom in their history, but basic freedoms, including freedom of the press, are not yet guaranteed. Zenawi\'s government was re-elected in 2000 in the first multi-party elections. Ethiopia is a federal republic with a parliamentary system where the Prime Minister exercises the function of head of government. Executive power is in the hands of the government while legislative power is shared between the government and the two houses of parliament. The judiciary is more or less independent of the executive and the legislature. The President of the Republic has only a representative role.', 'Independent states have been identified in parts of present-day Ethiopia for nearly 3,000 years. Around the eighth century BC. J.-C., one notes the formation of the D\'mt kingdom, followed by various other entities, without the continuities being always clear: the kingdom of Axum, the zagwe kingdoms. Around 1270, the Solomonic dynasty was established, which would continue in various forms until the Ethiopian Empire, the Provisional Military Government of Socialist Ethiopia, the People\'s Democratic Republic of Ethiopia and the current Democratic Federal Republic of Ethiopia. Considered one of the cradles of humanity, Ethiopia is one of the oldest areas of human settlement. The first traces of hominids date back 3 or 4 million years. The appearance of Homo erectus and Homo sapiens in the region is between 1.7 million years and 200,000 years before our era. Ethiopia, during antiquity, seems to have been part of the country of Punt (3rd millennium BC - 1st millennium BC).\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Aksum stelae with that of Ezana in the center. Unesco World Heritage.\r\nIn the 1st millennium BC. AD, Sabaean populations from Yemen settled in the highlands of Eritrea and Ethiopia and founded several settlements there. The Sabaeans introduced their architecture, their artistic style, their religion and their writing system. Their presence in Ethiopia and Eritrea is reflected in the numerous inscriptions present.', 'uploads/lova18.jpg', 'The culture of Ethiopia, a landlocked country in the Horn of Africa, primarily refers to the observable cultural practices of its 103,000,000 people (2018 estimate).\r\n\r\nEthiopian culture refers to all the cultures of the various peoples of Ethiopia. According to the official 2007 census, 62.8% of Ethiopians are Christian (43.5% Orthodox, 18.6% Protestant and 0.7% Catholic), 33.9% Muslim and 3.3% from traditional religions. Since 1994, Ethiopia has been a constitutionally secular country.', 'uploads/ethio.jpg'),
(57, 'Gabon', 'Gabon, in long form the Gabonese Republic, is a country located in Central Africa, crossed by the equator, bordering the east, southeast and south of the Republic of Congo, north-northwest of Equatorial Guinea and northern Cameroon.', 'gabon', 'What is now Gabon was colonized by France and incorporated into the colony of the French Congo in 1882. The territory became a separate colony in 1906 and gained independence in 1960. Gabon is a republic with a presidential regime. In 1968, the Gabonese Democratic Party (PDG) was declared the only party. Although the multiparty system was introduced in the early 1990s, the PDG still remains the dominant party.\r\n\r\nIt is a forest country where the fauna and flora are still well preserved and protected in thirteen national parks including the Lopé and Ivindo national parks, listed as UNESCO World Heritage Sites.\r\n\r\nA small population, large forest resources and abundant oil have made Gabon one of the most prosperous countries in Africa. The country has the highest human development index in sub-Saharan Africa according to the United Nations, with the second highest per capita income behind Equatorial Guinea and ahead of Botswana. GDP grew by more than 6% per year for the period 2010-2012. However, due to large inequalities in the distribution of income, a significant proportion of the population remains poor.\r\n\r\nThe official language is French. Almost all of the inhabitants are members of the Bantu ethnic groups. Christianity is the most practiced religion.', 'In 2022, the Gabonese economy recorded growth of 3.0% against 1.5% in 2021. This good performance is the result of the good performance of the oil sector (+7.1%) and that of the non-oil sector ( +2.3%). Fourth largest oil producer in sub-Saharan Africa, Gabon has recorded strong economic growth over the past decade, driven in particular by the production of oil and manganese.', 'Gabon has a hybrid regime. It includes both the characteristics of the presidential system and of the so-called parliamentary system. The first president of the Gabonese Republic was Léon Mba in 1960. Omar Bongo became the second president of the Gabonese Republic in 1967, on the death of Léon Mba. He was then, at 32, the youngest head of state in the world. He remained in power from 1967 until his death in 2009.\r\n\r\nBetween 1968 and 1990, the country was under the regime of a single party, the Gabonese Democratic Party (PDG). A national conference was held in March-April 1990. At the end of it, important political reforms were adopted, including the creation of a national senate, the decentralization of finances, freedom of assembly and of the press. , the abolition of the compulsory exit visa and the multi-party system, with the first multi-party legislative elections in almost thirty years in September-October 1990.\r\n\r\nDespite this certain democratization, the country\'s economic situation hardly changed while Omar Bongo and his presidential party remained in power. He died on June 8, 2009, at the age of 73. The interim is ensured by the President of the Senate, Rose Rogombé, until the early election of 2009. Ali Bongo then succeeds his father.', 'The first traces of human occupation in Gabon date back 400,000 years.\r\n\r\nThe first inhabitants of Gabon, Pygmies then Bantu peoples, are known only by oral transmission of information.\r\n\r\nWith the arrival of the Portuguese navigators in the 15th century, we begin to have written testimonies on the coastal populations. For three centuries, the life of the Pongo was punctuated by the slave trade between coastal tribes and European merchants (Portuguese and Dutch, in particular).\r\n\r\nIn the 19th century, France gradually occupied the country, starting from the Komo estuary and the mouth of the Ogooué, following the action of explorers such as Victor de Compiègne, Alfred Marche, Pierre Savorgnan from Brazza.\r\n\r\nGabon was a colony of French Equatorial Africa until its independence in 1960. From 1967 to 2009, it was run by the same president, Omar Bongo, who benefited from the exploitation of the country\'s various natural resources.', 'uploads/lova19.jpg', 'The Niembé (or Njembe, Njembe, or Ndjembe) is a rite practiced in Gabon, exclusively by women. It is a sort of response to the rites of Mwiri and Bwiti, which are reserved for men. These rites are thus the two pendants of the initiation which leads from childhood to adulthood. The culture of Gabon brings together all the cultural practices of the Gabonese people, inherited from the traditional culture of the different ethnic groups that compose it and from modern Western influence.', 'uploads/images (11).jpg'),
(58, 'Gambia', 'The Gambia, in long form the Republic of Gambia (in English: Gambia or The Gambia, and Republic of The Gambia), is a country in West Africa.\r\n\r\nLandlocked in Senegal to the north, south and east, The Gambia is bordered to the west by the Atlantic Ocean. These boundaries correspond to the course and valley of the Gambia River, which flows through the country and empties into the Atlantic Ocean. Its area is 11,300 km2 (it is the continental African country with the smallest area), for a population of just over two million inhabitants (2018 estimate). Banjul is the capital and the biggest cities are Serrekunda and Brikama.', 'gambia', 'The Gambia shares historical roots with other West African countries that experienced the practice of the slave trade. The slave trade is behind the establishment and maintenance of a colony on the Gambia River; first by the Portuguese, when the country was called “A Gâmbia”, and later by the British. In 1965, The Gambia gained independence from the United Kingdom.\r\n\r\nSince the proclamation of the republic in 1970, The Gambia has had three leaders: President Dawda Jawara, who ruled the country from 1970 to 1994 before Yahya Jammeh took power in a coup as a young army officer. On December 1, 2016, Adama Barrow won the presidential election but the outgoing president, Yahya Jammeh, did not recognize his defeat. A delegation from ECOWAS (of which The Gambia is a member state) tried to resolve the situation peacefully, but when negotiations failed, on January 19, 2017, the Senegalese army intervened in The Gambia, following the vote on a United Nations (UN) resolution. On the evening of January 21, 2017, Yahya Jammeh decided, under pressure from the UN and neighboring countries, to leave The Gambia and go into exile in Equatorial Guinea. This decision now allows Adama Barrow to exercise power.\r\n\r\nOn December 6, 2021, Adama Barrow was re-elected President of the Republic of The Gambia.\r\n\r\nThe Gambia\'s economy is dominated by agriculture, fishing and tourism. About a third of the population lives below the international poverty line of $1.25 a day.', 'Economic Situation of The Gambia\r\nThe country is classified among the least developed countries on the socio-economic level, it is the 174th country out of 189 in terms of HDI (2021). Agriculture, forestry and fishing represent 23% of GDP in 2020, industry 20% and services 57% .', 'A presidential election was held in 1996, which retired Colonel Yahya Jammeh won with 56% of the vote. The January 1997 legislative elections were dominated by the Patriotic Alliance for Reorientation and Construction (APRC), which won 33 of the 45 seats to be filled. The ban on parties from the Jawara era was lifted in 2001 and four officially registered opposition parties took part in the presidential election of October 18, 2001, which the outgoing President won with almost 53% of the vote. The APRC retained its large majority in the National Assembly during the legislative elections organized in January 2002, which were marked by the boycott of the United Democratic Party.\r\n\r\nIn 2005, five opposition parties united under the banner of the National Alliance for Democracy and Development, which brought together almost all of the country\'s opposition forces. On September 29, partial elections allowed the ANDD to win 3 of the four seats at stake. On November 15, three ANDD leaders were arrested, including Halifa Sallah, leader of the opposition in the National Assembly. On March 21 and 22, 2006, in a climate of tension preceding the presidential election, a coup d\'etat was reportedly foiled. The President returned prematurely from a trip to Mauritania, many army officials were arrested while others fled the country. The circumstances of this attempt have not been elucidated – it has been suggested that it was the President himself who orchestrated a set-up.', '\r\nThe Gambia gained independence in 1965 as a Commonwealth realm. In 1970, the republic was proclaimed and Dawda Jawara became its first president. The Gambia was united with Senegal from 1982 to 1989 in a confederation: the Confederation of Senegambia. At its height, in the fourteenth century, the Mali Empire extended as far as The Gambia.\r\n\r\nIn 1455, the Portuguese set up counters along the Gambia River from which they organized the slave trade. In 1723, the British Africa Company purchased land in The Gambia.\r\n\r\nFrom the 18th century, the British occupied this small landlocked territory in Senegal (with the exception of a French enclave in Albreda, ceded to the British by an agreement in 1857). Following a Franco-British treaty in 1889, the country officially became a British protectorate in 1894.\r\n\r\nThe Gambia gained independence in 1965 as a Commonwealth realm. In 1970, the republic was proclaimed and Dawda Jawara became its first president. The Gambia was united with Senegal from 1982 to 1989 in a confederation: the Confederation of Senegambia.\r\n\r\nOn July 22, 1994 a group of officers, led by Captain Yahya Jammeh, overthrew the government. In 1996, pressed by the international community, donors having suspended all aid since the 1994 coup, President Jammeh agreed to initiate a process of democratization which would bring him back to power in the 1996 elections. , October 18, 2001 and September 22, 2006.\r\n\r\nOn January 19, 2017, Adama Barrow becomes the new president of Gambia by taking the oath at the Gambian Embassy in Senegal.', 'uploads/lova20.jpg', 'The culture of The Gambia, a country in West Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 2,000,000 inhabitants.', 'uploads/download (39).jpg'),
(59, 'Ghana', 'Ghana is located on the Gulf of Guinea, just north of the equator. It shares borders with Ivory Coast to the west, Togo to the east and Burkina Faso to the north.', 'ghana', 'Ghana, in long form the Republic of Ghana (in English: Republic of Ghana), is a country in West Africa located on the shores of the Gulf of Guinea.\r\n\r\nThe neighboring countries of Ghana are Côte d\'Ivoire to the west, Burkina Faso to the north and Togo to the east. Its capital is the city of Accra and its inhabitants are Ghanaians. The country is part of ECOWAS.\r\n\r\nThe official language is English and the currency is Cedi. Ghana has been an associate member of the International Organization of La Francophonie since 2006 and gives an ever more important place to French.', 'Real GDP growth has slowed from 5.4% in 2021 to 3.3% in 2022, due to macroeconomic instability, global financial tightening and the effects of Ukraine\'s invasion by Russia. Ghana is a country rich in raw materials. Its economy is mainly agricultural but the service sector has developed a lot since the beginning of 2011.', 'Ghana is a presidential republic in which the president serves as both head of state and head of government. The government exercises the executive power while the legislative power is shared between the parliament (mono-cameral system) and the government. The Constitution of Ghana, which ushers in the Fourth Republic, lays the foundations for a democratic republican state, declaring Ghana a united republic whose sovereignty rests with the people. The sharing of power between the president, the parliament, the government as well as an independent judiciary, must contribute to avoiding coups d\'etat, the seizure of power by a dictatorial government or by a single party. The current constitution, which succeeds those of 1957, 1960, 1969 and 1979, is partly inspired by provisions and institutions from the British and American constitutions. A controversial provision ensures immunity for PNDC members for any act or omission during the years the PNDC was in power.', 'Ghana is named after the empire existing in the Middle Ages in West Africa, the Empire of Ghana. This Empire was itself referred to in Europe and Arabia as the Empire of Ghana, after the title of its emperor, Ghana. The Empire seems to have been broken in 1076 following the conquest of the Almoravid general Abu Bakr Ibn Omar. A kingdom continued to exist after the end of the Almoravid dictatorship, and the kingdom was later incorporated into Sahelian empires, such as the Mali Empire.\r\n\r\nMuch of the area was unified under the Ashanti Empire in the 16th century. Ashanti governments operate first as a loose network and then gradually establish a centralized bureaucracy, with Kumasi as the capital. The colonial powers were attracted to this territory for the gold trade and then the slave trade. This country gained independence in 1957.', 'uploads/lova21.jpg', 'Ghana, former Gold Coast, has a long tradition of working gold (weapons, masks, canopies, command staffs, jewelry, etc.). Copper objects, such as weights for weighing gold, scales, spoons and boxes used to store gold powder, are related to goldsmithing. The culture of Ghana, a West African country, is the set of cultural practices of its thirty million inhabitants and its diaspora.', 'uploads/ghana.jpg');
