(60, 'Guinea', 'Guinea Listen, in long form the Republic of Guinea, sometimes called Guinea Conakry from the name of its capital and main city, is a West African country of nearly 14 million inhabitants (2021). Rich in natural resources, it is nicknamed the water tower of West Africa and has a third of the world\'s bauxite reserves, which has earned it regular association with \"geological scandals\". It gained its independence from France on October 2, 1958, making it the first country in French sub-Saharan Africa to do so.', 'guinea', 'Guinea is a republic. Its president, directly elected by the people, is head of state and appoints a prime minister who is head of government. The unicameral National Assembly is the country\'s legislative body and its members are also directly elected by the people. The judiciary is dominated by the Supreme Court of Guinea, the country\'s highest court of appeal.\r\n\r\nGuinea is a predominantly Muslim country, with 85% of the population. The Guinean population is divided into several ethnic groups. French, the official language of Guinea, is the main language of communication in schools, public administration and the media. But more than 24 national languages, including Poular, Malinké, Soussou, Guerzè, Toma and Kissi are widely spoken as languages ​​of more common exchanges between populations.\r\n\r\nThe Guinean economy is largely dependent on agriculture and mining production. As of 2014, it is the world\'s sixth largest producer of bauxite and has reserves of diamonds and gold.\r\n\r\nIn 2011, the United States government asserted that acts of torture by security forces and the abuse of women and children (for example, female genital mutilation) constituted human rights abuses in Guinea. In 2014, the country was hit by the Ebola epidemic.', 'With a population of 14.7m and a GDP of USD 20.5bn in 2022 according to the IMF, Guinea is at the bottom of the HDI ranking, ranking 182nd out of 191 countries in 2021. Guinean growth should continue to progress in 2023. This new acceleration will still be mainly due to mining, particularly gold, which represents 50% of exports, and bauxite (44%). These mineral exports (60% of GDP in 2021) will be driven by their increased production.', 'Guinea is a republic with a presidential regime in which the President of the Republic, Head of State, appoints a Prime Minister, Head of Government. Executive power is in the hands of the government while legislative power is shared between the government and the National Assembly.In power since 2010, President Alpha Condé was overthrown by a military coup led by Colonel Mamady Doumbouya, head of the special forces group, on September 5, 2021. France, like the European Union, has strongly condemned the Coup d\'Etat.', 'It gained independence from France on October 2, 1958, making it the first country in French sub-Saharan Africa to do so. 13,885,724 inhab. Guinea is a republic. Its president, directly elected by the people, is head of state and appoints a prime minister who is head of government. This article deals with the history of the territory of the Republic of Guinea whose current geographical borders were drawn by the colonial powers at the end of the 19th century and in the 20th century. Previously, the history of this territory was marked by the rise, influence and decline of successive kingdoms and great empires.', 'uploads/lova22.jpg', 'The culture of Guinea, a country in West Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 13,000,000 inhabitants (2018 estimate). The diversity and complementarity of its natural ecosystems, the mixing of populations originally having different social and cultural activities and practices and a unique political history explain the exceptional richness of Guinean culture.', 'uploads/download (40).jpg'),
(61, 'Equqtorial Guinea', 'Equatorial Guinea or Guinea-Equatorial, in long form the Republic of Equatorial Guinea or Republic of Equatorial Guinea (in Spanish Guinea Ecuatorial and República de Guinea Ecuatorial, in Portuguese Guiné Equatorial and República da Guiné Equatorial) is a country in Central Africa . It is made up of two parts, one continental, bordered by Cameroon and Gabon, the other island with the island of Bioko (where the capital Malabo is located) and the island of Annobón.', 'equatorial-guinea', 'A former Spanish colony during the European colonization of Africa, Equatorial Guinea gained its independence in 1968 under the bloody dictatorship of President for life, Francisco Macías Nguema. Since his overthrow in a coup in 1979, the country\'s president has been his nephew Teodoro Obiang Nguema Mbasogo. Under its own dictatorship, Equatorial Guinea continues to experience serious human rights violations.\r\n\r\nSince the 1990s, Equatorial Guinea has become an important oil-producing country in sub-Saharan Africa. But its production has been declining since 2016 and will only reach 93,000 barrels per day in 2021, according to OPEC.\r\n\r\nIt is the fourth country in terms of GDP per capita in sub-Saharan Africa, but few people have benefited from the wealth from oil, and inequalities remain very significant.', 'Equatorial Guinea\'s economy, once dependent on commodities such as cocoa and coffee, is now characterized by a high oil rent, the country being the sixth largest producer of black gold in sub-Saharan Africa.\r\n\r\nThe commissioning of the offshore hydrocarbon deposits of Zafiro and Alba in 1996 (to which that of Ceiba was added in 2000) led to a phase of economic expansion allowing Equatorial Guinea\'s GDP to increase on average by 45% each year until the global economic crisis of 2008. However, the latter only benefited a small elite and not the overwhelming majority of the population (76.8% of them living under the national poverty line in 2006), the country being the most unequal in the world with a Gini coefficient of 65.\r\n\r\nIn addition, the fall in the price of oil between 2014 and 2016 led to a major recession in the economy of Equatorial Guinea, whose GDP was almost halved during this period. Despite the downward trend in hydrocarbon production, the rise in oil prices has led to a marked improvement in the situation of public finances: the budget surplus reached 4.7% in 2022, it should remain positive at 3.3% in 2023 and 1.7% in 2024.', 'Equatorial Guinea has been a multi-party state since 1991, where the Democratic Party of Equatorial Guinea holds power. Other minor formations are authorized, but on the condition of recognizing the sole authority of the PDGE. Equatorial Guinea is a republic with a presidential regime where the President of the Republic is the Head of State and the Prime Minister is the Head of Government. The President of the Republic is elected by universal suffrage for a seven-year term. The 1982 constitution grants him broad powers; he can thus appoint and dismiss ministers, modify laws or introduce new ones by decree and dissolve parliament.\r\n\r\nThe Prime Minister is appointed by the President of the Republic. It coordinates government activities, except in the areas of foreign affairs, national defense and security.', 'Around 1493, John II the Perfect, King of Portugal, proclaimed himself Lord of Guinea and Lord of Corisco. The Portuguese begin to colonize the islands of Bioko (then called Fernando Póo, named after its discoverer), Pagalu (then called Annobón) and Corisco; they serve as counters for the slave trade. The history of Equatorial Guinea before colonization is poorly known. The existence of political entities, such as the kingdom of Oyo and the city-states of the Fang clans on the mainland, the Benga kingdom on the island of Corisco, and the Bubi kingdom on the island of Bioko, is however attested. Portuguese navigators were the first Europeans to explore the Gulf of Guinea, in 1471. It was on this date that Fernando Póo noted the location of the island of Bioko, while he was looking for the route to India. Around 1493, John II the Perfect, King of Portugal, proclaimed himself Lord of Guinea and Lord of Corisco. The Portuguese begin to colonize the islands of Bioko (then called Fernando Póo, named after its discoverer), Pagalu (then called Annobón) and Corisco; they serve as counters for the slave trade.\r\n\r\nIn 1641, the Dutch East India Company settled without the agreement of Portugal on the island of Bioko, and made it the center of the slave trade in the Gulf of Guinea; the Portuguese did not appear again on the island until 1648, and replaced the Dutch company with the Company of Corisco, which devoted itself to the same activities. They build one of the first European buildings on the island, the fort of Punta Joko. Portugal, which supplied itself with certain coastal kingdoms already practicing slavery, resold slaves to France, Spain and England.\r\n\r\nThe islands remained in Portuguese hands until March 1778, when they were ceded to Spain in the Treaty of El Pardo. Spain also obtains on this occasion the rights of free trade on the side of the Gulf of Guinea between Niger and Ogooué, in exchange for the colony of Sacramento. Equatorial Guinea was then part of the Viceroyalty of La Plata, until it disappeared with American independence in 1810.', 'uploads/lova23.jpg', 'Christians, especially Catholics (80-87%), and Protestants (5%) are the vast majority (>90%). Minority religions are Islam (2%), Bahaism... Animism concerns 5 to 10% of the population. The culture of Equatorial Guinea, a small country in Central Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 1,403,000 inhabitants (in 2020). Equatorial Guinea was created from three former Spanish colonies: Río Muni, a strip of land between Cameroon and Gabon Bioko, an island close to Cameroon, and Annobón, an island in the Atlantic Ocean far from the mainland.\r\n\r\nEquatorial Guinea\'s national anthem was written by Atanasio Ndongo Miyone and was officially adopted in 1968, when the country gained independence from Spain.', 'uploads/download (41).jpg'),
(62, 'Guinea-Bissau', 'Guinea-Bissau or Guinea-Bissao, in long form the Republic of Guinea-Bissau (in Portuguese: Guiné-Bissau and República da Guiné-Bissau), is a Portuguese-speaking country in West Africa. Its capital is Bissau. The country is part of the Economic Community of West African States and the Organization of Islamic Cooperation.', 'guina-bissau', 'Guinea-Bissau, officially called the Republic of Guinea-Bissau (or República da Guiné-Bissau) is a country in West Africa bathed by the Atlantic Ocean, bordered to the north by Senegal, to the east and south by Guinea-Conakry (or Guinea), i.e. French-speaking states. Due to its geographical location, Guinea-Bissau is therefore landlocked in French-speaking Africa, between Guinea-Conakry and Senegal.\r\nGuinea-Bissau owes its name to its capital, Bissau, and extends over 36,125 km² (which is barely larger than Belgium), including some sixty islands in the Atlantic, including the archipelago of the Bissagos.\r\n\r\nGuinea-Bissau is one of the five countries in Africa that use Portuguese as an official language, which in this case corresponds to a second language for the inhabitants of these countries: Angola, Mozambique, the Cape Verde Islands and the islands of São Tomé and Príncipe.', 'Guinea-Bissau suffers from political instability. On February 2, 2022, a failed coup attempt at the government palace in Bissau. Structurally, the country has one of the lowest tax pressure rates in the WAEMU zone, around 10% of GDP against a community target of 20% of GDP. The low revenues are mainly used to finance current expenditure (70% of total expenditure) including more than 40% of the latter for the salaries of civil servants; while the country remains highly dependent on ODA to finance investment expenditure. However, after standing at 9.6% of GDP in 2020, the budget deficit narrowed to reach 5.8% of GDP in 2022 (against 5.9% in 2021) mainly due to the reduction in investment spending (from 9.4% of GDP in 2021 to 6.0% of GDP in 2022).', 'Guinea-Bissau suffers from political instability. On February 2, 2022, a failed coup attempt at the government palace in Bissau. Guinea-Bissau, currently in a period of transition, is a semi-presidential representative multi-party republic. The President of the Republic is the Head of State, the Prime Minister is the Head of Government. Executive power is exercised by the government while legislative power is shared between the government and the National People\'s Assembly. The judiciary is independent of the executive and the legislature. The African Party for the Independence of Guinea and Cape Verde (PAIGC) and the Social Renewal Party (PRN), socialists, have been in power since 1994.\r\n\r\nThe country has experienced great instability since its independence and coups have multiplied in a country that has become a hub for drug trafficking.', 'The territory where present-day Guinea-Bissau (Guinea-Bissao, Guinea) is located has been occupied since the Neolithic period. Until the end of the first millennium various groups arrive, integrate and little by little create small feudal nations, with varied political organizations, which constantly exchange and mingle (by conflict, especially by marriage, by trade, by adventure, etc.). At least 3000 years ago, the coastal peoples invented wet rice cultivation along the rivers, then rice cultivation on mangroves. The inland nations weave a trade network to the North, South and East. The Baïnouks kingdom, whose southern part encompasses a large part of this territory, is the largest and the oldest centralized country.\r\n', 'uploads/lova24.jpg', 'The culture of Guinea-Bissau, a small country in West Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 1,700,000 Bissau-Guinean inhabitants (in 2017).\r\n\r\nGuinea-Bissau has about thirty ethnic groups speaking as many languages ​​and practicing various religions, most of them animists. The Muslim religion is the most widespread, followed by the animist religions of the majority ethnic groups. The towns have a certain percentage of Catholics and Protestants.', 'uploads/download (42).jpg'),
(63, 'Kenya', 'Kenya, in long form the Republic of Kenya (in Swahili: Kenya and Jamhuri ya Kenya, in English: Kenya and Republic of Kenya), is a country in East Africa.\r\n\r\nIt borders South Sudan to the northwest, Ethiopia to the north, Somalia to the east, Uganda to the west, and Tanzania to the south-southwest. It is bathed by the Indian Ocean to the southeast.', 'kenya', 'Its name comes from that of its highest peak, Mount Kenya, which the Kamba call Kiinyaa, which means “ostrich mountain”. This last name refers to the color of the peaks, which are white with snow and black with rocks, resembling the plumage of the male.\r\n\r\n Kenya is a country in East Africa, crossed by the equator, with a population of 46,000,000. It takes its name from its highest peak, Mount Kenya or Kirinyaga. Its largest watercourse is a river, the Tana River, which flows west to east from Mount Kenya to the Indian Ocean.\r\n\r\nIts capital is Nairobi, the most populous city in the country. Its official currency is the Kenyan shilling. The official languages ​​are English and Swahili..The current spelling derives from a series of evolutions since Johann Ludwig Krapf observed it in 1849. Twisting the word Kiinyaa, he gave it the name Kegnia ([ˈkiːnjə] in phonetic pronunciation in English).', 'First economy in the East African Community (EAC), with a GDP of USD 116.0 billion in 2022, or USD 2,277.7 per capita (compared to (USD 2,215.8 in 2021), Kenya has was the first EAC country classified as middle income (joined in 2020 by Tanzania) . Kenya is, according to the World Bank, a lower middle income country, the only one in East Africa, the others being poorer. First economy in the East African Community (EAC), with a GDP of USD 116.0 billion in 2022, or USD 2,277.7 per capita (compared to (USD 2,215.8 in 2021), Kenya has was the first EAC country classified as middle-income (joined in 2020 by Tanzania) Since 1993, Kenya has experienced a fairly high continuous growth phase (around 5%), with all the same some variances which are linked to its excessive dependence vis-à-vis the outside world, for example, in 2007, its GDP growth rate was 6.8% then in 2008, it was only 0.2%.\r\n\r\nIn April 2022, the Kenyan Ministry of Finance presented a 2022-2023 budget of $28 billion. This budget contains a plan to help revive growth after the crisis linked to the Covid-19 pandemic. The Kenyan economy grew by 7.6% in 2021, after emerging from the crisis against a decline of 0.3% in 2020, with the loss of 700,000 jobs in the Kenyan economy, mainly in the tourism sector . The government growth forecast for 2022 is 6%. This plan (to the tune of 1.3 billion dollars), which comes a few months before the presidential election, also aims to create new large-scale infrastructures partly financed by China.', 'In Kenya, the president is both head of state and head of government. The Constitution plays a key role, since it is what governs the institutional and political actions of the President. It is the Kenyan people who elect their president for a five-year term, renewable only once. In order to win the elections, a candidate must meet two conditions:\r\n\r\nhave an absolute majority,\r\nObtain 25% of the votes in at least half of the counties of the country,\r\nAs a member state of the United Nations and the African Union, Kenya has ratified several human rights conventions. The latter therefore oblige the country to respect certain obligations in terms of respect for human rights. This guarantees a number of individual freedoms and fundamental rights. Among them, we can cite the fight against all forms of discrimination, the prohibition of the use of torture, the protection of children and people with disabilities, etc.', 'The first men who walked the land of Kenya date back several million years. Fossils of hominids dating back more than 2.5 million years have been discovered on the lands of East Africa. Kenya\'s history dates back to the earliest hominids.\r\n\r\nThe first inhabitants are hunter-gatherers, supplanted from the 3rd millennium BC. AD by breeders of Cushitic languages ​​from the north. Around 700 AD. AD arrive populations speaking Nilotic languages. At the end of the 1st millennium, Bantu peoples migrated from Central Africa to the region. From 1500 arrive other Nilotic peoples from Sudan.\r\n\r\nKenya was briefly a German protectorate before becoming a British protectorate and then an English colony in 1890. The country has been independent since December 12, 1963.', 'uploads/lova25.jpg', 'The culture of Kenya, an East African country, primarily refers to the observable cultural practices of its people (42,000,000, 2017 estimate). Ethnic Groups in Kenya, Demographics of Kenya\r\nKikuyu (17.1%), Luhya (14.3%), Kalenjin (13.4%), Luo (10.7%), Kamba (9.8%), Somali (5.8%), Kisii (5.7%), Mijikenda (5.2%), Meru ( 4.2%), Maasai (2.5%), Turkana (2.1%), non-Kenyan (1%), other (8.2%) (2019 est.)\r\n.In Kenya, the culture is marked by millennial traditions. Some of the major tribes in Kenya include the Luo, Kikuyu, Luhya and of course the Maasai. Living in Kenya and Tanzania, the Maasai live mainly in central and southwestern Kenya, especially around the Rift Valley. Kenya is also an incredible diversity of landscapes, between lakes and volcanoes. Listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, Kilimanjaro reveals extraordinary landscapes. The stratovolcano is located in Tanzania, but some of its most beautiful scenery is across the border in Kenya.', 'uploads/download (43).jpg'),
(64, 'Lesotho', 'Lesotho (in long form the Kingdom of Lesotho, in South Sotho Muso oa Lesotho and in English Kingdom of Lesotho) is a state in southern Africa, mountainous and landlocked, entirely landlocked in the territory of South Africa. of the South, on which it is economically dependent. A former British protectorate (Basutoland), the country gained independence in 1966. Today it is a constitutional monarchy whose sovereign is Letsie III. Its capital and only major city is Maseru. Lesotho has about two million inhabitants. The Sothos — who gave their name to the country — are in the majority there. Most are Christians. The two official languages ​​are English and Southern Sotho.', 'lesotho', 'Lesotho (short form) or the Kingdom of Lesotho (long form; in Sesotho: Muso oa Lesotho), is a small country with an area of ​​30,355 km2 (equivalent to Belgium) located in southern Africa entirely landlocked in the South Africa. Lesotho became independent from the United Kingdom in 1966. The capital, which is also the most important city of Lesotho, is Maseru. Its official language is Sesotho but English remains widely spoken. It is a poor country but since 2000 significant economic growth has been observed. The country is crossed by the Drakensberg whose highest point, the Thabana Ntlenyana, is also that of Lesotho. The country\'s only border country is South Africa, with which it shares 909 km of land border.', 'Lesotho is a small economy (landlocked in South African territory) of 2 million inhabitants for a GDP of 2.1 billion USD in 2020. The GDP per capita amounts to just over 1,000 USD. Lesotho is a country located in southern Africa with an area of ​​30,360 km2(1). It is a state made up of 70% mountainous territory, completely surrounded by South Africa (2). According to 2018 estimates, this tiny African nation is home to 2,039,000 people (3). In 2018, the Human Development Index (HDI) ranks Lesotho 164th out of 189 countries (4). This can be explained by still-present inequalities as well as by an economy focused on the primary sector.', '\r\nThe last elections were held in October 2022, and allowed a smooth democratic alternation. Businessman Sam Matekane and his Revolution for Prosperity (RFP) party succeed Prime Minister Majoro.\r\n\r\nSam Matekane\'s priorities are the fight against corruption and economic stability, in order to improve attractiveness and reduce public debt and unemployment.\r\n\r\nHowever, the political situation remains fragile in Lesotho. The balance of coalitions remains an important subject. The proliferation of parties – sixty registered to date – blurs the political landscape. The European Union is a major player in terms of cooperation in Lesotho. It has representation there and maintains cooperation actions in the water, sanitation, energy and governance sectors. Funded via the NDICI, the European Union (EU) multi-annual indicative program (MIP) in Lesotho (2021-2027) amounts to €83 million for 2021-2024. Lesotho has benefited, as a SADC Member State, from EU funding, as well as from the EU-SADC Economic Partnership Agreement (EPA) since 2016. The EU maintains an annual political dialogue with the Lesotho, under Article 8 of the Cotonou Agreement, the last session of which was held on March 24, 2022 in Maseru. At the invitation of Lesotho, the European Union has deployed its first Election Observation Mission (EOM) to the country, to carry out an independent and impartial assessment of all aspects of the electoral process of the National Assembly elections of October 7.', 'Lesotho\'s history began with the San, hunter-gatherers who lived self-sufficiently for thousands of years in this mountainous region of southern Africa in the heart of South Africa. In the 16th century, the Sothos settled in the territory and replaced the San, or at least influenced their way of life. The first difficulty, in the history of southern Africa, is in the choice of names used to designate the populations: the terms used in the 20th century were often those of the colonizers of European origin. The French term \'Bochimans\', for example, is derived from the word used by Dutch settlers \'bosjesman\', and literally meaning \'men of the bushes\', \'men of the bush\' or \'men of the bush\'. English settlers used the literal translation \"Bushmen\". These Bushmen, hunter-gatherers, were opposed to populations, arriving from more northern countries, with a more pastoral way of life, devoting themselves to animal husbandry, agriculture and mastering the work of iron and having a more hierarchical social structure. At the end of the 20th century and the beginning of the 21st century, a distance was taken both from the vocabulary of settlers of European origin. Several terms are used but the hunter-gatherers initially settled are often referred to as San people. The San of the mountains lived in self-sufficiency for thousands of years. But in the 17th century, the Sothos who had arrived in southern Africa some five centuries earlier began to colonize the central Drakensberg mountains.', 'uploads/lova26.jpg', 'Lesotho (formerly known as Basutoland) is a country in the southern region of the African continent. With a size of around 11,583 square miles and a population of around two million, the country has a diverse culture and history. The name of the country means land where people speak Sesotho. The culture and traditions of the country in areas such as daily life, sports, clothing and others are quite unique. Here are some of the most important aspects of Lesotho culture.', 'uploads/download (44).jpg'),
(65, 'Liberia', 'Liberia, in long form the Republic of Liberia, is a country in West Africa bordered to the south-southeast and west-southwest by the Atlantic Ocean, to the northwest by the Sierra Leone, to the north by Guinea and to the east by Ivory Coast', 'liberia', 'In 1822, the American Colonization Society began to colonize the territory, under the assumption that black people would have a better chance at freedom and prosperity in Africa than in the United States. The country declared its independence in 1847, recognized by the United States in 1862, and is therefore the first nation in Africa to have, in contemporary times, obtained its independence. Between 1822 and the start of the Civil War in 1861, thousands of African-Americans and Afro-Caribbeans, former slaves and free-born settled there. The new settlers are developing their own Americo-Liberian culture and have not had good relations with the indigenous peoples. The Americo-Liberians became a small elite, and dominated the political life of the country for several decades as leaders of the dominant party, the True Whig while disfavoring the indigenous peoples. A coup in 1980 put an end to American-Liberian domination and marked the seizure of power by Samuel Doe, the first indigenous president. Establishing a dictatorial regime, he was assassinated in 1990 in the context of the first Liberian civil war which had broken out in 1989 and lasted until 1997 with the election of rebel leader Charles Taylor as president. In 1999, the second Liberian civil war broke out against its own dictatorship, and Taylor was overthrown at the end of the war in 2003. Since then, the country has been relatively stable and democratic, although the country\'s economy is still devastated by two civil wars.\r\n\r\nThe country, which is among the twenty least developed countries in the world with a human development index of 0.481 in 2021, is part of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS).', 'Despite the end of the Ebola virus disease epidemic, officially recognized by the World Health Organization (WHO) in June 2016, economic activity is struggling to rebound. The fall in the prices of exported raw materials (iron ore in particular) represents a greater shock than initially expected due to the fall in production volumes. To a lesser extent, the gradual dismantling of the UN peacekeeping mission (UNMIL) weighed on activity, particularly on the services sector. Liberia entered recession in 2016 (-1.6%) after two years of sluggish growth (0.7% in 2014 and 0% in 2015). In 2018, growth was modest (1.2%), followed by two years of recession (-2.5% in 2019 and -3% in 2020 in the context of the Covid-19 pandemic).\r\n\r\nThe country was supported by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) through a program backed by an extended credit facility. Liberia\'s macroeconomic difficulties disrupted the conduct of the program (several performance criteria were not met). The implementation of corrective measures, however, enabled the adoption of the 7th and 8th reviews and the completion of the program at the end of 2017. Liberia concluded in 2019 a new agreement with the IMF for the implementation of a reform program aimed, among other things, at improving governance (program accompanied by an extended credit facility of USD 213.6 million over 4 years).', 'George Weah (Coalition for Democratic Change – CDC) was elected President of the Republic in the second round of the presidential election on December 26, 2017, with more than 61.5% of the vote, against the current Vice-President, Joseph Boakai . The first round of October 10, in which Weah came first with 38.4% of the vote, had led to a long legal procedure (appeal for annulment, finally rejected by the Supreme Court). The electoral observation missions (African Union, European Union, Economic Community of West African States - ECOWAS) deemed the electoral process fair. Like his predecessor, President Ellen Johnson Sirleaf, President Weah wishes to establish close ties with his neighbors (Côte d\'Ivoire in particular) in order to promote regional integration and promote economic exchanges. Liberia also wishes to join the International Organization of La Francophonie (OIF).\r\n\r\nGeorge Weah also wishes to diversify his partners economically. He thus chose France to make his first trip outside the African continent in February 2018. The United States, however, remains Liberia\'s first partner, in particular for historical reasons.\r\n\r\nChina is a leading partner on the economic side, particularly in the infrastructure sector (renovation of the parliament, airport, etc.). George Weah made an official visit to Beijing in September 2018 on the occasion of the China-Africa Summit (FOCAC).', 'Liberia\'s history as a country begins in 1847, when it became officially independent from the American Colonization Society, which settled freed black slaves near Cape Mesurado. Quickly, a malaise between Americo-Liberians and the indigenous population appears. .Liberia was originally a colony created in 1822 by an American philanthropic society with the objective of welcoming freed slaves and spreading Christianity on the African continent. This colony became an independent state in 1847. The first contact with the indigenous populations was established in 1461 by Portuguese explorers who designated the country as Costa da Pimenta. In 1602 the Dutch created a trading post at Grand Cape Mount, destroyed the following year2. It was in 1663 that the English set up a trading post.', 'uploads/lova27.jpg', 'The culture of Liberia, a small country in West Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 4,500,000 inhabitants, as of 2017. Identification. Liberia lies on the west coast of Africa. The name comes from the English word \"liberty\" and refers to the nation\'s origin as a colony of free blacks repatriated to Africa from the United States in the early nineteenth century. Although the settlers and their descendants, known as Americo-Liberians, defined the boundaries of the nation-state, made English the official language, and dominated the government and economy for almost one hundred fifty years, they have never constituted as much as 5 percent of the population. The remaining people belong to sixteen broadly defined ethnolinguistic groups of the Niger-Congo family. The Mel (West Atlantic) group consists of the Gola and Kissi, who are believed to be the oldest inhabitants. The Mande group, made up of Mandingo, Vai, Gbandi, Kpelle, Loma, Mende, Gio, and Mano peoples, is believed to have entered the area from the northern savannahs in the fifteenth century. The southern and eastern areas are inhabited by people who speak Kruan (Kwa) languages; the Bassa, Dei (Dey), Grebo, Kru, Belle (Kuwaa), Krahn, and Gbee are linguistically related to the peoples of the Niger delta far to the east.', 'uploads/KrahnMask.jpg'),
(66, 'Libia', 'Libya (in Arabic: ليبيا, Libya; in Berber: ⵍⵉⴱⵢⴰ, Libya), in long form the State of Libya (in Arabic: دولة ليبيا, Dawlat Libya; in Berber: ⴰⵡⴰⵏⴽ ⵏ ⵍⵉⴱⵢ ⴰ, Awaikn Libya), is a state from North Africa which is part of the Maghreb. It is bordered to the north by the Libyan Sea in the Mediterranean Sea, to the northwest by Tunisia, to the west by Algeria, to the southwest by Niger, to the south-southeast by Chad, to the southeast by Sudan and east by Egypt. It extends over 1,759,540 km2, which places it fourth in Africa and eighteenth in the world. Its population is estimated between 6 and 8 million inhabitants. It is concentrated on the coasts, the interior of the country being desert. Its capital, Tripoli, is also its largest agglomeration (1.8 million inhabitants), ahead of Benghazi (650,000 inhabitants), Misrata (over 350,000 inhabitants6) and El Beïda (250,000 inhabitants).', 'libia', 'The majority of Libyans are of Arab culture and Sunni Muslim faith. Libya\'s gross domestic product is one of the highest in Africa. Its economy is largely based on the export of oil. It is a member, among others, of the Arab League, the Arab Maghreb Union and the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).\r\n\r\nLibya takes its name from an Amazigh tribe which was named Libou, which gave the ancient Greek word Λιβύη / Libyè. Traditionally, the regions of Tripolitania, Cyrenaica and Fezzan are distinguished. Originally populated by Berbers, its territory was colonized during Antiquity by the Phoenicians, then the Greeks, before being conquered by the Roman Empire. In the 7th century, it was conquered by Arab armies, who spread their culture and religion there. After being subject to various kingdoms during the Middle Ages, it came under the control of the Ottoman Empire in the 16th century. The regency of Tripoli became a real state before being directly taken over by the Ottoman Empire in 1835.', 'Libya\'s economy depends mainly on revenues from the oil sector, which make up almost all of its exports. Industry and agriculture are limited, with agricultural activity suffering above all from the nature of the country\'s soils, which are 94% desert.\r\n\r\nOil revenues coupled with a small population have allowed Libya to have the highest GDP per capita on the African continent. From the year 2000, we witness a surge in the price of Brent, which pulls Libyan growth upwards (over the period 2003-2008, the GDP is multiplied by 3). In 2009, with the fall in oil prices linked to the recession that is hitting the whole world, Libyan GDP fell from 87 billion to 63 billion US$, it rose slightly the following year, but the Arab Spring and the two wars Successive civil wars in 2011 completely disrupted the economy of the country, whose various rival factions are fighting over oil resources. That same year, the GDP fell to 34 billion US$. Nowadays, the country is still far from having regained its pre-crisis economy, indeed the GDP amounted in 2017 to 51 billion US$.', 'Libya has been striving since 2011 to develop good neighborly relations. Libyan officials (GUN) are increasing visits to countries in the region to obtain political support and develop economic relations in the context of internal polarization in the country.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe international community is mobilized to reach a political solution under the auspices of the United Nations. France hosted the Celle-Saint-Cloud meeting in July 2017 between Fayez Sarraj and Khalifa Haftar, as well as the international conference on Libya in Paris in May 2018. The Berlin conferences held in January 2020 and then in June 2021 established the “Berlin process” including thematic working groups and a follow-up committee.<br><br>\r\n\r\nOn November 12, 2021, Paris hosted a new international conference for Libya, chaired by the President of the Republic, in the presence of members of the Berlin process, countries neighboring Libya, and the Libyan authorities (Prime Minister of the GUN Abelhamid Dbeiba and Chairman of the Presidential Council Mohamed Menfi).', 'Libya is a country in North Africa, whose name derives from Libou, a Berber people known since antiquity.\r\n\r\nIn Antiquity, the name of this people is also at the origin of that of the region of the continent commonly called ancient Libya, and of the denomination of Libyans, which then designates the North African Berber populations.\r\n\r\nThe territory of present-day Libya has been dominated throughout history by various peoples and states, including the Roman Empire, the Byzantine Empire, the Ottoman Empire, and finally in the 20th century the Kingdom of Italy. The regency of Tripoli under the Ottoman Empire was succeeded, from 1911, by the Italian colony of Libya: on this occasion, the country resumed the name of Libya, in force in antiquity. It was only after the Second World War that Libya emerged as a truly sovereign state.\r\n\r\n', 'uploads/lova29.jpg', '\r\nThe culture of Libya, a vast country in North Africa, primarily designates the observable cultural practices of its 6,500,000 inhabitants.\r\n\r\nLibyan culture is the result of a multicultural heritage influenced by multiple Barbarian, Arab, Ottoman, Berber and Italian invasions or occupations.', 'uploads/download (45).jpg'),
(67, 'Madagascar', 'Madagascar (in Malagasy: Madagasikara), in long form Republic of Madagascar (in Malagasy: Repoblikan\'i Madagasikara), is an island state located in the Indian Ocean and geographically attached to the African continent, from which it is separated by the Mozambique Channel . It is the fourth largest island in the world after Greenland, New Guinea and Borneo. 1,580 km long and 580 km wide, Madagascar covers an area of ​​587,000 km2. Its capital is Antananarivo and the country\'s currency is the Ariary. Its inhabitants, the Malagasy, are a people associating a mixture of populations of Austronesian and East African origins, but speaking a Malayo-Polynesian language: Malagasy. The country is surrounded by other islands and archipelagos: the Mascarenes (including Reunion and Mauritius), the Comoros (including Mayotte) and the Seychelles.', 'madagascar', 'During most of the 19th century, the island was administered by the Kingdom of Madagascar, this administration was exercised within the framework of the French protectorate of Madagascar after 1883, following the first Madagascar expedition. Considering that the protectorate is little applied by the Malagasy government, France organizes a second military expedition from 1895. The French establishments of Diego-Suarez, Nosy Be and Île Sainte-Marie are attached to the protectorate on January 28 1896. The troubles following the French military intervention will lead, in 1897, to the end of Malagasy autonomy, to the annexation of the island by France and to the reunion of the former protectorate and other territories French within the colony of Madagascar and dependencies. The first Malagasy autonomous government was reborn on October 10, 1958 when the Republic of Madagascar was proclaimed on the territory of the former protectorate (territory of the former Merina Kingdom and the former French establishments of Diego-Suarez, Nosy Be and Sainte-Marie Island) while remaining a member of the French Community. In 1960, the Malagasy Republic gained independence, which made the country one of the first to become sovereign in this area of ​​the Indian Ocean.', 'Economic growth reached 5.7% in 2021 despite the COVID-19 pandemic and multiple climatic shocks that have exacerbated Madagasca\'s fragility.<br><br> IMF has revised growth pace down to Madagascar in 2023 (4.0% against 4.2% initially forecast), driven by an increase in tourist activities (+1.2 points of GDP in travel receipts compared to 2022) and mining exports (+0.8 points of GDP). A significant increase in tourist arrivals is noted in 2022 (132 k arrivals against 35 k in 2021), but which remained half as high as in 2019 (383 k). The initial finance law for 2023 provides for a more optimistic growth scenario (+4.9%). This growth remains stable compared to 2022 (+4%), and follows the rebound in 2021 (+5.7%) driven by the resumption of activities of the country\'s main mining project (Ambatovy), after a sharp contraction of 7 .1% in 2020.\r\n\r\nGDP per capita remains one of the lowest in the world (536 USD in 2023, compared to 526 USD in 2022), economic growth being largely absorbed by population growth (+2.8% on average per year).', 'Politics in Madagascar is based on a multi-party semi-presidential unitary republic state model. The institutions of Madagascar are defined by the 2010 Constitution founding the Fourth Republic. The president is the elected head of state for five years, and the prime minister is the head of government. Executive power is in the hands of the government while legislative power is shared between the government and the two houses of parliament. The judiciary is independent of the first two.\r\n\r\nThe current President of the Republic is Andry Rajoelina since January 19, 2019.', '\r\nFirst discovery of the island by Europeans (1500-1817)\r\n\r\nIn 1643, the French installed the Colony of Fort-Dauphin there. In 1665, Louis XIV insisted on making Madagascar the forward base of the French East India Company.<br><br>The history of Madagascar refers to the human history of this island country located in the western part of the ocean Indian, SE Africa; for natural history, see \"Geology of Madagascar\" and \"Fauna of Madagascar\". The island of Madagascar is part of the African continent and therefore the Malagasy Republic is a member of the African Union. The population of Madagascar is mainly derived from African, Austronesian and Semitic contributions.<br><br>Archaeological discoveries allow us to consider a first presence of the human species in Madagascar around 8,000 years ago. Given the history of African settlement, it is possible that these first populations were related to the current Khoisan but from a genetic and linguistic point of view, there is no evidence that they were maintained and that they contributed to later settlement. from the island .', 'uploads/lova30.jpg', 'The culture of Madagascar, a vast island country located in the Indian Ocean and a member of the African Union, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 25 million inhabitants. This culture reflects the different waves of populations at the origin of the settlement of the Island whether from Asia, Africa, France during colonization or Arab culture. <br><br>The Malagasy people come from a vast mixture both human and cultural. This is due to the different origins of the settlement of the island of Madagascar for centuries already. Thus, depending on the region, we see different cultures manifesting themselves. In Antananarivo, the capital of the island, one feels more the French and Asian cultural influence, while in certain coastal areas one feels more the African and Arab influence.', 'uploads/gasy.jpg'),
(68, 'Malawia', 'Malawi, in long form the Republic of Malawi (in English Republic of Malawi, in chewa Malaŵi, or Nyasaland until 1964), is a state located in southern Africa, between Mozambique, Zambia and Tanzania. Without outlet to the sea, it is bathed by Lake Malawi, or Nyassa, the third largest lake in Africa by its area, which covers about one-fifth of the country\'s area and into which flow eight main rivers and hundreds of small rivers. \'water.', 'malawi', 'In 1891, the territory was colonized by the United Kingdom as the British Protectorate of Central Africa before being renamed Nyasaland in 1907. In 1953, Nyasaland was integrated into the federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland until the dissolution from the latter in 1963. The following year, the country was renamed Malawi and gained independence as a Commonwealth realm under Prime Minister Hastings Kamuzu Banda. In 1966, the latter became president by transforming the country into a presidential republic. From the early 1970s, Banda ruled the country as president for life of a repressive one-party dictatorship. In 1993, the multiparty system was established and Banda was defeated in the general elections of 1994. Since then, the country has continued to experience peaceful transitions of power.\r\n\r\nBantu ethnic groups represent almost the entire population. The official languages ​​are English and Chewa.', 'The country\'s GDP stands at USD 12.2 billion. It is thus one of the poorest economies in the world – 39th in sub-Saharan Africa in terms of GDP per capita (567 USD). According to the latest figures from the United Nations (Human Development Index – HDI), the country ranks 174th out of 198 countries, with a poverty rate (less than 1.9 USD per day) of nearly 75% of the population. population. With a population growth rate of almost 3% per year in recent years (the population is expected to double by 2050).<br><br>\r\nWith a GDP per capita of USD 567 in 2021, Malawi is one of the poorest countries in the world. <br><br> The country\'s GDP is USD 12.2 billion. It is thus one of the poorest economies in the world – 39th in sub-Saharan Africa in terms of GDP per capita (567 USD). According to the latest figures from the United Nations (Human Development Index – HDI), the country ranks 174th out of 198 countries, with a poverty rate (less than 1.9 USD per day) of nearly 75% of the population. population. With a population growth rate of almost 3% per year in recent years (the population is expected to double by 2050).<br> <br>\r\n\r\nMalawi\'s economy is not very diversified, with a great dependence on the agricultural sector (nearly 25% of GDP and 75% of jobs on average over the period 2018-2020). It is also particularly vulnerable to natural disasters (cyclones Ana in January 2022 and Freddy in March 2023).<br> <br>\r\n\r\nThe development of the private sector is hampered by structural difficulties: strong state intervention (particularly in the agricultural sector), which results in numerous market distortions; difficulties in accessing electricity and basic and telecommunications services; the underdeveloped level of the financial and banking system, and finally the mediocre quality of transport infrastructure, in a landlocked country.<br> <br>\r\n\r\nMalawi is classified as a “low income” country by the World Bank. As such, it is eligible for the most concessional financing from the window of the International Development Association (IDA), which is also the main external creditor of the country with nearly 50% of the outstanding amount.\r\nMalawi\'s economy is not very diversified, with a great dependence on the agricultural sector (nearly 25% of GDP and 75% of jobs on average over the period 2018-2020). It is also particularly vulnerable to natural disasters (cyclones Ana in January 2022 and Freddy in March 2023).', 'Dominated since its independence on July 6, 1964, by the authoritarian regime of Hastings Kamuzu BANDA and its single party, the Malawi Congress Party (MCP), Malawi experienced its first free general elections in May 1994, won by the United Democratic Front (UDF) of Bakili MULUZI.\r\n\r\nSeveral peaceful elections followed: June 1999: re-election of President MULUZI; May 2004: election of Bingu Wa MUTHARIKA (UDF); 2009: re-election of Bingu Wa MUTHARIKA (DPP - Democratic Progressive Party - founded in 2005 following a split within Mr. Muluzi\'s UDF); 2012: Vice President Joyce Banda became President of Malawi following the death of Bingu Wa MUTHARIKA; 2014: Election of Peter MUTHARIKA, brother of former President Bingu WA MUTHARIKA.<br><br>Malawi is a member of COMESA (Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa), SADC (Common Development of Southern Africa) and the African Union. It is also a party to the Non-Aligned Movement and the International Criminal Court (since 2002). Malawi contributes to UN peacekeeping operations and ratified the Paris Climate Agreement at the end of June 2017.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe European Union intervenes in Malawi, particularly in the areas of governance, sustainable agriculture and education.<br><br>\r\n\r\nMalawi has consistently voted in favor of all United Nations General Assembly resolutions relating to the war in Ukraine.', 'The history of Malawi in the prehistoric period is still relatively unknown. Malawi has some of the oldest remains of the genus Homo on the planet. The wave of Bantu expansion reached the area at the beginning of the Christian era. A second Bantu wave arrived in the 13th century. The Bantu political entities were followed by Portuguese exploration, the establishment of Arab trading posts and then British colonization in the form of a protectorate.\r\n\r\nAfter the failure of the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland, colonial Nyasaland became Malawi in 1964.', 'uploads/lova31.jpg', 'The culture of Malawi, a landlocked country in southern Africa, primarily refers to the observable cultural practices of its 16,500,000 inhabitants.<br><br>The official languages ​​are English and Chichewa. The other languages ​​spoken mainly by the population are Bantu: Tumbuka, Yao, Nyanja (including the Chewa dialect) and Ngoni.', 'uploads/download (46).jpg');
