(69, 'Mali', 'May is the fifth month of the Gregorian and Julian calendars. This month lasts 31 days. It is the third month of meteorological spring in the northern hemisphere, while it is associated with autumn in the southern hemisphere, but also the first month of summer (winter in the southern hemisphere).', 'mali', 'The name comes from the Latin maius (the month of May), in reference to the Italic deity Maia. Population: 20,856,000 inhabitants (UN 2021)\r\nAnnual population growth: 3% (UN 2021)\r\nLife expectancy: 59.5 (F), 58 (M) (at birth, UN 2021)<br><br>\r\n\r\nReligions: Islam 94.8%, Christianity 2.4%, animism 2% (2009 census)\r\nHuman Development Index: 186th out of 191 countries (UNDP, 2021)', 'GDP: 19.14 billion USD (World Bank, 2021)\r\nGDP per capita: US$873.8 (World Bank, 2021)\r\nGrowth rate: 2.5% (IMF, 2022)<br><br>\r\n\r\nInflation rate: 3% (IMF, 2023 - anticipation)\r\nMain clients: South Africa, Switzerland, Burkina Faso, Bangladesh (ITC, 2019)\r\nMain suppliers: Ivory Coast, France, China (ITC, 2019)<br><br>\r\n\r\nShare of main sectors of activity in GDP (UNCTAD, 2018):\r\nfarming: 40%\r\nindustry: 20%\r\nservices: 40%<br><br>\r\n\r\nExports from France to Mali (2021): EUR 406.9 million\r\nFrench imports from Mali (2021): EUR 7.8 million\r\n(French customs)', 'Mali has experienced two coups in the space of 9 months (August 2020 and May 2021) perpetrated by five colonels, including Assimi Goïta, currently president of the transition., The country is currently going through a transition phase whose modalities were initially determined to meet ECOWAS requirements, then were set out in a transition charter adopted in October 2020. According to the timetable agreed with ECOWAS, this transition period was to end in February/March 2022 with the holding of presidential and legislative elections. The presidential elections were postponed to February 2024 by the Malian transitional authorities and this extension of the duration of the transition was then the subject of a compromise with ECOWAS which, in July 2022, lifted the economic and financial sanctions. which it had taken against Mali in January 2022 (Mali remains however suspended from the organization).<br><br> Prominent Malian personalities have exercised an important role at the head of key organizations: the former Head of State Alpha Oumar Konaré as President of the African Union Commission (2003-2008), Soumaïla Cissé as Head of the WAEMU Commission (2004-2011), Michel Sidibé as Executive Director of UNAIDS (2008-2019) or Adama Ouane as administrator of the International Organization of La Francophonie (2015-2019).', 'Mali was the cradle of three great empires: the Ghana Empire, the Mali Empire and the Songhai Empire. It was subsequently a French colony from 1895 to 1960. A few years after its independence, it suffered the dictatorship of Moussa Traoré before experiencing a democratic regime (since the early 1990s).<br><br>\r\n\r\nAlso called Ouagadou, it was erected by the Sarakolés in the 4th century. He bases his prosperity on salt and gold. The empire will disintegrate in 1076 following the breakthroughs of the Berbers who came to Islamize West Africa. Founded in the 11th century, it was unified around 1222 or 1230 by Soundiata Keïta, king of Mandé, a region roughly corresponding to present-day Mali. He unites the Malinkés in order to counter the attacks of the king of Sosso, Soumaoro Kanté. In 1235, at the battle of Kirina, he defeated his adversary.\r\n\r\nThe “Manden Charter”, dating from 1222 or 1236, corresponds to the oath taken by Soundiata Keïta on the occasion of his enthronement. Considered to be one of the oldest texts relating to human rights, it is an oral, \"constitutional\" content relating to human rights and to the formal and legal organization governing the relationship between men. It will not be the subject of a written transcription until the 20th century. Soundiata Keïta then continued her conquests, thus taking over Koumbi Saleh, the former capital of the Ghana Empire, from the hands of the King of Sosso. He creates the second of the three great empires, the very rich and powerful empire of Mali, which is expanded, organized and managed by his successors.', 'uploads/lova32.jpg', 'The culture of Mali, a vast landlocked country in West Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its inhabitants (17,000,000, 2017 estimate).\r\n\r\nThe multitude of ethnic groups and the historical heritage make it a rich and diversified culture, preserving both its traditions such as orality with the griots or crafts and opening up, since its independence, to literature, theater , cinema and photography. <br><br>Since independence in 1960, Mali, a former French colony of French Sudan, French is the official language. It is spoken only by a minority of the population who prefer to express themselves in the different national languages. Bambara is the most spoken language in Mali. The main other languages ​​are Peul, Malinké, Sénoufo, Soninké, Sonrhaï and Dogon.\r\n\r\nThe 1987 census recorded the language spoken by people over the age of 6. Bambara is by far in the lead (50.3%), followed by Peul (10.7%), Dogon (6.9%), Songhay (6.3%) and Soninké (6.3%)1 .\r\n\r\nFrench is the language taught at school. Since the 1990s, an experiment called “convergent pedagogy” has enabled children in basic school to first learn to write in the national language, the one they naturally speak at home, then gradually French. Convergent pedagogy is currently becoming widespread.', 'uploads/download (47).jpg'),
(70, 'Morocco', 'Morocco (in Arabic: ٱلْمَغْرِب, al-Maġrib; in Amazigh: ⵎⵓⵔⴰⴽⵓⵛ, murakuc), or, since 1956, in long form the Kingdom of Morocco, formerly called the Cherifian Empire, is a regionalized unitary state located in North Africa. Its political system is a unitary and decentralized semi-parliamentary constitutional monarchy. Its administrative and political capital is Rabat and its largest city, as well as its economic capital, is Casablanca. ', 'maroc', 'Morocco consists of mountainous or desert areas, and it is one of the only countries - with Spain and France - to have shores on the Mediterranean Sea on one side and the Atlantic Ocean on the other. Its population is nearly 37 million in 2023 and its surface area is 446,550 km2 (76.84 inh./km2), or 710,850 km2 including Western Sahara — formerly \"Spanish Sahara\", considered as a non-autonomous territory by the United Nations Organization - of which it administers de facto about 80% and which it claims in its entirety, just like the Polisario Front. Its culture has been Arab-Berber for several centuries and has spread mainly to the Maghreb and southern Spain.\r\n\r\nThe Moroccan territory has traces of the presence of hominids dating back approximately 700,000 years and has been inhabited since prehistoric times by various populations. The Moroccan state, as a separate entity, was founded in 789 by Idris I.\r\n\r\nIt is also part of the United Nations, the Arab League, the African Union, the Arab Maghreb Union, the Organization of Islamic Cooperation, the International Organization of La Francophonie , of the Group of 77, of the Union for the Mediterranean and a candidate for membership of ECOWAS.', 'Morocco has returned to economic growth since the early 2000s, but this remains correlated with the agricultural sector and the global economy. After a slowdown in growth since 2018 (3.1% and 2.5% in 2019 against 4.2% in 2017), Morocco entered its deepest recession in 25 years in 2020, at -7.2% (source: IMF).<br><br>\r\n\r\nFaced with the Covid-19 health and economic crisis, Morocco quickly implemented strong support measures for businesses and the population, financed by a special Pandemic Management Fund, the amount of which reached more than 3 €bn. On the occasion of the Throne Day on July 29, 2020, the King announced an ambitious recovery plan (11% GDP) and structural reforms in the economy, social protection and public services.<br><br><br> br>\r\n\r\nThe country is working to promote greater resilience of the Moroccan economy to agricultural fluctuations. In this sense, major reforms have been undertaken as part of a sectoral diversification strategy. The stakes are high, because the agricultural sector represents 14% of GDP and employs 39% of the active population. Cereal yields were severely affected by recurrent droughts in 2020 (agricultural GDP down 8.1%).<br><br>\r\n\r\nThis reform plan was accompanied by efforts to straighten out the accounts\r\nbudgetary and external. The budget deficit has been constantly reduced for 5 years to reach 3.7% of GDP in 2018 However, the emergency measures decided in response to the crisis and the drop in revenue increase the imbalance in the public accounts in 2020 (doubling of the public deficit to -7.7% of GDP and increase of 11.3 points in public debt to 76.5% of GDP).', 'Morocco\'s politics are based on a constitutional monarchy with an elected parliament.\r\n\r\nExecutive power is shared between the government and the palace. Legislative power is shared between the government, and the two chambers of parliament, the House of Representatives and the House of Councillors. Morocco is a constitutional monarchy endowed with a strong power of leadership in the Person of the King. The King is the supreme political leader. He chairs the Council of Ministers; can dismiss any minister, dismiss the head of government, dissolve parliament, suspend the constitution, call new elections, or rule by dahir (royal decree). The king is the chief of the armies and religious leader of the country (“the commander of the believers”). <br><br>\r\nMorocco\'s politics are based on a constitutional monarchy with an elected parliament. Executive power is shared between the government and the palace. Legislative power is shared between the government, and the two chambers of parliament, the House of Representatives and the House of Councillors.', 'In the 19th century, Morocco was coveted by the great European powers and became a French protectorate in 1912. The country obtained true independence in 1956 after a war against France, and is today a parliamentary monarchy headed by King Mohamed VI. .<br><br>Inhabited since prehistoric times, Morocco and its territory have known Berber, Phoenician, Carthaginian, Roman, Vandal, Byzantine and Arab settlements. It was in 788, during his exile, that Idris I, fleeing the persecutions of the Abbasid caliphate, gave birth to a state in the Maghreb al-Aqsa (extreme Maghreb). Since then, Morocco has always kept, if not absolute independence, at least very strong autonomy.\r\n\r\nThe attraction of wealth from trade from the South (the Sahara) to the North (the West) will attract the covetousness of various tribes with the crossroads city Marrakech which will naturally become the capital of various dynasties, in particular those coming from the South ( Almoravids, Almohades, Saadians); this is the reason why the whole history of Morocco (from the Idrissides to the Alawites) was marked by the trade in wealth from the South to the North. The history and origin of Morocco were, are and will be marked by the link with the Sahara.', 'uploads/lova33.jpg', 'The culture of Morocco, a Maghreb country, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 36,500,000 inhabitants (2021 estimate).\r\n\r\nMoroccan culture has different aspects, which are developed below.\r\n\r\nIts geographical location makes Morocco a country at the crossroads of cultures and influences: Arab, Berber, sub-Saharan Africa, and Europe. This mosaic of cultures and influences gives Morocco a pleasant cultural richness . <br><br>They are honest with each other and have a sacred, brotherly relationship. They are fine workers from generation to generation and are very good in negotiation. Hospitality is a duty with them, because it is in their tradition.', 'uploads/download (48).jpg'),
(71, 'Mauritania', 'Mauritania (Arabic: موريتانيا), in long form the Islamic Republic of Mauritania (Arabic: الجمهورية الإسلامية الموريتانية), is a state in North West Africa. It is part of the African Union, the Arab League, the Arab Maghreb Union, the Organization of Islamic Cooperation and the Organization for the Development of the Senegal River (OMVS), in addition to be a member of the International Organization of La Francophonie (OIF). Its capital and largest city is Nouakchott. The other main towns are Nouadhibou, Kiffa, Kaédi, Zouerate and Rosso.', 'mauritania', 'Most of the country\'s surface lies in the Sahara. It has a coast of about 800 km open to the Atlantic Ocean stretching from Ndiago in the south to Nouadhibou in the north. To the north, it borders Western Sahara (claimed by Morocco and the Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic), Algeria to the north-northeast, Mali to the east and south-southeast, and Senegal to the southwest.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe territory became a French colony in 1903 and gained independence in 1960. Since then, the country has experienced several coups and periods of military rule. Mohamed Ould Ghazouani\'s victory in Mauritania\'s 2019 presidential election was supposedly the country\'s first peaceful transition of power since independence.<br><br>\r\n\r\nMauritania constitutes a space of contact between North Africa and sub-Saharan Africa, which makes it a multi-ethnic country; it is mainly populated by an Arab and Berber community in which two groups stand out: the Arab-Berber Moors called \"White Moors\" or Beidanes (which would represent 30%), and the Haratins called \"Black Moors\", descendants of slaves Arabic speakers, of Bafour origin (who would be 40% of the population), and of a black-African group made up of several ethnic groups originating from the southern regions of Mauritania, such as the Fulani, Soninke, Wolofs and Bambaras, who would represent 30% of the population (The World Factbook, 2023).', 'Average annual inflation reached 9.5% in 2022 and is expected to decline to 8% in 2023 as external price pressures abate. The fiscal balance recorded a deficit of 3.5% of GDP in 2022 compared to a surplus of 2.2% of GDP in 2021.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe Mauritanian economy is structurally volatile because it is dependent on international mineral prices – whose exports correspond to 28.9% of GDP. In 2021, minerals represented 72.6% of total exports (2.3 billion USD) (54.8% for iron, 10% for gold and 7.8% for copper). SNIM, which holds the iron production monopoly, produces between 12.7 and 13 Mt/year; making Mauritania the 15th largest producer in the world and the 2nd in Africa behind South Africa. New projects are being developed in the hope of reaching a production of 40 Mt/year. Fishery products represent 25.8% of total exports. The GDP is distributed as follows: the primary sector represents 20.3%, the secondary 35.9% and the tertiary 44%. The primary sector experienced negative growth of 3.6% in 2021, the agricultural sector suffering from poor quality inputs and lack of structuring of the sector, while the fishing sector lacks landing and fish processing.<br><br>\r\n\r\nAfter a recession in 2020 (-0.9%) and a slight rebound in 2021 (+2.4%), Mauritania\'s economic growth will have been robust in 2022 at 5.2%. This is explained by the good performance and a rebound effect of the extractive sector and in particular gold production (which had been strongly affected by a fire in 2021), as well as by the performance of the agricultural sector. According to the World Bank, growth will decline slightly in 2023, to 4.5%.', 'The Islamic Republic of Mauritania is a democracy led by a president elected by universal suffrage. Executive power is exercised by the government while legislative power is shared between the government and the National Assembly. The Constitution of the Islamic Republic of Mauritania dates from July 20, 1991, and has been revised three times, in 2006, 2012 and 2017. It recalls in its preamble its attachment to Islam and to democratic principles as defined in the Declaration universal human rights as well as in the African Charter on Human and Peoples\' Rights.', 'Between 1902 and 1934, Mauritania was conquered by the French colonial army, the city of Rashid was razed, and shared with Spain to the north. In 1920, it was distinguished as an entity within the framework of French West Africa, and any reference to the empire of Morocco or that of Sudan disappeared.<br><br>The history of present-day modern Mauritania begins with the official definition and delimitation of the country\'s borders in 1904 by France and Spain, then occupying colonial powers.\r\n\r\nThis boundary line was not established according to the populations and therefore some of these populations were divided by this process of partition. Ethnic mixing has always existed in Mauritania and its first inhabitants were of various sub-Saharan origins (Mali, Niger, Ghana, Senegal). The history of these peoples goes back several millennia, but written traces are rare for the oldest periods in the country.', 'uploads/lova35.jpg', 'Mauritanian culture, due to the geographical position of Mauritania, is a mixture of Moorish (Arab-Berber) and black-sub-Saharan culture. For a long time, Mauritania was a place of convergence of various currents of civilizations, The empires (of Mali, Ghana, the Almoravids, etc.) <br><br>The culture of Mauritania, a country in North Africa- West, designates primarily the observable cultural practices of its 4,000,000 inhabitants.\r\n\r\nMauritanian culture, due to the geographical position of Mauritania, is a mixture of Moorish (Arab-Berber) and black-sub-Saharan culture.\r\n\r\n\r\nManuscript in a Chinguetti library\r\nFor a long time, Mauritania was a place of convergence of various currents of civilizations, The empires (of Mali, Ghana, Almoravids, etc.) which succeeded one another, made Mauritania a land of fertile exchanges and mixing ethnic and cultural backgrounds as rich as they are varied.\r\n\r\nHistoric towns such as Chinguetti, Ouadane, Tichitt and Oualata, classified by UNESCO as World Heritage Sites, are one of the visible expressions of this heritage and the diversity that have marked the history of Mauritania.\r\n\r\nThe universities of the desert (traditional universities) and its libraries where several thousand unpublished manuscripts have wandered for centuries testify to the richness and originality of the Mauritanian cultural heritage.\r\n\r\n99% of the inhabitants of Mauritania are Sunni Muslims.', 'uploads/mqdefault.jpg'),
(72, 'Mozambic', 'Mozambique, in long form the Republic of Mozambique, in Portuguese: Moçambique and República de Moçambique, is a state located on the eastern coast of the African continent. It is surrounded by South Africa, Eswatini, Madagascar, Comoros, Zimbabwe, Zambia, Malawi and Tanzania. The capital, and the most populous city in the country, is Maputo.', 'mozambique', 'The territory was colonized by the Portuguese colonial Empire in 1498. After more than four centuries of colonial domination, a war of independence broke out in 1964 between Portugal and the Mozambique Liberation Front (FRELIMO), an anti-colonialist armed movement. The country gained its independence in 1975 following the Carnation Revolution as a communist republic with FRELIMO as its single party. Two years later, a civil war broke out in 1977 between the FRELIMO government and the anti-communist rebels of the National Resistance of Mozambique (RENAMO). It ended in 1992 following the peace agreements between RENAMO and FRELIMO establishing a multiparty system. However, FRELIMO remains the dominant party despite changing its ideology from communism to democratic socialism in 1989.\r\n\r\nRetaining Portuguese as the official language, Mozambique is the second Portuguese-speaking country in Africa, behind Angola, by population and area. The country is a member of the Community of Portuguese-Speaking Countries (CPLP), the International Organization of La Francophonie (OIF), the Commonwealth and the Organization of Islamic Cooperation. The population consists almost exclusively of Bantu ethnic groups.', 'The country\'s main development assets are in the tourism and mining sectors. In 2007, major underground mining projects emerged to exploit mineral sands, coal, gold, bauxite, copper, silver and tantalum.<br><br>The After thirty years of uninterrupted growth (7% on average between 2010 and 2015 followed by a slowdown from 2016), Mozambique experienced its first decline in 2020 (-1.5%) under the effect of the pandemic and cyclone episodes. This development was followed by a modest recovery in 2021 (+2.5%). With a GDP/inhabitant of 444 USD, Mozambique is in the category of “least developed countries” of the World Bank. In particular, it faces significant demographic pressure (+2.9%, 32.1 million inhabitants).\r\n\r\nThe country has many advantages: through its coastal geography, Mozambique offers three logistics corridors to neighboring landlocked countries (Zimbabwe, Malawi, Zambia, northern South Africa); the primary mining and agricultural resources are considerable and make up 77% of the State\'s exports; Mozambique is a regional electricity supplier thanks to its hydraulic reserves.', 'Mozambique has been independent from Portugal since June 25, 1975. After sixteen years (1977-92) of civil war between the ruling party, Frelimo (Mozambique Liberation Front), of Marxist allegiance, and Renamo (National Resistance Mozambique), supported by the South African apartheid regime, the Rome Peace Accords (October 4, 1992) opened a period of relative stability. Since then, political life has been dominated by Frelimo and two opposition parties, Renamo and the Democratic Movement of Mozambique (MDM, born in 2009 from a split from Renamo).<br><br>Mozambique favors the action within the framework of the African Union (AU), striving to promote common positions across the continent in international negotiations. Mozambique signed the agreement to establish the Continental Free Trade Area in March 2018, but has yet to ratify it. Mozambican diplomacy, pragmatic, aims to attract investors and mobilize international resources for its development. Mozambique is a non-permanent member of the United Nations Security Council for 2023-2024.', 'By history of Mozambique, we mean here the history of the territories belonging to Mozambique, before and after the independence of this country, acquired in June 1975. <br><br>\r\n\r\nThe history of Mozambique in its prehistoric period is poorly known. The first difficulty lies in the choice of names used to designate the populations: the terms used in the 20th century were often those of the European colonizers. The French term \'Bochimans\', for example, is derived from the word used by Dutch settlers \'bosjesman\', and literally meaning \'men of the bushes\', \'men of the bush\' or \'men of the bush\'. English settlers used the literal translation \"Bushmen\". These Bushmen, hunter-gatherers, were opposed to the Hottentots, another term of the Dutch colonists, to designate populations, arrived from the north, from the Zambezi valley and with a more pastoral way of life, devoting themselves to the breeding of animals, agriculture and mastering the work of iron and having a more hierarchical social structure. At the end of the 20th century and beginning of the 21st century, a distance was taken both from the vocabulary of settlers of European origin and from this pattern of opposition, this dichotomy. Several terms are used but the hunter-gatherers initially settled are often referred to as the San people, and the pastoral populations of Khoikhoi .', 'uploads/lova36.jpg', 'Mozambican culture, a country in southern Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 27,000,000 inhabitants (2018 estimate, compared to 5,500,000 inhabitants in 1950).\r\n\r\nMozambique is a country created by the Portuguese by bringing together several peoples of Bantu languages, but also some of Nilotic languages. Most of the inhabitants do not speak Portuguese and only speak their language or that of the neighboring ethnic groups. The Portuguese did not westernize these peoples. However, the political and economic elite is deeply impregnated with Portuguese culture to the detriment of its culture of origin.\r\n\r\nMozambicans cultivate and consume cassava, yams, maize and different kinds of millets.', 'uploads/download (50).jpg'),
(73, 'Namibia', 'Namibia, in long form the Republic of Namibia (in English: Namibia and Republic of Namibia; in Afrikaans: Namibië et Republiek van Namibië; in German: Namibia et Republik Namibia), is a country located in southern Africa. It is bordered geographically to the west by the Atlantic Ocean, to the north by Angola, to the south by South Africa, to the east by Botswana and to the northeast by Zambia. Its easternmost limit is less than two hundred meters from the tripoint where the borders of Zimbabwe, Botswana and Zambia meet, on the Zambezi River, at the confluence of the Kwando River. Largely desert, the country owes its name to the Namib Desert, which covers its Atlantic coast. Its eastern borders are largely covered by the Kalahari Desert. The capital, which is the most populous city in the country, is Windhoek.', 'namibie', 'With a population of around 2.6 million, its population density is the lowest in Africa and second to last in the world. The population consists largely of Bantu ethnic groups, notably the Ovambos who make up almost half of the population. Although the country is secular, almost 90% of the inhabitants are Christians. English is the official language of the country, but several other languages ​​are also spoken there.\r\n\r\nThe territory of the country was colonized by Germany in 1884 and then became German South West Africa. Between 1904 and 1908, a genocide was committed against the Hereros and Nama peoples. During the First World War, the territory became South West Africa, a territory under the mandate of South Africa, under which apartheid was imposed in the late 1940s. A war of independence broke out in 1966 and ended the country\'s independence in 1990. Since then, the country has been a republic with a semi-presidential regime. Although multiparty, the South West African People\'s Organization (SWAPO) remains the dominant party. The country\'s economy is mainly based on agriculture, fishing, mining and tourism.\r\n\r\nNamibia is a member of the United Nations and the African Union. It also became an observer associated with the Community of Portuguese-Speaking Countries (CPLP) at the Dili Summit in 2014.', 'With a GDP of USD 12 billion in 2021, Namibia is a small economy. But with a population of 2.5 M inhabitants, it also ranks in the top 10 of the richest countries in sub-Saharan Africa (GDP per capita of 4,800 USD).<br><br>Namibia ranks 128th in the world for GDP per capita. At the level of the African continent, it ranks 8th in terms of per capita income and 11th in terms of the human development index. It is a stable and open economy that relies mainly on its mining resources. Due to the weakness of its domestic market, it is very dependent on its foreign trade, which makes it very dependent on the South African economy. Furthermore, as the Namibian economy is hardly diversified, it is therefore highly exposed to fluctuations in the price of raw materials. It is still confronted with major social disparities stemming from the apartheid suffered during the occupation of South Africa. Furthermore, the AIDS pandemic that is raging in Namibia is a real brake on its economic development.', 'Namibia is a multi-party presidential republic, where the president is both head of state and head of government. Executive power is in the hands of the government while legislative power is shared between the government and the two houses of parliament. The judiciary is independent of the first two.\r\n\r\nThe South-West African People\'s Organization has been the dominant party since independence. Opposition parties are allowed but it is generally accepted that they have little chance of gaining power. <br><br>\r\n\r\nParliament is made up of two chambers, the National Assembly and the National Council. The National Assembly has 78 members in office for five years, of whom 72 are elected by proportional suffrage and 6 are appointed by the president. The National Council has 26 members elected for six years in constituencies of two seats each.\r\n\r\nThe Assembly is the main legislative body, with the Council playing more of an advisory role.', 'In 1915, South Africa, being a member of the Commonwealth at the time occupied by the German colony of South West Africa administered Namibia between 1915 - and 1966. Namibia fought for independence during the period from 1966 to 1990 and was finally declared independent in 1990.<br><br>The history of Namibia is divided into several very distinct eras. Namibia is the third youngest country in Africa after the independence of Eritrea in 1993 and South Sudan in 2011, Namibia has been independent since 1990.\r\n\r\nFormerly \"land without a name\", baptized Deutsch-Südwestafrika from the German colonization in 1884, this territory was administered by the dominion of the Union of South Africa from 1915 to 1961, then was placed under the supervision of the Republic of South Africa until 1990.', 'uploads/lova37.jpg', 'The culture of Namibia, a vast country in southern Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 2,534,000 inhabitants.<br><br>The most spoken language is Oshiwambo which concerns 48% of Namibian speakers (mother tongue). The Khoikhoi language comes second with 11% of speakers tied with the Afrikaans language spoken by 11% of the population. The Kwangali language is spoken by 10% of the population.\r\n\r\nAlthough English is the official language, it is only spoken by less than 1% of the population as their mother tongue, and 7% among the white population, but it is often poorly spoken, despite compulsory schooling (which is however recent). The German language is also present in the territory, it is spoken in particular by the descendants of Germanic settlers (about 30,000 people), by German-speaking expatriates and it is also spoken as a second language by 45,000 Namibians, especially in the Swakopmund region. . Küchendeutsch is a German sabir spoken by 15,000 black African people. German is therefore spoken, to varying degrees, in Namibia by at least 100,000 people. The presence of Portuguese on Namibian soil is explained by the country\'s proximity to Angola.\r\n\r\nNamibia is a very heterogeneous country linguistically. In fact, in addition to these languages ​​of European heritage, there coexist eight languages ​​and more than twenty main dialects (Silozi, Otjihero, Setswana, Damara-nama, Oshiwambo, etc.).', 'uploads/download (51).jpg'),
(74, 'Niger', 'Niger is a country in West Africa. It is bordered by Algeria, Benin, Burkina Faso, Chad, Libya, Mali and Nigeria. Its capital is Niamey. The inhabitants are Nigeriens, not to be confused with Nigerians who are the people of Nigeria.', 'niger', 'Population: 24.2 million (World Bank, 2020)\r\nPopulation growth rate: 3.8% (World Bank, 2020)\r\nUrban population growth rate: 4.4% (World Bank, 2020)\r\nGNI per capita (in USD): 540 (World Bank, 2020)\r\nLife expectancy at birth: 62 years (World Bank, 2019)\r\nFertility rate: 6.8 children per woman (World Bank, 2019)\r\nPrimary school completion rate: 62.3% (World Bank, 2019)\r\nHuman Development Index: 189th out of 189 (UNDP, 2020)\r\nReligions: Islam (98%), Christianity, animism .', 'Niger\'s economic growth should follow a positive trend in 2023, reaching a rate of 6.9%, and practically double by 2024 (12.5%) if the authorities achieve their oil production objectives. ', 'Niger is one of the poorest countries in the world, despite its uranium resources. Undermined by attacks from groups linked to the Islamic State and Al-Qaeda, it is the third country in the region to suffer a coup since 2020 after Mali and Burkina Faso.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe Nigerien crisis comes on July 29, 2023, after the July 26 coup in Niger where the country\'s presidential guard detains President Mohamed Bazoum, while the commander of the presidential guard, Brigadier General Abdourahamane Tchiani, proclaims himself leader of a new military junta.<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn response, on July 30, 2023, the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) gave the putschists an ultimatum, until August 6, 2023, to restore democracy under pain of international sanctions and a use of force. The military junta nevertheless remains in control of the country after this date.', 'French military conquest since 1900, Niger despite much resistance was forced into a colony on October 13, 1922, inside French West Africa; declared a member of the French Community in December 1958, the republic has been declared independent since August 3, 1960. <br><br>\r\n\r\nMany fossils of dinosaurs (iguanodons) from the Lower Cretaceous have been found in Tazolé, in the south-east of Aïr. Ceramic remains from the 8th millennium BC have been unearthed in the Aïr massif. BC, contemporaneous with the invention of pottery in other parts of the world.\r\n\r\nBetween 2000 and 3000 BC. J.-C., the desertification of the Sahara, begun at that time, then pushes the populations of farmers and ceramists towards the south, giving way to communities of cattle breeders who engrave on the rocks many representations of their herds. Engravings from this period also testify to the presence at this latitude of elephants, hippopotamuses and abundant and varied savannah fauna.\r\n\r\nThe Ténéré desert is rich in testimonies of human presence in the Neolithic era with abundant stone material (arrowheads, millstones, etc.), until the desertification of the region in the 1st century BC.', 'uploads/lova38.jpg', 'The culture of Niger, a vast landlocked country in West Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 20,000,000 inhabitants.<br><br>\r\nThe cultural wealth of Niger resides essentially in the ethnic diversity of its population: Hausa, Djerma, Songhaï, Tuareg, Peulh, Toubou, Kanouri and Arab characterized by two worlds which coexist, nomadic and sedentary, or breeders and farmers with each has its own cultural particularities.<br><br>The official language of Niger is French1, spoken by 12.70% of Nigeriens in 2012 as a second language and not a native one (it is the language of education)2 . The ten “languages ​​of the communities constituting the nation of Niger”3, and therefore native, are Hausa (49.6%), Zarma-Songhaï (20.8%) and (4.7%), Tamasheq (8, 4%), Fulani (8.3%) or Fulfulde, Kanuri (4.8%), Dialectal Arabic (1.2%), Buduma, Gulmancema, Tassawaq and Toubou. There is also the gourma (0.5%).\r\n\r\nFrench is the only language of instruction from the fourth year of primary education to university.', 'uploads/download (52).jpg'),
(75, 'Nigeria', 'Nigeria or Nigeria, in long form the Federal Republic of Nigeria9 or Federal Republic of Nigeria, is a West African country located in the Gulf of Guinea. With more than 219 million inhabitants in 20221, Nigeria is the most populous country in Africa and the sixth country in the world by number of inhabitantsb.', 'nigeria', 'Nigeria is a country in the Sahelian belt.\r\n\r\nLocated on the edge of the Gulf of Guinea, Nigeria has 4,047 km of land borders and 853 km of coastline. It is bordered to the west by Benin (773 km), to the east-south-east by Cameroon (1,690 km), to the north by Niger (1,497 km) and to the east-north- east by Chad (84 km).\r\n\r\nThe country is the first economic power of the African continent in 2016, and the 27th in the world (GDP) according to the World Bank. Nigeria\'s economic and demographic weight have earned it the nickname \"Giant of Africa\". However, despite significant oil production and a diversified economy, the country remains relatively poor, in particular due to high levels of corruption. The last elections take place in February 2023 with the victory of Bola Tinubu (from the Congress of Progressives party).\r\n\r\nSince 1991, the capital of Nigeria has been the new city of Abuja. The country is part of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) and the Organization of Islamic Cooperation (OIC). Its inhabitants are Nigerians.', 'Real GDP growth fell to 3.3% in 2022 from 3.6% in 2021, mainly due to lower oil production. This led to a 5% decline in all industry, offset by growth in services (7%) and agriculture (2%).<br><br>Nigeria\'s economy is in its structure comparable to that of many African countries, but everything is on a higher scale: based on abundant labor and natural resources, leakage of funds linked to illicit financial practices favored among other things by corruption and overall, the opacity of the global financial system is a major obstacle to development.\r\n\r\nThe most populous country in Africa, it is the continent\'s leading oil producer, this hydrocarbon representing 90% of all export products. Its gross domestic product (GDP) per capita places it in the African average, but it remains well below the pre-independence level. About two thirds of the population live below the absolute poverty line ($1 per day), compared to 43% in 1985. Thanks to its human potential [ref. necessary] and its wealth in natural resources, Nigeria ranks as the 1st economic power in Africa with a GDP of 481.07 billion dollars (2016), ahead of South Africa (312.8 billion dollars in 2016). Its GDP (in purchasing power parity) was the second in Africa behind Egypt in 2018.\r\n\r\nMost of the economic activity takes place in the coastal zone, in the south of the country, particularly around Lagos. Although employing most of the working population, the country\'s agriculture has tended to develop in recent years (33% of GDP in 2009) with the appearance of local companies such as Dangote, which produces bananas, maize, cassava, cocoa, groundnut, etc. The industry is not very present in the whole country.\r\n\r\nTransparency International\'s 2008 Corruption Perceptions Index ranked it 121st out of 180 countries assessed.', 'Nigeria is a multi-party federal republic with a presidential system, where the president is both head of state and head of government. Executive power is vested in the president, while legislative power is shared between the government and the two chambers of parliament, the Senate and the House of Representatives.<br><br>The National Assembly forms the bicameral parliament. It is made up of the House of Representatives, which has 360 members elected for four years in as many constituencies. The current president of this Chamber is Femi Gbajabiamila. The Senate has 109 members elected for four years (three members for each of the country\'s 36 states, plus one member for the capital Abuja).', 'Nigeria\'s history dates back to prehistoric times. In the 9th century, the first known political institutions developed and extended their influence during the period corresponding to the European Middle Ages. Europeans, through the Portuguese, did not discover the region until the 15th century.<br><br>In the forests of southwestern Nigeria, some of the oldest human remains in Africa were discovered by Charles Thurstan Shaw in 1965, in a rock shelter at Iwo Eleru. These human remains have been dated between 16,000 BC. AD and 12000 BC. It seems in particular that humans lived in tropical forests 14,000 years ago, as demonstrated by the site of Iho Eleru.\r\n\r\nOther archaeological research also testifies to a settlement in southwestern Nigeria around 9000 BC. J.-C., (and perhaps even earlier) in Okigwe, in the south-east of the country. The breeders of the 4th millennium BC. J.-C. practice ceramics and microlithics. In the south, populations of hunter-gatherers settled down and began to live from agriculture around the 1st millennium BC. J.-C. The working of iron is attested in the 2nd century BC. AD.\r\n\r\nThe first known civilization in Nigeria is the Nok civilization, which appeared around 1000 BC. AD on the plateau of Jos, in the northeast of the country.', 'uploads/lova39.jpg', 'Of the 250 ethnic groups in Nigeria, three predominate: the Hausa in the north, the Ibo (or Igbo) in the east and the Yoruba in the west. Religions tend to follow these ethnic lines: Muslims dominate in the North, Catholics in the East and animists in the West.<br><br> The culture of Nigeria, a country in West Africa, is the set of cultural practices of its 200,000,000 inhabitants, essentially from the many civilizations that have succeeded one another.\r\n\r\nThe oldest traces of settlement in Nigeria date back to prehistoric times. The Nok culture, which dates back to the first millennium BC, leaves the oldest known statues in sub-Saharan Africa.', 'uploads/download (53).jpg'),
(76, 'Uganda', 'Uganda, in long form the Republic of Uganda or the Republic of Uganda, (in English: Uganda and Republic of Uganda, in Swahili: Uganda and Jamhuri ya Uganda), is a country in East Africa . It is also considered part of the African Great Lakes. It is surrounded by the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the west, Kenya to the east, Rwanda to the southwest, South Sudan to the north, and Tanzania to the south. The south of the country encompasses a large part of Lake Victoria. Uganda takes its name from the kingdom of Buganda, which once covered the southernmost regions, whose capital and largest city is Kampala. Uganda is a member country of the Organization of Islamic Cooperation.', 'uganda', 'The territory became a British protectorate in 1894 and obtained its independence in 1962 under Prime Minister Milton Obote, who became president in 1966 by transforming the parliamentary system into a presidential system. In 1967, the country became a republic and abolished the precolonial monarchies. Most monarchies are re-established in the 1990s as constitutional monarchies. In 1971 Obote was overthrown and replaced by Idi Amin Dada in a coup. Amin imposed a brutal dictatorship until his overthrow in 1979 by the Ugandan-Tanzanian war. A bush war broke out the following year against the restored government of Obote. In 1986, the National Resistance Movement won the war and Yoweri Museveni became president. Thanks to the constitutional amendments, he remains the current president.', 'Uganda\'s economy is traditionally based on agriculture (80% of the working population), particularly coffee; it is developing slowly despite an often unfavorable regional context.<br><br>With an estimated GDP of 42.5 billion USD in 2021 and a population of 42.5 million inhabitants, Uganda is the third largest economy in the East African Community (EAC). GDP growth, which was 7.5% per year during the 2000s, slowed to 2.3% in 2012 before returning to an annual average of 5.5% until 2019. Population growth (3 .6% per year) limits the increase in GDP per capita to USD 1000.5 in 2021. The economy is dominated by services (53.5% of GDP in 2019), followed by industry (23.8 %) and agriculture (22.7%). In 2021, the Ugandan economy, driven by the gradual reopening of the economy and the recovery in consumption, rebounded to 5.1%. Growth in 2022 is expected at 4.9%. After 4 years of relatively low inflation, this inflation, linked to the economic effects of the war in Ukraine, should stand at 6.1% in 2022, above the central bank\'s target (5. 0%).', 'Uganda has been ruled since 1986 by President Yoweri Museveni. Following the presidential election on January 14, 2021, he was re-elected for a sixth term with 58.64% of the vote. The main opponent, Bobi Wine (real name Robert Kyagulanyi Ssentamu), won 34.83% of the vote. Turnout (57.22%) is down compared to the 2016 presidential elections (67.61%).\r\n\r\nAfter the confirmation of the election results, President Museveni was sworn in in May 2021 and reshuffled his government in June - his party, the NRM (National Resistance Movement), having also won the legislative elections.<br><br>Relations with the DRC are marked by Ugandan military interventionism in eastern Congo in the 1990s. The Ugandan occupation of Ituri during the Second Congo War was the subject of a legal dispute before the International Court of Justice ( ICJ). The accession to power of President Tshisekedi in 2019 has improved relations between Kinshasa and Kampala. The DRC is now one of the regional priorities for Kampala, particularly with a view to strengthening economic exchanges by renovating roads between border towns.', 'This article presents a summary of the history of Uganda. Uganda is a country in East Africa, and is also part of what is commonly called the Africa of the Great Lakes, with in particular Lake Kyoga in the northern part of the country, Lake Victoria at the southern limits of the country, and lakes Edward and Albert at the eastern limits. This region saw the development of several kingdoms, from the 15th century to the 19th century, the particularity of which was an early political centralization. The most important of these kingdoms was Buganda, from which its name is derived. The region was colonized by the British in the second half of the 19th century, and regained its independence in 1962.<br><br>The 17th, 18th and 19th centuries were marked by the expansion of the kingdom of Buganda whose influence replaces that of the declining Bounyoro. The strategy of the various Kabaka (kings) takes several aspects. The first is to try to control the trade routes that connect the Indian Ocean coast to Bunyoro, then the commercial center of the region. The second consists in taking advantage of the succession disputes and the political explosion to intervene more and more insistently in the neighboring kingdoms. The decisive rise of the kingdom comes under the reign of the Kabaka Suna. The weakened kingdoms then pass under the dependence of the Bagandas.', 'uploads/lova40.jpg', 'This article is about the culture of Uganda (East Africa), the cultural practices of its 40,000,000 people.<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nThe cultural diversity in Uganda consists of more than 50 tribes, including the indigenous Ugandan people, and a small population from the migration of Europeans, Asians and Arabs. There are four main ethnic groups in Uganda which are Bantu, Nilotic, NiloHamitic and Hamite.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe importance of culture in Uganda has been recognized by the cultural values ​​it brings to the community. Within this diverse culture, traditional dance has always been part of Ugandan identity. Each ethnic community has its own dances, with different meanings and purposes, and visitors can easily distinguish one tribe from another. Local people often incorporate these dances into their daily lives to maintain and share cultural values ​​with different generations.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe “Gomesi” and the “Kanzu” are traditional Ugandan clothes. the “Gomesi” is a national dress in Uganda often worn by Ugandan women during events or ceremonies, while the “Kanzu” is worn by Ugandan men in the exercise of cultural functions.', 'uploads/download (55).jpg');
