(77, 'Republic of congo', 'Congo, in long form the Republic of Congo, or informally Congo-Brazzaville (to distinguish it from Congo-Kinshasa), is a country in Central Africa, located on either side of the equator. Its neighbors are: Gabon to the west; Cameroon to the north-northwest; the Central African Republic to the north-northeast, the Democratic Republic of the Congob to the northeast, southeast and south; Cabinda (Angola) to the southwest. The country extends over 1,500 km from north to south and 425 km from east to west.', 'rep-of-congo', 'The Republic of the Congo is frequently referred to informally as \"Congo-Brazzaville\", after its capital, to easily distinguish it in common parlance from the neighboring Democratic Republic of the Congo or \"Congo-Kinshasa\", Kinshasa being the capital of the country. another Congo.\r\n\r\nBefore French colonization, the current territory of the Congo was occupied by several political entities, including the kingdom of Loango (founded around the 16th century), the Kongo (founded around the 13th century) and the Tio kingdom (founded in the 17th century) . Following several exploration missions, the most notable of which remains that of the Frenchman Savorgnan de Brazza (the capital of the country today bears his name), this territory was integrated into the second French colonial empire at the end of the 19th century.', '\r\nGDP thus posted growth of 8.5% in 2022 according to the IMF (after 6.2% in 2021) - the initial forecasts having been raised - and this, despite a difficult external environment with the repercussions in particular of the war in Ukraine.<br><br>The economy of the Republic of Congo is based mainly on the exploitation of hydrocarbons along the Atlantic coast. Wood, services, and an embryonic agriculture constituting the rest of the activity. Congo is a developing country, included in the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries Initiative (IPPTE)2.\r\n\r\nThe two mainstays of exports are wood and oil, both of which are mainly exploited by French companies which pay very large foreign currencies to the State in return.\r\n\r\nWood represents an important part of Congo\'s exports: mahogany, okoumé, limba, etc. Industrial activity is based on the production of consumer goods: tobacco, cement, textiles, soap, alcoholic beverages, shoes, etc. More than 95% of trade is in the hands of foreigners or people of foreign origin .', 'The republic of the Congo is a multiparty republic with a presidential system, where the president is both head of state and head of government.<br><br>The republic of the Congo is a multiparty republic with a presidential system, where the president is both head of state and head of government. Executive power is in the hands of the government while legislative power is shared between the government and the two chambers of Parliament: the National Assembly and the Senate. From 1970 to 1992, the country, officially called the People\'s Republic of Congo, was governed under a one-party system. After the adoption of a new constitution in 1992 and until the civil war in 1997, the country\'s system of government was similar to the French system. Having taken power, Denis Sassou-Nguesso suspended the 1992 constitution. The constitution, adopted by referendum in 2002, returns to a presidential regime, with a seven-year term for the head of state and a bicameral parliament. The constitution, adopted by referendum in 2015, returns to presidential rule, with a five-year term for the head of state.', 'This country gained its independence on August 15, 1960. Its other names during the colonial era were French Congo then Middle Congo Territory (to distinguish it from the Congo Free State which became Belgian Congo in 1908) and finally Republic of the Congo from November 28, 1958 (a year and a half before its independence).<br><br>This article summarizes the history of the current Republic of the Congo from 1880 to the present day. This country gained its independence on August 15, 1960. Its other names during the colonial era were French Congo then territory of the Middle Congo (to distinguish it from the Congo Free State which became Belgian Congo in 1908) and finally Republic of Congo from November 28, 1958 (a year and a half before its independence).\r\n\r\nThe current Republic of Congo is a country in Central Africa, sometimes called Congo-Brazzaville to differentiate it from the Democratic Republic of Congo (called Congo-Kinshasa for the same reason). The Republic of Congo was also known by the official name of People\'s Republic of Congo from 1969 to 1992 before returning to its original name.', 'uploads/lova41.jpg', 'Congolese culture is the essence of national identity. In an ethnic mosaic, its heterogeneous character constitutes a transcendent wealth that has been able to inspire the arts, but above all music.<br><br>The Republic of the Congo, by the very layout of its territory, has a wide variety of cultures, from the savannahs of the Niari plain to the flooded forests of the North, from the immense Congo river to the steep and forested mountains of Mayombe and the 170 km of beaches on the Atlantic coast.', 'uploads/download (56).jpg'),
(78, 'Rwanda', 'Rwanda, in long form the Republic of Rwanda, (in Kinyarwanda: Repubulika y\'u Rwanda, in English: Republic of Rwanda, in Swahili: Jamhuri ya Rwanda), nicknamed the \"land of a thousand hills\", is a country of East Africa. Rwanda extends its 26,338 km2 in the Great Lakes region. It shares borders with, to the north, Uganda, to the east, Tanzania, to the south, Burundi, and to the west, the Democratic Republic of Congo. Its capital Kigali is located in the center of the country.', 'rwanda', 'The Rwandans speak Kinyarwanda, and live in the hills which constitute the reference location of the habitats. The Banyarwanda, the cultural group of the country is divided into three sub-groups, the Twa, the Hutu and the Tutsi, who respectively constitute 1%, 84%, and 15% of the population. Rwanda was established as a kingdom in the 15th century ruled by Tutsi kings before becoming part of the German colony of German East Africa in 1885. After Germany\'s defeat in World War I, the territory became part of the Belgian colony of Ruanda-Urundi in 1923. The two colonial powers practiced a pro-Tutsi policy through the monarchy and engendered resentment in the majority Hutu .', 'Despite these challenges, real GDP grew by 8.2% in 2022. Rwanda\'s development model, which is largely based on the state sector, has shown its limits with the considerable increase in public debt in recent years. .<br><br>The Rwandan economy is expected to contract in 2020. Forecast at 2.0% in the October World Economic Outlook (WEO) and 8.0% before the pandemic, the growth forecast for 2020 has revised by the IMF to -0.2% during its October mission. Economic activity picked up in the second half, notably thanks to the monetary and economic support measures taken by the government, but less quickly than initially expected. Hotels and restaurants are particularly affected by the crisis (up to -80%). The Fund also expects a more timid rebound in 2021 (5.7% vs. 6.2% in the October WEO).', 'The policy of Rwanda is strongly impregnated with the consequences of the genocide of the Tutsi of 1994, of the context of the bad development and the instability of Africa of the great lakes (Burundi, Uganda, East of the democratic Republic of Congo). <br><br>\r\n\r\nPresident Kagame, who grew up in exile in Uganda, came to power in Rwanda following the 1994 Tutsi genocide and the victory of the Rwandan Patriotic Army (armed wing of the Rwandan Patriotic Front, a political party by Paul Kagame). It was during the pre-genocidal period (1990-1994) that he forged his image as a military commander through the victories of the rebellion he led from Uganda to the capture of Kigali in June. 1994. After the genocide of the Tutsi, Paul Kagame participates in the formation of a government of national unity in which he becomes essential, combining the functions of Vice-President of the Republic of Rwanda and Minister of Defence.<br <br>\r\n\r\nRelations between the DRC and Rwanda are marked by several violent episodes. The Kabila regime, in power until December 2018, was installed in 1997 by the Alliance of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Congo (AFDL), a militia supported by Rwanda and Uganda. The twenty years that followed were marked by several clashes between Congolese rebel groups supported by Rwanda (the National Congress for the Defense of the People, part of which became the March 23 Movement – ​​M23 in 2012, a movement accused by the UN of having committed \"crimes against humanity\" in 2013) and Rwandan groups supported by the DRC (Democratic Liberation Forces of Rwanda - FDLR) in the Kivu territory.', 'Rwanda was established as a kingdom in the 15th century ruled by Tutsi kings before becoming part of the German colony of German East Africa in 1885. After Germany\'s defeat in World War I , the territory became part of the Belgian colony of Ruanda-Urundi in 1923.<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn 1091, Rwanda began to transform into a true nation under Gihanga I, the first king of Rwanda. (Banyarwanda).[insufficient source]. Rwanda becomes a kingdom at the head of which 25 kings succeed each other between 1081 and colonization.<br><br>\r\n\r\nGoverned by the Tutsi Nyiginya clan, the kingdom of Rwanda became the dominant kingdom from the middle of the 18th century. It spread through a process of conquest and assimilation and reached its peak during the reign of King Kigeli Rwabugiri (1853–1895). Rwabugiri extends the kingdom to the west and north, and launches administrative reforms which create a gap between the Hutu and Tutsi populations. These include uburetwa, a system of forced labor that Hutus must perform to regain access to land that had been confiscated from them, and ubuhake, under which Tutsi bosses surrender cattle to Hutu or Tutsi clients in exchange for economic and personal services.', 'uploads/lova42.jpg', 'The traditional Rwandan culture is linked to that of the populations of Africa of the Great Lakes. The structure of ancestral royalty impressed the first settlers with its sophisticated organization, which they could not attribute to an African people. The traditional belief in a single God, Imana, sensitive to their condition, the oral stories, the language (Kinyarwanda) and the proverbs, the songs, the drums and the dance hold a great place in this culture strongly impregnated with the fights of the warriors and agricultural activities: animal husbandry, agriculture, hunting and gathering.', 'uploads/download (57).jpg'),
(79, 'Western Saraha', 'Western Sahara (Arabic: الصحراء الغربية) is a territory of 266,000 km2 in northwest Africa, bordered by the Moroccan province of Tarfaya to the north, Algeria to the northeast, Mauritania to the east and to the south, while its west coast overlooks the Atlantic. A non-autonomous territory according to the UN, this former Spanish colony has still not found a definitive legal status since the departure of the Spaniards in 1976.', 'ouest-sahara', 'The territory is claimed by both Morocco and the Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic (SADR), proclaimed by the Polisario Front in 1976. The latter is a movement whose objective is the total independence of Western Sahara, a claim supported by Algeria. Having become a global issue illustrating the rivalry between Morocco and Algeria, the Saharan issue is still blocking the construction of the Arab Maghreb Union (AMU). The Polisario relies on an \"overwhelming consensus among the Sahrawis living in the territory in favor of independence and in opposition to integration with any neighboring country\", as described in a UN report in 1975. The Polisario Morocco bases its claim on the Madrid Accords and on the basis of past ties of allegiance between the Sahrawi tribes and the sultans of Morocco. Indeed, the Moroccan position highlights the fact that the territory belongs to different dynasties such as the Almoravids, from this same Sahara, and the Almohads, whose current monarchy is the heir, and qualifies the conflict as a relic of colonization.', 'The economy of Western Sahara reveals mineral wealth, the best known being (phosphate) but also metal as well as oil found in large pockets discovered and fully exploited by foreign companies in the Moroccan administered area.<br ><br>Most Swedish companies have already withdrawn from the territory, as well as some French, Spanish or British companies, others such as the Belgian Nettin or the Dutch ProFinance have already negotiated with the Sahrawi Republic their operating quotas and investment for the future of a liberated and self-managed Sahara.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe greatest wealth lies in the abundant phosphate mines that the territory has in Bucraa During the last period when Spain controlled the Sahara, became one of the first producers of this compound, through the company Fos Bucraa . Currently, the Moroccan government maintains a policy of secrecy and misinformation in its area of ​​control regarding this and other aspects of the economy, especially regarding the exploitation of wealth and raw materials. Thus it is currently prospecting for the presence of uranium for these nuclear power plants .', 'The Parliamentary Assembly remains concerned about the lack of significant progress in the search for a just and lasting political solution to the conflict over Western Sahara.\r\n\r\nThe constant efforts of the United Nations since 1965, and more particularly of the United Nations Mission for the Organization of a Referendum in Western Sahara since 1991, have reached a decisive phase qualified by observers as a “last chance”. The Assembly considers it essential to put an end to a particularly long conflict which has dramatic consequences for refugees, prisoners of war and political prisoners and is detrimental to the development of the Maghreb and to good relations between the countries of the region.\r\n\r\nThe Assembly fully supports United Nations Security Council Resolution 1541 of 29 April 2004, by which the Council reaffirmed its support for the Peace Plan for the self-determination of the people of Western Sahara as the optimal political solution and calls on Morocco to be conciliatory about this agreement.\r\n\r\nThe Assembly also calls on its member states to encourage by appropriate means the parties concerned to work together with the United Nations to ensure that the Peace Plan is rapidly accepted and implemented.', 'The history of Western Sahara is that of a desert territory populated by nomadic tribes, which has never been organized into a nation-state. It is closely linked to that of its neighbours, Morocco, Mauritania and Algeria.<br><br>The history of Western Sahara is that of a desert territory populated by nomadic tribes, which has never been organized into a nation-state. It is intimately linked to that of its neighbours, Morocco, Mauritania and Algeria. After a few unsuccessful attempts in the 15th century, the Spaniards made it a colony between 1884 and 1975. Following the disengagement of Spain in 1975 which abandoned this territory without proceeding to the referendum of the Sahrawi people for which it was mandated by the UN , the territory was militarily invaded and annexed by Morocco and Mauritania; the Polisario Front, an independence movement, undertakes an armed struggle. Western Sahara is today a non-autonomous territory according to the United Nations, claimed by the Kingdom of Morocco (which controls about 80%) and the Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic (which controls about 20%); its final status remains pending since the 1991 ceasefire.<br><br>\r\n\r\nBetween -5000 and -2000, the territory of Western Sahara is a wooded savannah with a rich biodiversity, attested by fossil remains and rock art, including ostriches, gazelles, cattle, elephants, giraffes, hippos or crocodiles, from which the first inhabitants derived their subsistence, as evidenced by rock or parietal art. Among these nomadic agro-pastoral peoples, anthropologists working on artefacts, prehistorians studying bones and linguists listing toponyms believe they have identified Bafours, a black people, and Berbers, mainly Sanhadja.', 'uploads/lova43.jpg', 'The people of Western Sahara speak the Ḥassānīya dialect of Arabic, also spoken in northern Mauritania, and Spanish. They are of mixed Arab, African (including Berber descent), many consider themselves to be Arab. Most claim that they descend from the tribe called Beni Hassan, an Arab tribe, who immigrated to the Western Saharan desert in the 14th century. The Sahrawis are Muslims of the Sunni sect and the Maliki law school. Their interpretation of Islam has traditionally being quite liberal and adapted to nomad life (i.e. generally functioning without mosques).\r\n\r\nThe clan- and tribe-based society underwent a massive social upheaval in 1975, when a large portion of the population fled fighting in the country and settled in the refugee camps of Tindouf, Algeria, breaking up families and clans. The Polisario Front, which runs the camps, has attempted to modernize their society, placing a public emphasis on education, the eradication of tribalism and the emancipation of women. The role of women in camps was enhanced by their shouldering of the main responsibility for the camps and government bureaucracy during the war years, as virtually the entire male population was enrolled in the Polisario army.', 'uploads/download (58).jpg'),
(80, 'Senegal', 'Senegal, officially the Republic of Senegal, is a country in West Africa, on the Atlantic Ocean coastline. Senegal is bordered by Mauritania to the north, Mali to the east, Guinea to the southeast and Guinea-Bissau to the southwest. Senegal nearly surrounds the Gambia, a country occupying a narrow sliver of land along the banks of the Gambia River, which separates Senegal\'s southern region of Casamance from the rest of the country. Senegal also shares a maritime border with Cape Verde. Senegal\'s economic and political capital is Dakar .', 'senegal', 'Senegal is notably the westernmost country in the mainland of the Old World, or Afro-Eurasia. It owes its name to the Senegal River, which borders it to the east and north. The climate is typically Sahelian, though there is a rainy season. Senegal covers a land area of almost 197,000 square kilometres (76,000 sq mi) and has a population of around 17 million. The state is a unitary presidential republic; since the country\'s foundation in 1960, it has been recognized as one of the most stable countries on the African continent.\r\n\r\nThe state was formed as part of the independence of French West Africa from French colonial rule. Because of this history, French is the official language, but it is understood by only a minority of the population. Over 30 languages are spoken in Senegal, and Wolof is the most widely spoken one, with 80% of the population speaking it as a first or second language, acting as Senegal\'s lingua franca alongside French. Like other post-colonial African states, the country includes a wide mix of ethnic and linguistic communities, with the largest being the Wolof, Fula, and Serer people. Senegalese people are predominantly Muslim.', 'Overall, economic activity is expected to rise by 5.0% in 2021 against 1.5% in 2020. This renewed dynamism is linked to the strong recovery in economic activity in the secondary sector (+8 ,8%).<br><br>The global health crisis has interrupted a trend of strong growth (6% on average between 2014 and 2019, but only 1.5% in 2020) and development progress in Senegal . In 2021, the Senegalese economy returned to its growth trajectory, at 6.1%, a dynamic supported by industrial production, services and retail trade. The resumption of economic activity is, however, accompanied by a widening of the public deficit (6.5% in 2022) and the country\'s debt estimated at 75% of GDP (i.e. above community standards of 3% and 70% respectively), in connection with the increase in expenditure linked in particular to the response to the health crisis and economic recovery. In 2022, the Senegalese economy will also have been strongly affected by the impact linked to the war in Ukraine (inflation, increase in the public deficit linked to the increase in subsidies, etc.). The expected arrival of hydrocarbons at the end of 2023 or 2024 nevertheless gives favorable medium-term prospects for Senegal.', 'Senegal is a republic with a multiparty presidential regime where the President exercises the office of Head of State and the Prime Minister, the function of Head of Government. Executive power is in the hands of the president while legislative power is shared between the government and parliament. The judiciary is independent of the first two. Senegal is one of the few countries in Africa to have never experienced a coup. Léopold Senghor, the first president after independence, abdicated in favor of his prime minister, Abdou Diouf, in 1981. The current president, Macky Sall, was democratically elected in March 2012.', 'The history of Senegal – before the country gained its independence in 1960 – is first and foremost part of that of larger entities such as, successively, the Sahara, Sudan, Senegambia or West Africa. French (AOF), before being associated in contemporary times with that of the neighboring states of the African Sahel. <br><br>As for many other countries on the African continent, the writing of this history comes up against multiple difficulties, both methodological and ideological.\r\n\r\nThe commentaries attributed to certain ancient explorers, the manuscripts of Arab travelers constitute the first known testimonies. It is from the fifteenth century that we have European sources – narrations, compilations or archival documents – whose purpose was generally not historical at the start: the Chevalier de Boufflers describes his exile to Madame de Sabran , the naturalist Adanson details the flora and fauna of the country, the director of the Compagnie du Sénégal Durand recounts the adventures of his expedition and the Abbé Boilat, in his Senegalese Sketches, thinks above all of the evangelization of the region.', 'uploads/lova45.jpg', 'The culture of Senegal, in West Africa, first refers to the cultural practices of its 17,000,000 inhabitants in the early 2020s.\r\n\r\nFrom the most isolated villages to the trendy places of Dakar the capital, Senegalese culture is characterized in particular by its taste for traditional sports, music, dance, clothing, the creative and ingenious work of any material at hand, the moments of conviviality linked to meals and celebrations, without forgetting – from the palaver tree to mobile phones – an undeniable attraction for exchange and oral communication.<br><br> The Senegalese are Muslims in their very great majority (more than 95%). Christianity (5%) – generally Catholicism – is practiced among the Serers, Diolas and Manjaques. Traditional beliefs nevertheless persist, through practices such as ndut or boukout.', 'uploads/download (40).jpg'),
(81, 'Sierra-Leone', 'Sierra Leone, in long form the Republic of Sierra Leone (in English: Republic of Sierra Leone and in Krio language: Salone), is a state in West Africa, with an area of ​​71,740 km2, populated by about 8 million inhabitants. It is located between Guinea (to the northwest and east-northeast) and Liberia (to the southeast) and is bordered to the west-southwest by the Atlantic Ocean.', 'sierra-leone', 'In 1808, the United Kingdom began to colonize the territory. The country gained independence as a Commonwealth realm in 1961 as the Dominion of Sierra Leone. In 1971, Prime Minister Siaka Stevens became president by transforming the country into a presidential republic before declaring the All People\'s Congress (APC) a single party in 1978. In 1985, Joseph Saidu Momoh succeeded him and introduced a multiparty system in 1991. A brutal civil war broke out that year between the government and the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) rebels. During the war, the country experienced three coups and two periods of military rule. The war ended in 2002 after a British military intervention leading to the final defeat of the RUF. Since then, the country has remained relatively stable. Governed by civilian rule since 1998, the two main political parties are the APC and the Sierra Leone People\'s Party (SLPP).<br><br>\r\n\r\nSierra Leone is part of ECOWAS. This country is one of the poorest on the planet. With a Human Development Index (HDI) of 0.477 in 2021, it ranks 181st globally.\r\n\r\nEnglish is the official language, and Krio, a creole based on English, serves as a common language between the different ethnic groups of the country. The two main religions practiced are Islam (78%) and Christianity (21%).', 'The Covid-19 pandemic has had a strong impact on the budget balance, but could fall below the 3% target as early as 2024 according to the IMF. In 2020-2021, revenues were impacted by the weakening of economic activity as well as increased difficulties in revenue collection, while in parallel the response and recovery measures led to a significant increase in expenditure. As a result, the budget deficit stood at 7.4% of GDP (excluding iron ore) in 2021 (against 5.8% in 2020 and 3.1% in 2019 respectively). While the IMF anticipated a decrease in the deficit from 2022, it finally deteriorated to 10.9% of GDP, mainly due to under-budgeting and discretionary measures (transfers in response to the rising energy prices); through a reduction in excise duty rates; and the decline in timber exports following their ban under the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES). The fiscal deficit is projected for the year 2023 at 5.6% of GDP.<br><br>According to the latest IMF Debt Sustainability Analysis (May 2023), the country is at high but sustainable risk of debt distress . Indeed, the outstanding public debt reached 98.9% of GDP in 2022 while it was 48.6% on average over the period 2010-2018. According to the IMF, public debt is sustainable assuming fiscal adjustment efforts and continued recourse to concessional financing and grants, but the risk of over-indebtedness is increasing. In addition, Sierra Leone was able to benefit in 2020 and 2021 from the debt service suspension initiative (ISSD) as well as from the debt relief measure put in place by the IMF (CCRT).', 'The political scene in Sierra Leone is dominated by two major parties, the All People\'s Congress (APC) and the Sierra Leone People\'s Party (SLPP), which have alternately held power since the end of the civil war (2002).\r\n\r\nAt the end of the second term of President Ernest Bai Koroma (APC), Sierra Leoneans elected the opposition candidate, Julius Maada Bio, to the highest office. The latter won, during the second round of the presidential election held on March 31, 2018, with 51.8% of the vote, against the government candidate, Samura Kamara (APC, 48.2% ).<br><br>Sierra Leone has been a member of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) since its inception in 1975. It also belongs, alongside Liberia, Guinea and Côte d\'Ivoire, to the Mano River Union (MRU) created in 1973 to promote economic integration. The election of Alpha Condé to the Guinean presidency has helped to strengthen ties between these two countries, despite a territorial dispute over Yenga hill.', 'The territory of present-day Sierra Leone was the refuge of many peoples, such as the Kissis, the Sherbros and the Krims, during the political conflicts of the savannah.\r\n\r\nIn the 15th century, driving back the first occupants, Mandinka peoples settled there, the Mendés on the eastern coast, the Temnes towards the border of present-day Liberia and the Soussous in the center.\r\n\r\nIn 1460, the Portuguese explorer Pedro de Sintra gave the name of Serra Leoa (later renamed \"Sierra Leone\" probably by mistake due to a confusion between Latin languages ​​because Sierra is in Spanish and Leone in Italian, literally the \"mountain du lion\") to the peninsula where the capital Freetown would later be.\r\n\r\nIn the 16th century, the slave trade really began. Europeans, with the participation of the coastal populations, begin the triangular trade in the country, in settlements such as Lomboko. <br><br> In 1787, the British bought the site where the capital Freetown would be built. The first wave of settlement is made up of 400 blacks from London. Then there is added, through the Sierra Leone Company, a part of the black loyalists, slaves, freed in return for their engagement in the British camp during the war of independence of the United States. After passing through Nova Scotia or London, the majority of them are sent to Freetown. The settlement was completed by maroon Negroes from Jamaica (reconquered in 1796) deported to Nova Scotia and a growing number of recaptives, Blacks torn by British cruisers from smuggled slave ships. Sierra Leone became the first British colony in West Africa in 1792 and, in 1794, the post of governor was given to Zachary Macaulay. The colony, whose foundation remains fragile, must face the assault of the French revolutionary troops.', 'uploads/lova47.jpg', 'The culture of Sierra Leone is the set of observable cultural practices of its approximately 7,500,000 inhabitants in 2022. It has some similarities with that of its immediate neighbors, Guinea and Liberia, other small coastal states with a hinterland. mountainous and a humid tropical climate. Sierra Leone is also marked by the slave trade, its colonial past within British West Africa and, more recently, by the civil war which raged there between 1991 and 2002. In the meantime (2012), the country has returned to the path of democracy and political change, even if its human development index (HDI) remains among the lowest (180th out of 187 in 2011).', 'uploads/download (60).jpg'),
(82, 'Somalia', 'Somalia, in long form the Federal Republic of Somalia (in Somali Soomaaliya and Jamhuuriyadda Federaalka Soomaaliya; in Arabic الصومال (aṣ-Ṣūmāl) and جمهورية الصومال الفدرالية (J umhūriyyat aṣ-Ṣūmāl al-Fideraaliya)), is a country located in eastern end of the Horn of Africa, in the Gulf of Aden. The country has direct borders with three neighboring countries: Djibouti to the northwest, Ethiopia to the west and Kenya to the southwest.', 'somalia', 'An important site of trade in antiquity, the country is among the most likely sites in the Land of Punt. Between the Middle Ages and the late 19th century, the territory was home to several powerful Somali sultanates including the Ajuran Sultanate, Adal Sultanate, Geledi Sultanate and Isaaq Sultanate. The territory was subsequently divided by the United Kingdom and Italy, which partitioned it into two colonies: Italian Somalia to the south and British Somalia to the north.\r\n\r\nAfter the Second World War, the two colonies were unified and the Somali Republic gained its independence in 1960. In 1969, Mohamed Siad Barre seized power in a coup and imposed a communist dictatorship. His regime was overthrown in 1991 by the Somali revolution, which also saw the unilaterally declared independence of Somaliland in the territory of the former British colony, although it was still not recognized by the international community. In the following decades, Somalia was labeled as a failed state due to the prolonged lack of a permanent central government authority, the continuation of the civil war and the rise of several warlords and radical armed groups including Harakat al-Shabab al-Mujahideen. A series of transitional governments were followed by the establishment of the Federal Government of Somalia in 2012 which reformed the country as a federation, after insurgents lost most of the territory they controlled.\r\n\r\nSomalis are the dominant ethnic group, and Sunni Islam is the dominant religion. The official languages ​​are Somali and Arabic.', 'Somalia balanced its budget in 2022, in line with its completion point commitments under the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) initiative, from a deficit of 1.1% of GDP in 2021 , which was funded by the 2021 Special Drawing Rights Allocation (USD 203 million,...<br><br>Somalia\'s economy, despite civil war since the 1990s, relies mainly on livestock farming and, in a more complementary way, on the exploitation of salt mines.Oil is coveted by large companies which negotiate with the governments in place.\r\n\r\nDue to a lack of official statistics and the ongoing civil war, it is difficult to assess the size and growth of the economy. In 1994, the CIA estimated GDP at $3.3 billion. In 2001, it was estimated at $4.1 billion. In 2009, the CIA estimates that the GDP was 5.731 billion dollars, with a growth rate of 2.6%. In 2003, the World Bank affirmed that the trade, transport, animal husbandry, agriculture and fishing sectors have experienced significant growth.', 'Somalia became an independent state on July 1, 1960, resulting from the union of British Somalia (independent from Great Britain since June 26, 1960) and Italian Somalia (then under United Nations trusteeship). The President of the Republic is the Head of State and the Prime Minister assumes the function of Head of Government. Legislative power is shared between the government and parliament.<br><br>After the fall of the Somali Democratic Republic regime led by General Mohamed Siad Barre, defeated by the United Somali Congress (CSU) on January 27 1991, various military factions took control of the country. The ensuing chaos prompted a US-led international intervention, UNITAF. This operation was followed by the United Nations Mission in Somalia, which ended in failure in 1994. Since 1991, all attempts at national reconciliation have failed and various groups and factions have tried to extend their territorial hold and regularly engage in conflicts. In 1997, Mohamed Ibrahim Egal was elected by his partisans President of the Republic of Somaliland, that is to say the provinces of the North-West. In 1998, the region of Puntland, in the northeast, declared itself autonomous with Abdullahi Yusuf Ahmed as president and Garowe as capital. Puntland affirmed its will to remain autonomous until the setting up of a federation of Somalia. Abdullah Yusuf ruled the region until mid-2001, when Colonel Jama Ali Jama succeeded him in November. Forces still loyal to Abdullah Yusuf, who had retreated to Galkayo, then attacked Garowe, resulting in the de facto partition of Puntland.', 'The history of Somalia can be, like other African states, divided into pre-colonial, colonial and post-colonial period. The latter is marked by troubles that have brought down Somali institutions.\r\n\r\nVestiges of the prehistoric era exist for example on the sites of Dhambalin, Gaanlibah, Karinhegane and especially Laas Geel, and by very many cairns. Traces of human civilization have been discovered in particular in Buur Heybe, in southern Somalia. To the north, cave paintings have been found at Karinhegane, Laas Geel as well as Dhambalin and other sites in the Togdheer region3.\r\n\r\nThe Sanaag region has many interesting archaeological sites, still little explored, including cairns, near Armale, Dabhan, Damala (Somalia), El Ayo, El Buh, Erigavo, Haylan, Hingalol, Karinhegane, Laako, Las Khorey, Macajulayn, Maydh, Neis, Qa\'ableh, Qombo\'ul, Salweyn, Yubbe, but also Gudmo Biyo Cas, Heis, Gelweita, El Ayo.\r\n\r\nThe ruined medieval town of Maduna is the most notable site (comparable to Amud, Yubbe and Abasa (Awdal) in the Awdal region), and probably from the time of the Sultanate of Adal.', 'uploads/lova48.jpg', 'The culture of Somalia, a vast country in the Horn of Africa, primarily refers to the observable cultural practices of its 11,000,000 people.<br><br>In addition, the Somali community includes many and significant Muslim personalities. These figures have greatly contributed to shaping the theory and practice of Islam in the Horn of Africa, the Arabian Peninsula and far beyond. Among these Muslim scholars is the 14th century Somali theologian and jurist Uthman Ibn Ali Zayla\'i, who wrote a unique text of the highest authority on the Hanafi school. The book consists of four volumes. The title of the work is al-Haqa\'iq li Sharh Tabayin Kanz al-Daqa\'iq (the title of the work in Arabic is to be verified).\r\n\r\nThe Islamic Courts Union has a current effective presence.The cultural diffusion of Somali commercial enterprise can be detected in its exotic cuisine, which contains Southeast Asian influences. Due to the Somali people\'s foremost ingenuity and facility with poetry, Somalia has often been referred to as a \"Nation of Poets\" and a \"Nation of Bards\", as, for example, by the Canadian novelist Margaret Laurence.[3] Somalis have a story-telling tradition.\r\n\r\nAccording to Canadian novelist and scholar Margaret Laurence, who originally coined the term \"Nation of Poets\" to describe the Somali Peninsular, the Eidagale clan were viewed as \"the recognized experts in the composition of poetry\" by their fellow Somali contemporaries:', 'uploads/download (61).jpg'),
(83, 'Sudan', 'Sudan (pronounced in French: /sudɑ̃/5; in Arabic: السودان as-Sūdān), in long form the Republic of Sudan (جمهورية السودان Jumhūrīyat as-Sūdān), is a country in Northeast Africa.\r\n\r\nSudan is bordered by Libya to the northwest, Egypt to the north, the Red Sea to the east-northeast, Eritrea to the east, Ethiopia to the east-southeast, South Sudan to the south, the Central African Republic to the southwest and Chad to the west. The official languages ​​of the country are Arabic and English since 2005 .', 'sudan', 'Its capital is Khartoum and its largest city is Omdurman.\r\n\r\nIts history has known the Kingdom of Kerma (circa 2500-1500 BC), the Egyptian New Kingdom (circa 1500 -1070 BC) and the Kingdom of Kush (circa 785 -350 AD). . After the fall of Kush, the Nubians formed the three Christian kingdoms of Nobatia, Makuria and Alodia. Between the 14th and 15th centuries, most of Sudan was gradually colonized by Arab nomads. From the 16th to the 19th century, central and eastern Sudan were dominated by the sultanate of Sennar, while Darfur ruled the west and the Ottomans the east. After the 1820s, under the Turkish-Egyptian rule of Sudan, the practice of the slave trade became entrenched in a north-south axis. From the 19th century, the whole of Sudan was conquered by the Egyptians under the dynasty of Mehemet Ali. Religious and nationalist fervor resulted in the Mahdist uprising, in which the Mahdist forces were eventually defeated by a joint Egyptian-British military force. In 1899, under British pressure, Egypt agreed to share sovereignty over Sudan with the United Kingdom under a condominium. The Egyptian Revolution of 1952 overthrew the monarchy and demanded the withdrawal of British forces from all of Egypt and Sudan. Muhammad Naguib, one of the two co-leaders of the revolution and first president of Egypt made the independence of Sudan a priority of the revolutionary government. The following year, under Egyptian and Sudanese pressure, the UK granted Egypt\'s request that the two governments end their shared sovereignty over Sudan and grant it independence. On January 1, 1956, Sudan was declared an independent state.', 'Economic Outlook in Sudan. GDP grew by 0.7% in 2022 after contracting by 1.9% in 2021 due to political instability and fallout from the Russian invasion of Ukraine.<br><br>The Sudan, which has just experienced a coup, has one of the poorest economies in the world. It has suffered many shocks over the past decade: the secession of the South in 2011 which deprived Khartoum of most of its oil-related resources, a collapse in national wealth and foreign exchange reserves as well as a prices of essential goods. The country had received significant international aid in the spring of 2021.', 'The country remains without a functioning government after the military seized power on October 25, 2021 and the resignation of the prime minister on January 2, 2022. Frequent protests continue to take place in several cities, including Khartoum and Omdurman.<br> <br>Sudan is a republic with a presidential system. The head of state has been Abdel Fattah Abdelrahmane al-Burhan since April 12, 2019. <br> <br>From 1983 to 1997, the country was divided into five regions in the north and three in the south, each headed by a military governor. Regional parliaments were suspended after the military coup of April 6, 1985. The Revolutionary Council was abolished in 1996 and the ruling National Islamic Front was renamed the National Congress. After 1997, regional administrative structures were reformed to a 26-state system. The members of the regional executives are appointed by the president. The state budget is entirely dependent on the central power in Khartoum.\r\n\r\nAccording to the provisional constitution which was adopted in 1986, the country has a legislative assembly comprising 301 seats. The president is officially the head of state but his functions are essentially representative. Executive power is in fact held by the Premier elected by the Legislative Assembly.', 'The history of Sudan is marked by the military and cultural influence of its neighbors, including Egypt, the Arabian Peninsula, Ethiopia, the two Congos, Republic of Congo and Democratic Republic of Congo and Chad, as well as, more recently the United Kingdom and the United States. Its territory intersects with that of several ancient kingdoms including the kingdom of Kush, those of Darfur and Nubia.<br><br>Archaeological excavations carried out on the Nile upstream of Aswan have confirmed the human occupation of the valley from the Paleolithic, more than 60,000 years ago, mainly around Khashm El Girba and Khor Musa, before 8000 BC, but also Afad 23 and Djebel Sahaba.\r\n\r\nIn the eighth millennium BC. BC, Mesolithic (8000-5000), then Neolithic (4900-3300) peoples settled there in fortified brick villages, practicing agriculture and livestock: Ad-Damir, Abu Darbein, Wadi Howar, Shaqadud, then Kadero, esh-Shaheinab, Kadruka, Kerma.\r\n\r\nThe predynastic societies of Nubia and Upper Egypt were ethnically and culturally very close, and evolved in parallel to Pharaonic kingdoms around -3300, in the Neolithic period. Lower Nubia then seems to have been emptied of its population as part of a forced process of Egyptianization and unification of the Nile Valley by the kingdoms established to the north.\r\n\r\nThe rock site of Geddi-Sabu remains an exception.', 'uploads/lova49.jpg', 'The culture of Sudan is intended to be an overview of the multitude of observable cultural practices of the 30,000,000 inhabitants of the two Sudans.<br><br>Lifestyle. Traditionally, the main cleavage in the ways of life in Sudan opposes pastoral nomads and sedentary farmers. Today, if this differentiation persists in most peripheral regions, the urban/rural opposition seems increasingly relevant.', 'uploads/download (62).jpg'),
(84, 'Southern Sudan', 'South Sudan, common name of the official form Republic of South Sudan (in English: South Sudan and Republic of South Sudan), is a federal state in East Africa, without access to the sea and independent of Sudan since July 9, 2011, whose capital and largest city is Juba.', 'suthern-sudan', 'Following the self-determination referendum held from January 9 to 15, 2011, South Sudan seceded from the Republic of Sudan on July 9, 2011. Despite South Sudan\'s membership of the United Nations (UN ), territorial disputes remain over the final and official course of the Sudanese-South Sudanese border.<br><br>\r\n\r\nBetween 2013 and 2020, this country experienced a particularly deadly and bloody civil war between the supporters of the President of the Republic, Salva Kiir, and those of the Vice-President of the Republic, Riek Machar.<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn 2021, South Sudan is ranked last country in the world in terms of human development index (HDI) by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), which assigns it an HDI of 0.385, in almost constant decline. since 2011.', 'After decades of conflict, South Sudan became an independent state in 2011, but has suffered from social unrest and an economic crisis. The peace agreement signed in September 2018 should restore lasting social peace and economic stability. However, the economy has been hit hard by the global Covid-19 pandemic, locust invasions, falling oil prices and three consecutive years of major flooding. After contracting to -6.6% in 2020, GDP growth rebounded to 5.3% in 2021, boosted by rising oil prices. According to IMF estimates, economic growth is expected to accelerate to 6.5% in 2022 before declining to 5.6% in 2023.<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn 2021, despite the continuing Covid-19 crisis and another year of flooding, South Sudan\'s economy started to recover, supported by rising oil prices. The authorities have successfully implemented a reform program aimed at restoring macroeconomic stability by strengthening fiscal discipline, removing distortions in the foreign exchange market and improving transparency (IMF). The value of the South Sudanese pound has stabilized and the gap between parallel and official rates has been eliminated (IMF). From an estimated budget deficit of 7% of GDP for the 2020/21 financial year, a surplus of 2.6% of GDP is expected for the 2021/22 financial year, mainly due to the recovery of oil revenues and the reduction payments from the Transitional Financial Arrangement in Sudan (IMF). According to IMF estimates, public debt fell from around 35.8% of GDP in 2020 to 64.4% of GDP in 2021.', 'Politics in South Sudan refers to the system of government, people, organizations and electoral consultations of the Republic of South Sudan, a country in East Africa.<br><br> After several decades of civil war which was one of the longest and deadliest wars of the 20th century (the First Sudanese Civil War and the Second Sudanese Civil War), between the Sudanese government and army, mainly Muslim and Arab and from the North, and the rebels black Christians from the SPLA and animists from the South, who demanded greater regional autonomy, a peace agreement, known as the Naivasha Accord was signed on January 9, 2005 in Naivasha, Kenya, giving autonomy to Sudan from South as part of the Republic of Sudan.<br><br>\r\n\r\nJohn Garang, the former rebel leader of the Sudanese People\'s Liberation Army, then became, on July 9, president of the autonomous government of South Sudan and first vice-president of the Republic of Sudan. A first constitution for the autonomous region was adopted in December 2005.<br><br>\r\n\r\nOn July 30, 2005, John Garang died in a helicopter crash in Uganda, and his vice-president, Salva Kiir Mayardit, became the second president of the autonomous government of South Sudan and first vice-president of the Republic of Sudan. Riek Machar becomes Vice President of South Sudan on August 11.<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn December 2019, Salva Kiir and Riek Machar agreed to form a government of national unity at the end of February 20203.', 'The History of South Sudan includes the history of the territory of present-day South Sudan and the peoples who inhabit it. <br><br>\r\n\r\nThere is little documentation of the region\'s history, prior to the start of Turkish-Egyptian rule over Sudan in the early 1820s and its expansion southward during the 19th century.<br><br>\r\n\r\nPrior to this dominance, information is largely based on oral history. According to these traditions, the peoples of Nilotic languages ​​including the Dinkas, Nuers, Shilluks, and other Nilo-Saharan tribes including the Ngbandi, Ngbaka, Mamvu, Lendu, Logo, Moru-Mangbetu, etc. settle in South Sudan around the tenth century, precisely in the White Nile region, according to the estimates of Samuel Baker who was the governor of one of the provinces of Sudan from the pre-colonial era assimilating earlier populations Omotics, of Afro-Asiatic languages.<br><br>\r\n\r\nDuring the period from the 15th century to the 19th century, tribal migrations, largely from the Bahr el Ghazal region, and due to progressive desertification, carried these peoples to their modern locations.', 'uploads/lova50.jpg', 'This article discusses different aspects of the culture of South Sudan (about 13,000,000 inhabitants in 2017).<br><br>South Sudan is made up of more than 200 different ethnic groups speaking as many languages ​​and dialects.', 'uploads/download (64).jpg');
