(85, 'Tanzania', 'Tanzania, in long form the United Republic of Tanzania (in Swahili: Tanzania /tanzaˈni.a/ and Jamhuri ya Muungano wa Tanzania; in English: Tanzania and United Republic of Tanzania), is a country in East Africa located on the edge of the Indian Ocean, in the tropical part of the southern hemisphere.', 'tanzania', 'It is surrounded to the north by Kenya and Uganda, to the west by Rwanda, Burundi and the Democratic Republic of Congo, to the southwest by Zambia and Malawi and to the south by Mozambique.\r\n\r\nThe country covers 945,087 km2 and has 58.5 million inhabitants in 2018, mainly Bantu. Its capital is Dodoma, located inland, but the main economic center is the former capital Dar es Salam, located on the coast. The official languages ​​are Swahili and English, but Arabic is also spoken, particularly on the islands of Zanzibar and Pemba.\r\n\r\nPresent-day Tanzania was born from the union of Tanganyika and Zanzibar on April 26, 1964, shortly after their respective independence from the United Kingdom. It has been a member of the Commonwealth since the end of 1961 and of the United Nations since December 14, 1961. In 1977, the Chama cha Mapinduzi (CCM) was founded as a single party. Although the multiparty system was established in 1992, the CCM remains the dominant party.', 'In 2021, the country\'s real GDP grew by 4.9% to reach USD 70.28 billion according to the Bank of Tanzania; while in 2022, growth was estimated at 4.5%, supported by public and private investment (mainly in infrastructure projects).<br><br>Tanzania\'s economy is, in many ways, respects, typical of a developing country: essentially centered on agriculture and the mining industry, it has an almost non-existent and uncompetitive industrial base. Tourism is a significant and growing source of foreign currency.\r\n\r\nBut the country is also very different from most African countries, with an Arab and Persian merchant presence on its coasts dating back to the first centuries of the common era, and a city, Zanzibar, which for several hundred years would dominate the economy of the whole region. A hub for the trade in gold, ivory and slaves, at the interface of the African, Arab and Indian worlds, its hinterland extends to Africa from the Great Lakes, nearly 1,000 km from distance. The arrival of Europeans in the wake of Vasco da Gama in the 15th century did not immediately call this domination into question, as they even offered new markets for a popular local commodity, cloves.', 'The United Republic of Tanzania has been a stable country since independence from Tanganyika in 1961 (mainland of Tanzania, which later merged with the Zanzibar archipelago in 1964). The foundations of the modern state were laid by the father of independence, Julius Nyerere: national unity, centralization of power, solid institutions, economic socialism, secularism.<br><br>Country deemed stable, Tanzania does not has known only one war since its independence (against Uganda, between 1978 and 1979). It still draws continental prestige from Julius Nyerere\'s pan-African support for African liberation movements. President Kikwete was also part of the tradition of Nyerere (multilateralism, pan-Africanism, Third Worldism). After a period of relative isolationism under the presidency of J. Magufuli, President Samia Suluhu Hassan is doing more to put Tanzanian diplomacy back on the international scene. The current priorities of Tanzanian diplomacy were set by the former Minister of Foreign Affairs, P. Kabudi: anti-colonialism, African sovereignty and national unity. These publicly defended values ​​are part of the glorification of the heritage of African socialism and of Tanzania\'s contribution to the emancipation of the continent.', 'Tanzania is a presidential multi-party federal republic born on April 26, 1964 from the merger of Tanganyika and Zanzibar, which had gained independence respectively on December 9, 1961 and December 10, 1963 after German and then British colonization.<br><br><br> >The area is believed to have been originally inhabited by rattle-speaking populations of the Khoisan language family, similar to the San and Khoikhoi of South Africa. Although traces of these original populations remain, most were displaced by Bantus migrating from the west and south and by Nilotes and other peoples from the north. The Bantus are believed to have arrived in the region as early as the 5th or 4th century BC. J.-C.\r\n\r\nThe Nilotics and par-Nilotics arrived in successive waves, the first at the beginning of the 1st millennium BC. J.-C. .\r\n\r\nSome of these African populations had reached a high level of organization and controlled large territories when European explorers and missionaries penetrated the interior of the country from the beginning of the 19th century.', 'uploads/lova51.jpg', 'With its large natural spaces, the abundance of wild animals and the richness of its vegetation, one would almost forget that Tanzania is also a country with incredibly rich and varied cultures. With more than a hundred ethnic groups scattered all over its territory, many of whom still live according to their ancestral traditions, the Tanzanian population and culture is an immense cultural mosaic.\r\n\r\nImmerse yourself in Tanzanian culture as you watch superb dance and music performances, visit grand architectural landmarks and learn about local handicrafts. Whether you are passionate about history, literature or authentic encounters, you will find all the happiness possible there.', 'uploads/download (65).jpg'),
(86, 'Chad', 'Chad (in Arabic: تشاد, Tšād), in long form the Republic of Chad (in Arabic: جمهورية تشاد, Jumhūriyyat Tšād), is a country in Central Africa, without access to the sea, bordering Libya in the north, from Sudan to the east, from the Central African Republic (or Centrafrique) to the south, from Niger to the west, from Nigeria to the west-southwest and from Cameroon to the south-southwest. Its capital, N\'Djamena, is also its most populous city.', 'chad', 'Geographically and culturally, Chad is a crossing point between North Africa and sub-Saharan Africa. Covering an area of ​​1,284,000 km2, it is the fifth largest country in Africa (after Algeria, the Democratic Republic of Congo, Sudan and Libya) and the twenty-first great in the world. With approximately 17.6 million inhabitants, it is the twenty-fourth most populous country in Africa and the sixty-ninth most populous country in the world. Chad is divided into three major geographical areas: from north to south, there is successively a desert region, a semi-arid space, then the Sudanese savannah. Lake Chad, which gives its name to the country, is its main body of water, and the highest point in the country is Emi Koussi, which rises to 3,415 m above sea level, an extinct volcano located in the north of the country and part of the Tibesti massif.\r\n\r\nThe official languages ​​of Chad are Arabic and French, and more than a hundred languages ​​are spoken on Chadian territory, which is home to more than 200 different ethnic groups. Chad is a secular country where religious freedom is guaranteed by law; Islam (55.3%) and Christianity (40.6%) are the two main religions practiced.', 'Chad\'s economy is largely dependent on oil production, which started in 2003 and allowed the country to experience a period of rapid growth until 2014 (average annual growth rate of 13.7%).<br> <br>Chad\'s economy is largely dependent on oil production, which began in 2003 and allowed the country to experience a period of rapid growth until 2014 (average annual growth rate of 13.7%). The non-oil primary sector mainly concerns livestock, the country\'s second export item, but also the cultivation of cereals, cotton, sesame and the collection of gum arabic, and brings together value chains with high development potential in Chad. The cotton sector has seen an upturn since the takeover, in 2018, of the public company CotonTchad by the Olam group. The manufacturing industry occupies a marginal place and is essentially based on the production of beer and soft drinks, the production of sugar, and the ginning of cotton and some cement works.', 'The situation in Chad has been tense since the attempted military coup in Niger on July 26, 2023. The border region with Niger could be particularly affected by any further deterioration in the political situation in Niger.<br><br> Chad\'s foreign policy is marked by security issues and by its link with France, which conquered the country in 1900 before it became a French colony in 1920. Chad became independent in 1960, but cooperation between the two French and Chadian governments remains important. France supported Idriss Déby Itno when he was elected in 1990 and intervened militarily on numerous occasions. On the death of the latter, the Élysée is saddened by the loss of a \"courageous friend\" while stressing the importance of a \"peaceful transition\" in Chad and its \"firm attachment to stability and territorial integrity” of the country.<br><br>\r\n\r\nChad is also a founding member of the African Union, a member of the Economic Community of Central African States and of the Organization of Islamic Cooperation.\r\n\r\nIn 1999, Chad became involved in the Second Congo War, supporting the Kinshasa government. Several thousand soldiers are sent by Idriss Déby to support Kabila\'s troops .', 'Considered a French protectorate from 1900, Chad was set up as a colony in 1920 within the framework of the AEF (French Equatorial Africa). Under the leadership of Governor Félix Éboué, it was the first French colony to join Free France in 1940.<br><br>Becoming an autonomous republic in 1958, Chad gained independence on August 11, 1960 under the presidency of François Tombalbaye. He soon had to face the revolt of the populations of the North, mostly Muslim, which led him to seek the help of French troops in 1968. After the assassination of Tombalbaye in 1975, power fell to General Félix Malloum, who had to give way in 1979 to the northerner Goukouni Oueddei, following the first battle of N\'Djamena. In 1980, the second battle of N\'Djamena allowed Goukouni Oueddei to oust his rival, Hissène Habré, with the decisive help of the troops of the Libyan Arab Jamahiriya of Muammar Gaddafi.\r\n\r\nAfter the failure of a proposed merger between Chad and Libya in 1981, Libyan troops withdrew under an agreement reached with the French government. In 1982, Goukouni Oueddei was overthrown in turn by Hissène Habré, who had to call on French troops the following year to contain a new Libyan invasion. In 1987, a counter-offensive by Chadian forces finally forced Libyan troops to evacuate the country, with the exception of the Aozou strip, which was not returned to Chad until 1994.', 'uploads/lova52.jpg', 'The different ethnic groups that make up Chad contribute to the richness of the country in terms of traditions. Thus, the natives place great importance on traditional music and dances.<br><br>The natural and cultural landscape of Chad is exceptional. Due to its diversity (lakes on the borders of the Sahara, reserves of endangered animals, fossiliferous sectors of the first hominids, parietal arts, Sao terracotta sculptures, iron production workshops, architecture, dances, theaters and traditional songs, colonial monuments, etc.), it definitely attests to the complex relationships between Man, his natural environment and his cultural choices. Research in the human sciences has brought this unique heritage to light, but much remains to be discovered, protected, conserved and enhanced. Far from being exhaustive, this article paints the portrait of a country sometimes little known, Chad, and of populations with a rich past and present. It also presents the tools and services in charge of the management and protection of this heritage.', 'uploads/download (66).jpg'),
(87, 'Togo', 'Togo, also called the Togolese Republic, is a country in West Africa, whose population is estimated in 2022 at around 8.095 million inhabitants for a density of 152 inhabitants/km2. Togo takes its name from the current Togo city .', 'togo', 'As one of the smallest continental African states, Togo covers an area of ​​56,785 km2 and stretches about 700 km from north to south with a width not exceeding 150 km. Bordered to the north by Burkina Faso, to the south by the Gulf of Guinea, to the east by Benin and to the west by Ghana, Togo has a great diversity of landscapes: a sandy coast lined with coconut trees in the south , hills, green valleys, small mountains in the center of the country, arid plains and large savannahs in the north of the country.\r\n\r\nIn 1884, the territory was colonized as a German protectorate. During World War I, the protectorate was partitioned into two mandates between the United Kingdom in the west and France in the east in 1916. While the British mandate became part of what is now Ghana in 1956, the French colony obtained its independence in 1960 to become the modern country. Following two coups in 1963 and 1967, Gnassingbé Eyadéma became president of the country and set up a strongly authoritarian one-party dictatorship. Although the multiparty system was established in the early 1990s, he continued to hold power until his death in 2005. His son, Faure Gnassingbé succeeded him as president and remains in power to this day.', 'Togo belongs to ECOWAS, UEMOA (West African Economic and Monetary Union), OHADA (Organization for the Harmonization of Business Law in Africa) and the Franc Zone. The country is a member of the WTO and has also ratified the agreement establishing the AfCFTA (African Continental Free Trade Area).\r\n\r\nThe return of international donors, from 2007, enabled the revival of GDP growth. Driven by agricultural production, transport services linked to international trade and the positive impact of improved infrastructure on private economic activity, the country was able to achieve growth of 5.3% in 2019 (compared to 4.9% in 2018). As a result of the economic slowdown linked to COVID-19 and the weakening of demand from its partners, the country experienced its first year without growth in more than 15 years in 2020, but the World Bank nevertheless considers this episode to be temporary. and that Togo should return to growth in 2021.', 'The death of Étienne Gnassingbé Eyadéma in 2005 caused a political and institutional crisis, during which the army entrusted power to his son Faure Essozimna Gnassingbé. The latter won the April 2005 election, in a context of violence (500 dead) and was re-elected in 2010.\r\n\r\nThe political debate has partly focused, after the election of President Faure Gnassingbé for a third term in April 2015, on the question of institutional reforms. The opposition notably called for a return to the two-term limit and a two-round ballot. Between August and December 2017, large marches organized in the main cities of the country at the initiative of the Pan-African National Party (PNP) of Tikpi Atchadam, which was joined by historical opponents, in particular the National Alliance for Change (ANC), brought together tens of thousands of demonstrators. Tensions escalated in October and November and reached a peak with the death of two soldiers in the town of Sokodé.', 'The Bassar country in the center and north of Togo became, from the 8th century, one of the main regions of metallurgical production in West Africa. The remains of old furnaces and slag confirm the intensity of metallurgical activity for several centuries.<br><br>The history of Togo is marked by the presence of the Portuguese on the coast in the 15th century, with the installation of a counter in Saint-Georges-de-la-Mine (Elmina). German colony since 1884, Togoland is divided, after the First World War, into two parts: one part, the future Togo, is thus, in 1922, placed under mandate from France, while the other, British Togoland , placed under the supervision of Great Britain, is attached to the former British colony of the Gold-Coast (1821-1957), which became independent in 1957 under the name of Ghana, in reference to the former Empire of Ghana (350 -1250, approximately). The territory of French Togo gains its independence in 1960 .', 'uploads/lova53.jpg', 'Traditional African religions (33-51%) (32.43% in 2020): Yoruba religion, Gèlèdé; Animism; Fetishism, Market of fetishists (Lomé);<br><br>Togo is made up of several peoples or ethnic groups from various backgrounds. There has been a mixture of cultures, mores and customs in its history.', 'uploads/download (67).jpg'),
(88, 'Tunisia', 'Tunisia (Arabic: تونس, tūnis Listen?, [ˈtuːnɪs]), in long form the Republic of Tunisia (Arabic: الجمهورية التونسية, al-jumhūriyya at-tūnisiyya Listen?) is an Arabic-speaking and predominantly Muslim state in Africa sovereign North since 1956.\r\n\r\nBordered to the north and east by the Mediterranean Sea (1,566 km of coastline), to the west by Algeria with 965 km of common border and to the southeast by Libya with 459 km of border, its capital Tunis is located in the northeast of the country, at the bottom of the gulf of the same name. More than 30% of the territory\'s surface is occupied by the Sahara Desert, the rest being made up of mountainous regions and fertile plains.', 'tunisie', 'The territory of present-day Tunisia is home to the Capsian culture, a Mesolithic culture that lasted from 10,000 to 6,000 BC and to which the city of Gafsa gave its name. It is also the cradle of the Carthaginian civilization which reached its peak in the 3rd century BC. BC, before becoming part of the Kingdom of Numidia, then becoming an important province of Roman Africa and passing for a few decades under Vandal domination. Led by a succession of Arab-Muslim dynasties within Ifriqiya (إفريقية), the longest of which was that of the Aghlabids, then became an Ottoman regency, it came under French protectorate on May 12, 1881 with the signing of the Bardo Treaty. At independence, on March 20, 1956, Tunisia first became a constitutional monarchy with Lamine Bey as sovereign, the nineteenth and last reigning bey of the Husseinite dynasty. But, on July 25, 1957, the republic was proclaimed and the nationalist leader Habib Bourguiba became the first president of the Tunisian Republic. He modernized the country he led for thirty years, marked at the end by clientelism and the rise of Islamism.', 'The Tunisian economic situation remains tense and will be weakened by the economic consequences of the Covid-19 crisis. GDP fell by 8.6% in 2020, the main sectors of activity in Tunisia having been affected by the combination of the effects of confinement and the contraction of European demand (80% of Tunisian exports). The tourism sector (between 7% and 14% of GDP), after experiencing a clear recovery in 2019, is in crisis. Unemployment (15.5% and 30% of young graduates) is expected to rise sharply in the coming months. The crisis and its effects, by increasing public spending, will have long-term effects on public debt (70.5% of GDP in 2019, 90% in 2020, 92.7% in 2021) and the level of the deficit (4 .8% of GDP in 2019, 7.3% expected at the end of 2021).', 'The Tunisian revolution pushed Zine el-Abidine Ben Ali to the start, on January 14, 2011. The new Tunisian constitution was adopted in January 2014 and elections were organized, under good conditions: legislative elections of October 26, 2014, won by Nidaa Tounès, and presidential election of November 23 and December 21, 2014, from which Béji Caïd Essebsi emerged victorious. The first democratic municipal elections were organized on May 6, 2018. <br><br>\r\n\r\nAfter a serious illness on June 27, 2019, President Béji Caïd Essebsi died on July 25 in Tunis. In accordance with the constitution, the President of the Assembly of People\'s Representatives, Mr. Mohamed Ennaceur, served as interim Head of State, until the election of the new President of the Republic.<br>< br>The Libyan crisis is the first source of concern for the Tunisian authorities. Tunis adopts a position of strict neutrality in the Libyan file, while providing support to the government of national unity. Tunisia pleads for an inclusive political solution and remains hostile to any foreign military intervention. Tunisia hosted, in November 2020, the first session of the Libyan Political Dialogue Forum.', 'The territory of present-day Tunisia is home to the Capsian culture, a Mesolithic culture that lasted from 10,000 to 6,000 BC and to which the city of Gafsa gave its name. It is also the cradle of the Carthaginian civilization which reached its peak in the III .<br><br>The history of Tunisia is that of an independent North African nation since 1956. But it is part of there to cover the history of the Tunisian territory since the prehistoric period of the Capsian and the ancient civilization of the Punics, before the territory passed under the domination of the Romans, the Vandals and then the Byzantines. The 7th century marked a decisive turning point in the itinerary of a population which gradually became Islamized and Arabized under the reign of various dynasties which faced resistance from the Berber populations.\r\n\r\nBy its strategic location in the heart of the Mediterranean basin, Tunisia becomes the stake of the rivalry of successive powers, the Spain of Charles V, the young Ottoman Empire then France, which takes control of the Ottoman province to get ahead of its rival. Italian. Marked by profound structural and cultural transformations, Tunisia quickly saw a nationalist movement assert itself which concluded with the tutelary power the agreements leading to independence in 1956. From then on, the country was led on a forced march towards modernization and economic integration under the impetus of a political party that remained dominant until the 2011 revolution.', 'uploads/lova54.jpg', 'The festival lasts two days and the sheep are killed to commemorate Abraham\'s sacrifice; - Eid el-Saghir: two days at the end of the month of Ramadan; - the Mouled: anniversary of the birth of the Prophet; - Ras el-Am Hejri: New Year of the Hegira, 20 days after Ramadan.<br><br>The culture of Tunisia forms a synthesis of the different Amazigh, Punic, Roman, Jewish, Christian, Arab, Muslim cultures , Turkish and French, which it integrated to varying degrees, as well as the influence of the successive dynasties which reigned over the country. Tunisia has indeed been a crossroads of civilizations and its culture, the heritage of some 3,000 years of history, testifies to a country which, by its geographical position in the heart of the Mediterranean basin, was at the heart of the expansion movement of great civilizations of the mare nostrum and the main monotheistic religions.', 'uploads/La_joie_de_danser.jpg'),
(89, 'Zambia', 'Zambia, in long form the Republic of Zambia, in English: Zambia and Republic of Zambia, is a country in southern Africa, without access to the sea. Its population is estimated at 16 million inhabitants in 2017. Democratic Republic, its capital is Lusaka. Its name comes from the name of the Zambezi River.', 'zambia', 'Initially populated by the San, a people of hunter-gatherers, the Zambian territory was occupied by the Bantu in the 4th century. During European colonization of Africa, the territory became the British colony of Northern Rhodesia. It gained independence in 1964 under President Kenneth Kaunda, who established a one-party regime under the United National Independence Party in 1973. He was replaced by Frederick Chiluba of the Movement for Multi-Party Democracy. after the 1991 presidential election. Since then, Zambia has become a multi-party state, has experienced several peaceful transitions of power.<br><br>\r\n\r\nMostly covered by savannah, the country is still home to a rich biodiversity, with fauna and flora typical of varied landscapes and environments, while being the scene of growing urbanization and peri-urbanization, as well as an increase in cultivated areas. <br><br>\r\n\r\nColonial borders result in a great diversity of cultural groups, which are partially recognized by the state through the formalization of kings and local chiefs. A colonial heritage, English is the official language and must also promote the unity of the nation. As a former British colony, it has been part of the Commonwealth since its independence.', 'Zambia\'s trade balance has been in structural surplus in recent years. In 2021, exports of goods amounted to USD 11.1 billion, while imports reached USD 7 billion, resulting in a trade balance of USD 4.8 billion. <br><br> Zambia is a major exporter of copper and cobalt, but the deposits are increasingly inaccessible and less rich.\r\n\r\nFrom 2021, the Zambian government is thinking of developing copper extraction to meet global demand because the energy transition is copper-intensive. The idea being to make copper \"the oil of the future\". Zambia is also the second largest copper producer in Africa and the seventh in the world.\r\n\r\nIn January 2021, the Mopani mines, which have belonged to the heavily loss-making Swiss giant Glencore since 2000, were again nationalized by the Zambian government in exchange for a symbolic dollar as well as the assumption of debts estimated at 1.5 million dollars. dollars. The Zambian government\'s objective is to find an investor.', 'Zambia is a multi-party presidential republic, where the president is both head of state and head of government. The executive power is in the hands of the government while the legislative power is shared between the government and the parliament. Formerly Northern Rhodesia, Zambia became a republic upon its independence in October 1964.<br><br>In December 1990, at the end of a turbulent year that saw numerous riots in the capital as well as an attempted coup, President Kenneth Kaunda agreed to end the PUIN monopoly. A new constitution came into effect in August 1991, which increased the number of deputies from 136 to 158, created an electoral commission and authorized several candidates to run for president.', 'The history of Zambia, from the prehistoric era to the medieval era, is still relatively unknown. Although archaeological research contributes to making it one of the cradles of humanity and has also been able to attest to the existence of ancient kingdoms from the 11th century, proven and dated facts only date back to the 1820s.\r\n\r\nDuring the British colonial period, the territory was a protectorate known as Northern Rhodesia. The country gained independence in 1964.<br><br>The oldest human bones found in the territory of the future Zambia were those of the so-called Homo rhodesiensis, who is said to have lived more than 150,000 years old. 200,000 year old tools have also been found near Victoria Falls.\r\n\r\nThe first known inhabitants of the region were the San, nomadic hunter-gatherers, who remained the only inhabitants of the region until the 4th century, when the Bantu arrived from the north.', 'uploads/lova55.jpg', 'The culture of Zambia, a landlocked country in southern Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 15,000,000 inhabitants: 18,380,000 in 2020. <br><br>Today the different ethnic groups – Bantu-speaking – occupy territories that are sometimes quite distant from each other, but many are found in the more populated areas of the center, in Lusaka or in the Copperbelt. The Bembas (about 36%) live in the northeast, the Nyanjas (18%) in the east, the Tongas (15%) in the southwest. The Lozis (or Rotse, who gave their name to Barotseland) represent about 8% and are established in the far west of the country.\r\n\r\nEnglish has the status of official language, but other languages ​​are spoken, such as Bemba, Nyanja, Tonga, Lozi, Kilunda or Luvale.\r\n\r\nNearly three-quarters of the population are Christians. Protestants are about 35%, Catholics more than 25%. Nearly 10% are followers of independent African churches. The other Zambians remain committed to traditional African religions.', 'uploads/download (68).jpg'),
(90, 'Zimbabwe', 'Zimbabwe (/zɪmˈbɑːbweɪ, -wi/), officially the Republic of Zimbabwe, is a landlocked country in Southern Africa, between the Zambezi and Limpopo Rivers, bordered by South Africa to the south, Botswana to the southwest, Zambia to the north, and Mozambique to the east. The capital and largest city is Harare, and the second largest is Bulawayo.', 'zimbabwe', 'A country of roughly 15 million people,[15] Zimbabwe\'s largest ethnic group are the Shona, who make up 80% of the population, followed by the Northern Ndebele and other smaller minorities. Zimbabwe has 16 official languages,[4] with English, Shona, and Ndebele the most common.\r\n\r\nBeginning in the 9th century, during its late Iron Age, the Bantu people (who would become the ethnic Shona) built the city-state of Great Zimbabwe; the city-state became one of the major African trade centres by the 11th century. By the mid 15th century, the city-state had been abandoned.[16] From there, the Kingdom of Zimbabwe was established, followed by the Rozvi and Mutapa empires. The British South Africa Company of Cecil Rhodes demarcated the Rhodesia region in 1890 when they conquered Mashonaland and later in 1893 Matabeleland after a fierce resistance by Matabele people known as the First Matabele War. Company rule ended in 1923 with the establishment of Southern Rhodesia as a self-governing British colony.', 'Dans les années 1980, le Zimbabwe est l\'une des économies les plus développées et les plus richesses du continent africain. L\'État dispose de multiples atouts : puissance agricole (en particulier la culture du tabac) et industrielle, richesse en minéraux (pierres et métaux précieux, nickel, minéral de fer), services publics performants. À la fin des années 1990, le programme de réforme mis en place par la présidence Mugabe entraîne une chute drastique de la production dont les conséquences sur la croissance sont accentuées par les sanctions internationales. Le pays accumule également des arriérés de paiements importants vis-à-vis des Institutions Financières Internationales (IFI), des créanciers du club de Paris et des autres créanciers comme la Chine.<br><br>\r\n\r\nDepuis octobre 2018, le pays fait face à une grave crise de change et de confiance dans la monnaie domestique qui a durement affecté le pouvoir d\'achat des ménages. En 2019, le PIB s\'est fortement contracté de 8,3%. L\'inflation a atteint des niveaux à trois chiffres et la monnaie s\'est fortement dépréciée. Les effets de la crise ont été encore exacerbés par la survenue de chocs externes : le passage des cyclones Idaï et Kenneth en 2019, les épisodes de sécheresse qui ont entraîné une chute de la production agricole et hydroélectrique (qui représente environ la moitié de l\' énergie produite localement), la crise de la Covid-19 qui a accentué la régression et creusé le déficit public. La pénurie de devises limite également la capacité du pays à importer, notamment pour satisfaire ses besoins en électricité.<br><br>\r\n\r\nEn 2021, le Zimbabwe est toutefois la 2e économie d\'Afrique australe en termes de PIB derrière l\'Afrique du Sud (26 Mds USD) et la 15e du continent. L\'économie a rebondi, tirée par la reprise de l\'agriculture et de l\'industrie et par la stabilisation relative des prix (60,7% d\'inflation fin 2021 contre 838% en juillet 2020) et des taux de change.< br><br>\r\n\r\nLa crise a également joué comme un facteur aggravant des conditions sociales dans le pays : taux de pauvreté autour de 57 %, insécurité alimentaire persistante, blocage des services publics. Le Zimbabwe était 150e sur 189 pays au dernier classement IDH.', 'Après l\'indépendance le 18 avril 1980, Robert Mugabe, leader de la guérilla anticolonialiste de l\'Union nationale africaine du Zimbabwe (ZANU), est élu Premier ministre, puis devient chef de l\'Etat du Zimbabwe à partir de 1987 sur modification de la Constitution. Le 21 novembre 2017, le président Mugabe démissionne après trente-sept ans de présidence, dans un contexte de fortes tensions et de scissions au sein de la ZANU-PF entre les prétendants à la succession.<br><br>\r\n\r\nLe 24 novembre 2017, l\'ancien vice-président et ministre de la Défense, Emmerson D. Mnangagwa, est désigné président par intérim par la ZANU-PF, puis élu président de la République lors des élections du 30 juillet 2018. Ces élections générales (présidentielles, législatives et locales) sont marquées par une très forte participation (85 %). Le Président Mnangagwa (ZANU-PF) est proclamé vainqueur dès le 1er tour avec 50,67 % des voix, contre 44,3 % voix pour son opposant Nelson Chamisa (Alliance MDC). A l\'Assemblée nationale (270 sièges), la ZANU-PF remporte 180 sièges contre 87 pour l\'Alliance MDC, 1 siège pour le National Patriotic Front (NPF), 1 indépendant, et 1 siège pour le MDC-T (faction de l\'Alliance MDC exécutée par Mme Thokozani Khupe). Au Sénat (80 sièges), la ZANU-PF également la majorité avec 35 sièges. L\'Alliance MDC\r\n\r\nLes prochaines élections générales auront lieu en 2023.\r\n\r\n<br><br> La diplomatie zimbabwéenne repose notamment sur la solidarité avec les frères d\'armes, notamment les anciens membres de la Ligne de Front, qui se sont retrouvés au sein de la Communauté pour le développement de l\'Afrique australe (SADC) Le Zimbabwe est également membre de l\'Union africaine et du Marché commun de l\'Afrique australe et orientale (COMESA). Dans les enceintes internationales et sur le plan bilatéral, le Zimbabwe s\'oppose en revanche aux pays ayant pris des sanctions à son rencontre à la suite des violations des droits de l\'Homme commises lors de la réforme agraire de 2001 et des élections de 2002 et 2008 (Etats-Unis, Canada, Australie, Nouvelle-Zélande, Commonwealth). Le Zimbabwe n\'a pas modifié le Statut de Rome de la Cour pénale internationale (CPI).', 'L\'histoire du Zimbabwe remonte à l\'âge de la pierre, époque des plus anciennes traces de peuplement humain. L\'existence d\'anciennes civilisations développées durant la seconde moitié du Moyen Âge est attestée par des vestiges archéologiques d\'importance.\r\n\r\nSi les Portugais sont les premiers Européens à s\'aventurer dans le territoire au xvie siècle, ce n\'est qu\'à partir de 1890 que la colonisation commence. La région est sous influence britannique. Le territoire prend alors le nom de Rhodésie du Sud jusqu\'en 1965, puis, après l\'indépendance de la Rhodésie du Nord devenue Zambie, de Rhodésie jusqu\'à la fin du régime ségrégationniste.\r\n\r\nLe 18 avril 1980, la Rhodésie devient un État indépendant sous le nom de Zimbabwe (« Maison de pierre »). <br><br>Au début du xvie siècle, les Portugais installent des établissements le long de la côte mozambicaine. Plusieurs escarmouches ont lieu entre les natifs de l\'intérieur et les contingents militaires envoyés dans la colonie du Mozambique. Les négociants portugais et swahilis parvinrent également à jouer des rivalités entre tribus pour tenter de s\'imposer et de s\'emparer de tout l\'or qu\'ils trouvaient.\r\n\r\nEn 1629, le roi Mwene Mutapa Kapararidze échoua à fédérer les tribus indigènes contre les Portugais. Il fut déposé et remplacé par Mwene Mutapa Mavura, un vassal à la solde des Portugais. À la suite de plusieurs renversements d\'alliances et de rébellion, en 1690, les Portugais, qui avaient investi le plateau rhodésien, sont finalement expulsés par les troupes du Monomatapa. Mais le domaine de l\'ancien empire est dorénavant limité à la vallée du Zambèze (ainsi fragilisé, il s\'effondre définitivement à la fin du xixe siècle, victime des raids britanniques et portugais) alors que la dynastie Torwa est absorbée en 1684 par le clan Changamire, lequel fonde l\'empire rozvi.', 'uploads/lova56.jpg', 'Traditional arts in Zimbabwe include pottery, basketry, textiles, jewellery and carving. Among the distinctive qualities are symmetrically patterned woven baskets and stools carved out of a single piece of wood. Shona sculpture, which has a long cultural history, began evolving into its modern form in the mid 20th century and gained increasing international popularity.[290] Most subjects of carved figures of stylised birds and human figures among others are made with sedimentary rock such as soapstone, as well as harder igneous rocks such as serpentine and the rare stone verdite. Zimbabwean artefacts can be found in countries like Singapore, China and Canada. e.g. Dominic Benhura\'s statue in the Singapore Botanic Gardens.<br><br>\r\n\r\nTraditionally, Zimbabwean dance is not set for the concert stage. A dance, such as a ritual of spirit possession, may last twelve hours, or even days in length. Time is a very important aspect of these dances because the dancer must have time to enter the spirit world of possession, and re-enter the material world.', 'uploads/download (70).jpg'),
(91, 'Benin', 'Benin (/be.nɛ̃/), in long form the Republic of Benin (in Yoruba: Orílɛ̀-èdè Olómìnira ilɛ̀ Benin; in Gun-gbe: Beninto; in Fon: Benɛto), is a state in East Africa. West, which covers an area of ​​114,763 km2 and stretches 700 km from the Niger River in the north to the Atlantic coast in the south. Benin had 10,741,458 inhabitants in 20167. The country is one of the member states of ECOWAS and has as neighbors Togo to the west, Nigeria to the east, Niger to the northeast and Burkina Faso to the north. -west.', 'benin', 'Benin gained full independence on August 1, 1960, under the name of the Republic of Dahomey. The powers were transmitted to President Hubert Koutoukou Maga by the French Minister of State Louis Jacquinot. In 1972, officer Mathieu Kérékou took power: in 1974 he adopted Marxism-Leninism as the official ideology of the government and, in 1975, renamed the country People\'s Republic of Benin. At the end of the 1980s, internal struggles within the Communist Party of Benin and serious economic difficulties led to the end of the regime: Benin began a process of democratic transition and, in 1990, adopted a new Constitution. This democratic transition is ensured by Nicéphore Soglo, former Africa director of the World Bank. The name Benin is retained, the country simply becoming the Republic of Benin. Mathieu Kérékou, defeated in the elections by Nicéphore Soglo in 1991, relinquished power. He returned to it democratically through the ballot box in 1996 and did not restore the dictatorship. He ruled the country until 2006.\r\n\r\nThe official capital is Porto-Novo (named Hogbonou by the Gouns and Adjatchè by the Yorubas), Cotonou being the economic capital.', 'With a fiscal easing policy, the budget deficit remained high, at 5.5% of GDP in 2022 against 5.7% in 2021. The outstanding debt increased by 2.5 points of GDP to stand at to 52.8% of GDP in 2022, compared to 50.3% of GDP in 2021.<br><br>Benin\'s economy remains dependent on the agricultural sector and formal and informal re-export and transit trade activities with the Nigeria. The year 2022 was marked by a slight slowdown in growth, settling at 6% in 2022, after a strong rebound in 2021 to 7.2%. Agricultural production, especially cotton, and the service sector boosted the growth rate. Inflation accelerated to 2.5%, but remains moderate compared to the regional average, in particular thanks to targeted and temporary tax measures as well as good food crop production.<br><br>\r\n\r\nFiscal policy remained expansionary for a 3rd consecutive year with a deficit, albeit down slightly but still high, at 5.6% of GDP for 2022 against 5.7% in 2021. The expiration of certain fiscal support measures for the economy as well as the gradual increase in tax revenue will reduce the public deficit from 2024. While the risk of over-indebtedness continues to be considered moderate, public debt has grown sharply, rising from 41.2% of GDP in 2019 to 52.8% in 2022, i.e. an increase of 11.6 percentage points of GDP in 3 years.', 'With a fiscal easing policy, the budget deficit remained high, at 5.5% of GDP in 2022 against 5.7% in 2021. The outstanding debt increased by 2.5 points of GDP to stand at to 52.8% of GDP in 2022, compared to 50.3% of GDP in 2021.<br><br>Benin\'s economy remains dependent on the agricultural sector and formal and informal re-export and transit trade activities with the Nigeria. The year 2022 was marked by a slight slowdown in growth, settling at 6% in 2022, after a strong rebound in 2021 to 7.2%. Agricultural production, especially cotton, and the service sector boosted the growth rate. Inflation accelerated to 2.5%, but remains moderate compared to the regional average, in particular thanks to targeted and temporary tax measures as well as good food crop production.<br><br>\r\n\r\nFiscal policy remained expansionary for a 3rd consecutive year with a deficit, albeit down slightly but still high, at 5.6% of GDP for 2022 against 5.7% in 2021. The expiration of certain fiscal support measures for the economy as well as the gradual increase in tax revenue will reduce the public deficit from 2024. While the risk of over-indebtedness continues to be considered moderate, public debt has grown sharply, rising from 41.2% of GDP in 2019 to 52.8% in 2022, i.e. an increase of 11.6 percentage points of GDP in 3 years.', 'In the city of Abomey, a major place in the history of Benin, the thematic museum of Abomey will be built, associated with the museum of the royal palaces, already classified by Unesco.<br><br>This article covers the history of the territory of Benin since the sixteenth century, for the geographical area included in 1960 in what was then called the Republic of Dahomey before becoming the People\'s Republic of Benin.<br><br>\r\n\r\nAt the beginning of the 20th century, the three kingdoms ceased to be autonomous and merged into a whole divided into circles managed by administrators and cantons managed by African chiefs. During World War I, unrest broke out in the north of the country after indigenous troops were sent to the European front. At the end of the war, the colony was structured: the means of communication developed, agricultural production was rationalized and schooling increased. Under the influence of Catholic and Protestant missions on the one hand, of secular education on the other, primary and secondary education was set up. Integrated into French West Africa (AOF), the Dahomeans entered the civil service and served in other territories of the federation; the country is then often referred to as the Latin Quarter of Africa.', 'uploads/lova03.jpg', 'In Benin, people attach great importance to spirituality, and religious practice, whether traditional or modern, is an important part of daily life. Benin is considered the cradle of Vodoun, a traditional religion that some also call Animism.', 'uploads/download (71).jpg'),
(92, 'Burkina Faso', 'Burkina Faso (pronunciation: /buʁ.ki.na fa.so/ or /byʁ.ki.na fa.so/), literally \"homeland of (people) with integrity\" or \"homeland of integrity\", formerly the Republic of Upper Volta and commonly called Burkina, is a West African country without access to the sea surrounded by six countries: Mali to the northwest, Niger to the northeast, Benin and Togo to the southeast. east, Ghana to the south and Côte d\'Ivoire to the southwest. The capital Ouagadougou is located in the center of the country. The country is part of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), the Council of the Entente and the African Union.', 'burkina', 'In 1896, the Mossi kingdom of Ouagadougou became a French protectorate before becoming the colony of Upper Volta in 1919, then again in 1947. Independent of France since August 5, 1960, the Republic of Upper Volta was renamed Burkina Faso in 1984 under the regime of Thomas Sankara. The latter was overthrown by Blaise Compaoré and assassinated in 1987. The country did not experience a democratic regime before November 30, 2015 and the accession to the presidency of Roch Marc Christian Kaboré. This first democratic period ends in 2022 following the January and September coups which lead to the establishment of a military dictatorship against a background of increasing terrorist attacks. Since the mid-2010s, the country has in fact been the victim of the extension of the actions of armed jihadist groups to the entire Sahel.<br><br>\r\n\r\nIts population is estimated at 20,505,155. Burkina Faso is ranked (184th out of 191), with a human development index of 0.449 in 2021. It is a member of the Organization for the Harmonization of Business Law in Africa (OHADA) and the Organization for Cooperation Islamic.', 'After strong growth in 2021, the secondary sector contracted by 4.9% in 2022 due to the closure of several mines due to insecurity.<br><br>In 2022, Burkina Faso recorded a economic slowdown attributable to socio-political instability, military coups, deterioration of the security environment and the consequences of Russia\'s invasion of Ukraine. Thus, economic growth slowed to 3.2% in 2022, against 6.9% in 2021, due to the decline in extractive activities (–13.6% in 2022, against 7.3% in 2021) after the closure of some mines due to insecurity. On the other hand, the agricultural (+10.3% in 2022 against –12.3% in 2021) and tertiary (6.6% in 2022 against 13.5% n 2023) sectors sustained growth. On the demand side, the economy suffered from the decline in public investment. The inflation rate accelerated to 14.4% in 2022 with the increase in the cost of imports of food and petroleum products. The banking sector has increased its financing to the private sector by 16% in 2022. The increase in public expenditure (26.1% of GDP in 2022, against 25.6% in 2021) to meet security and humanitarian challenges and subsidies to petroleum products has widened the budget deficit (–8.5% of GDP in 2022, against –6.3% in 2021). This trend has been mitigated by the increase in tax revenue (16.3% of GDP in 2022, compared to 15.2% in 2020). With a moderate risk of debt distress, public debt is estimated at 57.2% of GDP in 2022, compared to 47.1% in 2021. The current account recorded a deficit of 5.2% of GDP, after a surplus of 0 .4% in 2021, due to the increase in the value of imports of food and energy products and a weak increase in exports. At the social level, the security context and the resulting humanitarian crisis have accentuated poverty in rural areas (estimated at 51.1% in 2019) and unemployment, with 57% of the population aged 15+ being unemployed.', 'Burkina Faso (pronunciation: /buʁ.ki.na fa.so/), literally “Land of Upright Men”, is a semi-presidential republic. The President of Faso is the head of state. The executive power is in the hands of the government and the president while the legislative power is shared between the government and the parliament. The judiciary is independent of the first two. Officially multi-party, political life was until 2014 dominated by the Congress for Democracy and Progress.<br><br>\r\n\r\nSince the January 2022 coup, the constitution has been suspended, the president and the government have been dismissed. Since September 2022, the head of state has been Ibrahim Traoré, head of the junta, the Patriotic Movement for Safeguarding and Restoration.', 'This article covers the history of the territory of Burkina Faso since the Neolithic era, for the geographical area included in 1960 in what was then called the Republic of Upper Volta before being renamed, in 1984, Burkina Faso. <br><br>Little is known about the ancient history of Burkina Faso. A Neolithic civilization produced cut stones, engraved patterns and pottery here in the 1st millennium BC. J.-C. Then appeared agriculture with clearing of the primary forest. A wave of riders[ref. desired] then came to graft a military aristocracy on this structure. Holders of political power, these riders made agreements with the natives who remained owners of the land. This organization still appears in the form of chefs de cantons and chefs de la terre.<br><br>During the First World War, despite resistance to conscription in Bwamu and Marka country, which led to the war of the Bani-Volta, the Mossi provide most of the Senegalese Tirailleurs contingent.\r\n', 'uploads/lova.png', 'Burkina Faso is a West African country rich in traditions and diverse cultures. The people of the country are proud of their traditions, dances and ceremonies which are an integral part of their cultural heritage. Indeed, Burkina is made up of more than sixty ethnic groups, each with their own traditions and customs. The most important traditions of the country are related to daily life, such as marriage, funeral, birth of a child, etc. Each of these occasions is celebrated with specific rituals that reflect the history and culture of the Burkinabé people.', 'uploads/download (72).jpg');
