(93, 'Cape Verde', 'Cape Verde, in long form the Republic of Cape Verde (in Portuguese: Cabo Verde and República de Cabo Verde) is an island state in West Africa, composed of an archipelago of ten volcanic islands. Located in the Atlantic Ocean, off the coasts of Senegal, and Mauritania, it covers an area of ​​approximately 4,000 km2. Praia, the capital, is 644 km west of the Cap-Vert peninsula in Senegal. The archipelago is divided into two series of islands: to the south, the islands of Sotavento (Brava, Fogo, Santiago and Maio) and to the north, the islands of Barlavento (Boa Vista, Sal, São Nicolau, Santa Luzia, São Vicente and Santo Antão). The island of Santiago alone comprises more than half of the country\'s population, and Praia is the country\'s largest city.', 'cap-vert', 'The islands were uninhabited before the arrival of the first Portuguese explorers in 1456. The first European colony in the tropics, it serves as a bridgehead for the slave trade and triangular trade. Cape Verde then attracted many corsairs and pirates, including Francis Drake around 1580. The naturalist Charles Darwin also visited the archipelago in 1832. The colony continued to grow in the 19th century, becoming a stopover on the maritime routes leading to India East and Australia. During the 20th century, several famines decimated the population. The country gained independence in 1975 and became a member of ECOWAS the following year. At that time, many Cape Verdeans emigrated abroad, constituting a diaspora larger in number than the resident population of the country. Most of the inhabitants define themselves today as Creoles.\r\n\r\nNowadays, Cape Verde has an economy centered on the production of services, especially in tourism. Speaking Portuguese and Cape Verdean Creole, its culture is nourished by European and African influences. Cape Verdean music and its different components (funaná, coladeira, morna, kizomba), were popularized around the world by the singer Cesária Évora. Catholicism is the dominant religion (90%) and the clergy still has a strong influence on the population, even if Islam tends to spread with the arrival of Malian and Senegalese migrants.', 'Cape Verde\'s GDP ranks 190th in the world in 2017, due to its weak natural resources. In particular, when it freed itself from colonial rule and gained independence in 1975, Cape Verde suffered from serious economic underdevelopment. It was also a regular victim of water shortages due to ancient deforestation and long periods of drought. Only four of the ten islands of the archipelago can sustain agricultural production during normal rainy periods. In 2007, Cape Verde left the group of least developed countries. Benefiting from a stable political life, marked by democratic alternations of the two main parties, he began to develop services and tourism.', 'Politics in Cape Verde is characterized by a state model of a semi-presidential democratic republic where the president is the head of state and the prime minister is the head of government. The constitution of Cape Verde, first approved in 1980 and substantially revised in 1992, defines the bases of governmental organization. It declares that the government is \"the body which defines, conducts and executes the general internal and external policy of the country\" and is responsible to the National Assembly. The Prime Minister is the head of government and in doing so appoints the other ministers and secretaries of state. Members of the National Assembly are elected by universal suffrage for a five-year term. The Prime Minister is appointed by the National Assembly and his office is conferred on him by the President. The President is the head of state and is elected by popular vote for a five-year term, renewable once.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe judicial system is composed of a Supreme Court of Justice, whose members are appointed by the President, the National Assembly and the Superior Council of the Judiciary, and regional courts of justice. Misdemeanors and crimes are not judged by the same courts. Appeal to the Supreme Court is possible.<br><br>\r\n\r\nAll citizens of Cape Verde aged 18 and over have the right to vote.', 'This article presents a summary of the history of Cape Verde, an island country in the Atlantic Ocean off the coast of Africa.\r\n\r\nThe Cape Verde Islands were uninhabited when Portuguese sailors first landed there, between 1456 and 1460. For this reason and the fact of the remoteness from the mainland, the country experienced a history radically different from the rest of the Africa. <br><br>\r\n\r\nCape Verde was discovered in the middle of the 15th century by navigators hired by the Portuguese prince Henry the Navigator. In 1462, they installed the first European city in the tropics there: Ribieira Grande, which was renamed Cidade Velha, and whose remains are classified as World Heritage by UNESCO.', 'uploads/lova9.jpg', '\r\nC\'est le plus important du pays, avec ses parades défilant dans les rues de Praia et de Mindelo. Aux mois de mai et juin, São Tiago et Fogo célèbrent la Tabanka, pendant laquelle on pratique le jeûne et l\'on joue de la musique. Chaque île a son propre festival qui se déroule pendant environ une semaine.<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nAu Cap-Vert, la musique est un élément essentiel pour les habitants. Dans la vie de tous les jours, pour les événements familiaux ou pour les nombreuses festivités organisées au niveau national et dans chaque île, les Cap-Verdiens dansent, chantent et jouent de la musique. Les rythmes cap-verdiens sont à l’image de la mixité de sa population.<br><br>\r\n Entre les morceaux tendres et mélancoliques des mornas, notamment interprétés par la célèbre chanteuse Cesária Évora, les coldeiras au tempo plus rapide, et le zouk à la rythmique dansante, c’est un mélange unique d’influences portugaises, africaines, brésiliennes et antillaises. Lors des carnavals, des festivals ou pour toute autre manifestation festive, les sons du cavaquinho, de la cimboa, du bombolong, et du ferrinho résonnent dans tous les environs. Partie intégrante de la culture du Cap-Vert, les chants, les musiques et les danses de tanbanka, de funaná ou de batuque mettent en joie les Cap-Verdiens et les visiteurs.\r\nIt is the most important in the country, with its parades marching through the streets of Praia and Mindelo. In May and June, São Tiago and Fogo celebrate Tabanka, during which fasting is practiced and music is played. Each island has its own festival that runs for about a week.<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nIn Cape Verde, music is an essential element for the inhabitants. In everyday life, for family events or for the many festivities organized nationally and on each island, Cape Verdeans dance, sing and play music. Cape Verdean rhythms reflect the diversity of its population.<br><br>\r\n Between the tender and melancholy pieces of the mornas, notably interpreted by the famous singer Cesária Évora, the coldeiras with a faster tempo, and the zouk with a dancing rhythm, it is a unique blend of Portuguese, African, Brazilian and West Indian influences. During carnivals, festivals or for any other festive event, the sounds of the cavaquinho, the cimboa, the bombolong, and the ferrinho resound in all the surroundings. An integral part of the culture of Cape Verde, the songs, music and dances of tanbanka, funaná or batuque bring joy to Cape Verdeans and visitors.', 'uploads/download (73).jpg'),
(96, 'Eswatini', 'Eswatini (/ˌɛswɑːˈtiːni/ ESS-wah-TEE-nee; Swazi: eSwatini [ɛswáˈtʼiːni]), formally the Kingdom of Eswatini and formerly named Swaziland (/ˈswɑːzilænd/ SWAH-zee-land) is a landlocked country in Southern Africa. It is bordered by Mozambique to its northeast and South Africa to its north, west, south, and southeast. At no more than 200 km (120 mi) north to south and 130 km (81 mi) east to west, Eswatini is one of the smallest countries in Africa; despite this, its climate and topography are diverse, ranging from a cool and mountainous highveld to a hot and dry lowveld.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe population is composed primarily of ethnic Swazis. The prevalent language is Swazi (siSwati in native form). The Swazis established their kingdom in the mid-18th century under the leadership of Ngwane III. The country and the Swazi take their names from Mswati II, the 19th-century king under whose rule the country was expanded and unified; its boundaries were drawn up in 1881 in the midst of the Scramble for Africa. After the Second Boer War, the kingdom, under the name of Swaziland, was a British high commission territory from 1903 until it regained its full independence on 6 September 1968. In April 2018, the official name was changed from Kingdom of Swaziland to Kingdom of Eswatini, mirroring the name commonly used in Swazi.', 'eswatini', 'Eswatini is a developing country and is classified as a lower-middle income economy. As a member of the Southern African Customs Union and the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa, its main local trading partner is South Africa; to ensure economic stability, Eswatini\'s currency, the lilangeni, is pegged to the South African rand. Eswatini\'s major overseas trading partners are the United States and the European Union. The majority of the country\'s employment is provided by its agricultural and manufacturing sectors. Eswatini is a member of the Southern African Development Community, the African Union, the Commonwealth of Nations, and the United Nations.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe government is an absolute monarchy, the last of its kind in Africa, and has been ruled by King Mswati III since 1986. Elections are held every five years to determine the House of Assembly and the Senate majority. Its constitution was adopted in 2005. Umhlanga, the reed dance held in August/September, and incwala, the kingship dance held in December/January, are the nation\'s most important events. <br><br>The Swazi population faces major health issues: HIV/AIDS and (to a lesser extent) tuberculosis are widespread. 28% of the adult population is HIV-positive. As of 2018, Eswatini has the 12th-lowest life expectancy in the world, at 58 years. The population of Eswatini is young. As of 2018, people aged 14 years or younger constitute 35% of the country\'s population and the median age is 22 years.', 'Eswatini\'s economy is diverse, with agriculture, forestry and mining accounting for about 13% of GDP, manufacturing (textiles and sugar-related processing) representing 37% of GDP and services – with government services in the lead – constituting 50% of GDP. Title Deed Lands (TDLs), where the bulk of high value crops are grown (sugar, forestry, and citrus), are characterized by high levels of investment and irrigation, and high productivity.[citation needed] About 75% of the population is employed in subsistence agriculture upon Swazi Nation Land (SNL). In contrast with the commercial farms, SNL suffers from low productivity and investment.\r\n\r\nThe cultivation of sugarcane, the country\'s largest export, has forced evictions of rural communities to build plantations, child labor and work weeks of up to 60 hours. The International Trade Union Confederation refers to \"arduous and unhealthy working conditions, miserable wages and violent repression of any attempt to unionize.\"[101] Economic growth has lagged behind that of neighboring countries. Real GDP growth since 2001 has averaged 2.8%, nearly 2 percentage points lower than growth in other Southern African Customs Union (SACU) member countries. Low agricultural productivity in the SNLs, repeated droughts, the devastating effect of HIV/AIDS and an overly large and inefficient government sector are likely contributing factors. Eswatini\'s public finances deteriorated in the late 1990s following sizeable surpluses a decade earlier. A combination of declining revenues and increased spending led to significant budget deficits.', '\r\nLandlocked between South Africa and Mozambique, Eswatini (formerly Swaziland) gained independence from the United Kingdom in 1968. The last absolute monarchy in Africa, the regime nevertheless has a Constitution that codifies custom. The country has been ruled by King Mswati III since April 1986.<br><br>\r\n\r\nOn the occasion of the 50th anniversary of Swaziland\'s independence (April 19, 2018), the King announced that his country was changing its name to return to its original name of \"Kingdom of Eswatini\" (\"the country of the Swazis\" in swati) on the grounds that Swaziland is the only southern African country to have retained its name from the time of British colonization.<br><br>\r\n\r\nA new constitution entered into force in February 2006. This text provides for freedom of association but still does not expressly authorize the re-establishment of political parties and does not guarantee the independence of the judiciary.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe parliamentary elections of September 21, 2018 were peaceful, with the exception of a few isolated incidents. The results are a failure for the opposition: none of the candidate members of SWADEPA, the main opposition party, present in 46 out of 59 constituencies, was elected. A new government was formed on November 6, 2018.<br><br>\r\n\r\nEswatini is a member of SADC (Southern African Development Community) and the Commonwealth. The kingdom supports the principle of expanding the United Nations Security Council to Africa (Ezulwini consensus). Eswatini was among the first countries to ratify the Paris Climate Agreement in fall 2016.<br><br>\r\n\r\nSouth Africa, which pleads in favor of a democratization of the regime, closely follows the evolution of the country. Pretoria strongly influences Eswatini\'s monetary policy as part of the Southern African Customs Union (SACU) and is by far Mbabane\'s largest trading partner.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe United States participates in the distribution of aid in social areas, in particular through the Clinton Foundation and the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria.', '\r\nEswatini\'s history dates back to ancient times and has remained largely unknown due to the lack of written records. Archaeological research has unearthed human bones demonstrating the presence of men 100,000 years ago.<br><br>\r\n\r\nBritish protectorate Swaziland, which became Eswatini in 2018, became independent in 1968. Ngwane\'s post-colonial name transplant never came to fruition.<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn the 4th century, the Bantu peoples migrating from Central Africa gradually began to push the Khoisans towards the south-west of southern Africa. By the 11th century, the Southern Sotho- and Nguni-speaking Bantus had definitively driven the Khoisans out of the region and settled permanently in the territory of the future Swaziland.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe Dlamini were a clan descended from the Nguni people and originally settled in Mozambique. In the mid-eighteenth century, King Ngwane III had led his people near the Pongola River in what is now southern Swaziland. It is from this period that dates the birth of the Swazi nation led by the Dlamini clan. The Dlamini clan emerged politically at the beginning of the 19th century during the mfecane, following the Zulu expansion. King Sobhuza I, who had succeeded Ngwane III, retired to the Ezulwini Valley, where he protected his people from the imperial designs of Chaka Zulu and then his successor Dingane (Battle of Lubuya in 1839).', 'uploads/lova17.jpg', 'Swazi culture is the way of life and customs of the Swazi people through various historical stages. The culture of Swazi people involves music, food, religion, architecture, and kinship, among many other things. The Swazi people are composed of various Nguni clans who speak the Nguni language siSwati. These people mostly reside in Eswatini and South Africa.<br><br> Presently, Swazi people may also include citizens of Eswatini. In Eswatini, one of the most visible features of cultural identity is the traditional political structure of the nation and the home. In the national level, the Ngwenyama (the \"Lion\", or King) is considered the head of the nation alongside the Ndlovukati (the \"She-Elephant\", or Queen Mother) who is the spiritual leader of the nation. <br><br>National cultural events often involve the Ngwenyama or Ndlovukati. At home, the patriarch of the family is the head and often practices polygamy. This headman, usually referred to as umnumzane is central to all activities of the home. A group of homes forming a community and the land they reside on forms a chiefdom or umphakatsi. Several chiefdoms form an inkhundla which then belongs of a regional division of the country. This connects the older traditional leadership structures to more modern forms of government.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThere are national cultural events such as umhlanga, emaganu and incwala which take place at Royal residences of the Ngwenyama and Ndlovukati. Local cultural events in communities or imiphakatsi, take place at the residence of the chief also called emphakatsini. Weddings, funerals and religious events are usually carried out at family homesteads where neighbors are usually invited to partake.', 'uploads/download (75).jpg'),
(95, 'Comoros', '\r\nThe Comoros, in long form the union of the Comoros (in Comorian: Komori and Udzima wa Komori, in Arabic: جزر القَمَر (Juzur al Qamar) and الاتّحاد القَمَريّ (al-Ittiḥād al-Qamariyy )), are an independent state of Southern Africa made up of three islands located in the northern Mozambique Channel, a maritime area of ​​the Indian Ocean.\r\n\r\nThe country\'s capital is Moroni, the official languages ​​are Comorian (shikomor), spoken by 96.9% of the population, French and Arabic, and the currency is the Comorian franc.\r\n\r\nThe Union of the Comoros is a member of the Arab League, the Organization of Islamic Cooperation, the International Organization of La Francophonie and the Parliamentary Assembly of La Francophonie. A French colony from 1892, the Comoros gained their independence on July 6, 1975.', 'comores', 'The Comoros are a volcanic archipelago located off the east coast of Africa in the warm waters of the Mozambique Channel in the Indian Ocean. The largest island of this nation-state, Grande Comore (Ngazidja), is surrounded by beaches and volcanic rock from the active Karthala volcano. In the capital, Moroni, carved doors and a colonnaded white mosque, the Old Friday Mosque, are spread around the port and the medina, bearing witness to the Arab past of the', 'The human development index places the union of the Comoros in 156th place out of 191 countries in 2021. The per capita income is estimated at 465 dollars in 2005. It is slightly below the average for sub-Saharan Africa (510 dollars) . In 2005, 60% of the population lived in poverty.\r\n\r\nMost of the population is rural and lives from food crops or fishing. There are no other growth sectors in the Comoros, with fishing and agriculture remaining subsistence activities and the tourism sector still in its infancy. The islands nevertheless export vanilla, ylang-ylang and cloves. The country is not self-sufficient in food. Stock shortages of petroleum products, but also other goods such as foodstuffs are recurrent. They are due, for example, to the lack of government funds for fuels, of fuel for water and electricity companies, of funds and foresight for private importers.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe economic situation makes daily life difficult for the inhabitants. The Comorian Diaspora, very united, contributes significantly to the survival of the population by sending money to the country.', 'The political system of the union of the Comoros is that of a federal republic with a presidential regime, multiparty and largely decentralized, where the president is both head of state and head of government. The executive power is in the hands of the government while the federal legislative power is shared between the government and the parliament. The Constitution provides that a representative of each of the islands accedes every four years to the post of president of the government. Grande Comore was represented between 2002 to 2006 and Anjouan was from 2006 to 2010. Since then, the representative of Mohéli Ikililou Dhoinine, has acceded to the supreme magistracy and it is he who is currently in office. Considering that Mayotte is an integral part of its territory, the constitution of the union of the Comoros has provided in its Constitution that this rotating presidency falls to the Ile aux Parfums in 2016. The constitution provides for a Mahorais to become president in 2016. So that Mayotte has become a French department, a period of vacancy or a constitutional problem will arise from this situation. Journalist Hakim Ali Saïd presented himself as a candidate.<br><br> On May 12, 2016, following partial elections in 13 offices on the island of Anjouan, complementing the general elections of April 10, the vice-president of the CENI announced the victory of Azali Assoumani as president, in great confusion caused by the departure without explanation of the president of the CENI and some of his colleagues.', 'From 1908 to 1946, the Comoros were administratively attached to Madagascar. This official link facilitated the obtaining of visas for the Comorians who came to settle mainly in Diego-Suarez (in the north), in Antananarivo (in the center) and especially in Mahajunga (in the northwest) in order to work.<br> <br>Inhabited for nearly two millennia, the different islands of the Comoros have had a very similar history with several waves of migration. These islands have long been known to Arab pirates, they are even mentioned in the tales of the Thousand and One Nights. A passage describes the native population living there. Then it was France, a colonial power, which administratively united the islands. The history of the islands separates again after the formation in 1976 of the Islamic Federal Republic of the Comoros and the wish of the Mahoran population to remain French.', 'uploads/lova11.jpg', 'Comorian culture is historically a southern subdivision of the important Swahili culture, an African cultural ensemble of Bantu origin, Indian and Arab-Muslim influence[citation needed], present on the entire East African coast and part of the islands of the western Indian Ocean (region formerly called \"Zanguebar\"), and whose main historical political unit was in the 19th century the great Sultanate of Muscat and Oman (which would become the Sultanate of Zanzibar at the end of the 19th century, to which the islands of the Comoros did not however, never formally belonged). The Comoros, however, constitute a satellite region of this cultural group - hence the fact that the different Comorian dialects are linguistically slightly distant from continental Kiswahili - marked by many other strong influences such as Malagasy cultures (very important in Mayotte, much less in the Comoros), Persian (Shirazie), Indian or of course French, especially through Mayotte', 'uploads/download (74).jpg'),
(97, 'Mauritius', 'Mauritius (in English: Mauritius), in long form the Republic of Mauritius (in English: Republic of Mauritius), is an island state in the Indian Ocean 868 kilometers east of Madagascar and 172 kilometers east- northeast of Reunion. The country includes the main island of Mauritius, but also Rodrigues Island 560 kilometers east of the main island. The more distant islands of Agaléga and Saint-Brandon are part of the national territory. The islands of Mauritius and Rodrigues are part of the Mascareignes archipelago, with the island of La Réunion, which is a French overseas department. The total area of ​​the country is 2,040 km2. The capital and largest city is Port-Louis.', 'mauritius', 'A former Dutch (1638-1710) and French (1715-1810) colony, Mauritius became a British colonial possession in 1810 and remained so until 1968, the year of its independence. The British colony of Mauritius once included the present territories of Mauritius, Rodrigues, the remote islands of Agaléga, Saint-Brandon, the Chagos Archipelago and the Seychelles. Mauritian territories were gradually reduced with the creation of a specific colony of Seychelles in 1903. Today, sovereignty over the Chagos Archipelago is disputed between Mauritius and the United Kingdom. The United Kingdom amputated the archipelago from Mauritian territory in 1965, three years before its independence. He gradually depopulated the archipelago of its indigenous population and rented its largest island, Diego Garcia, to the United States, which made it a military base. Access to the archipelago is forbidden to tourists, the media and its former inhabitants. Mauritius also claims, from France, its sovereignty over the small island Tromelin.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe population of Mauritius is multi-ethnic, multi-confessional, multi-cultural and multilingual. The government of the country is very close to the Westminister parliamentary system, and Mauritius is highly rated in terms of freedoms and democracy7. In 2021, Mauritius\' Human Development Index (0.802) is the highest in the African region and 63rd globally4.<br><br>\r\n\r\nAlong with the other Mascarene Islands, Mauritius is known for its fauna and flora, with several species endemic to the country. The island is particularly famous for the dodo, which along with other endemic species, became extinct shortly after the arrival of the first human beings.<br><br>\r\n\r\nMauritius is the only country in the African zone where Hinduism is the main religion. The government uses English as the main language and French as the second language. Mauritian Creole is spoken by the majority of the population, but is not officially recognized by the Constitution.', 'Economy of Mauritius refers to the economic activity of the Republic of Mauritius. The Mauritian economy is often presented as an example in Africa and one of (or the) best performing in Africa. It is also an economy that has grown by almost 5% per year on average since independence. Mauritius is now in the category of high middle income countries. For 2017, various estimates show a GDP/capita of $10,000 (in nominal terms, i.e. at the exchange rate between the dollar and the Mauritian rupee) and $20,000 (in power parity purchasing power, i.e. at an exchange rate so that the purchasing power between dollar and rupee is the same, in an exchange rate without overvaluation or undervaluation of the rupee).\r\n\r\nThe financial services sector alone represents nearly 50% of GDP in 2017, compared to 7% for tourism and 15% for industry.', 'Prime Minister Pravind Jugnauth, who arrived at the head of the Mauritian government in January 2017 following the resignation of the previous Prime Minister, his father Sir Anerood Jugnauth, was reappointed after the victory of his coalition, the Morisien Alliance , in the legislative elections of November 7, 2019. The latter then won an absolute majority (42 seats out of 70) in the National Assembly.<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn opposition, the National Alliance, which brings together the Labor Party of former Prime Minister Navin Ramgoolam and the Mauritian Social Democratic Party of Xavier-Luc Duval (current leader of the parliamentary opposition), obtains only 17 seats; the Mauritian Militant Movement of Paul Bérenger, engaged alone in the campaign, has only 9.<br><br>\r\n\r\nOn the proposal of the Prime Minister, the National Assembly of Mauritius elected on December 2, 2019 Mr. Prithvirajsing Roopun as President of the Republic of Mauritius and Mr. Marie Cyril Eddy Boissézon as Vice-President. These two functions are essentially ceremonial, with executive power being held by the Prime Minister.<br><br>\r\n\r\nMauritius is home to the headquarters of the Indian Ocean Commission (IOC), of which it is to take over the annual presidency during the second quarter of 2023. Mauritius also hosts the general secretariat of the IORA (Indian Ocean Rim Association - Association of Riparian States of the Indian Ocean), of which France became a member in December 2020.<br><br>\r\n\r\nIt is present in several regional and African organizations: African Union, SADC (Southern African Development Community - the Southern African Development Community), COMESA (Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa - the Common Market for Eastern Africa and southern). Mauritius is also a member of the Vanilla Islands Association, the International Organization of La Francophonie (OIF) and the Commonwealth.<br><br>\r\n\r\nVery low emitter of greenhouse gases, Mauritius is active within the group of Small Island Developing States (SIDS).', 'THE HISTORY OF MAURITIUS. Discovered by the Portuguese in 1507, then occupied by the Dutch from 1598 to 1710, Mauritius became the possession of the Compagnie des Indes in 1715, and of the King of France in 1767, who named it Île de France. <br><br>In 1494, the Treaty of Tordesillas will leave the field open to the Portuguese in Africa and the Indian Ocean. The Portuguese will divert to their advantage the trade in spices, gold, ivory and slaves. This will deal a severe blow to Arab trade and accelerate the decadence of the Muslim states of the Mediterranean. The Portuguese no longer want to depend on the Arabs to supply themselves with exotic products.\r\n\r\nFrom 1500, they undertook the conquest of all the Arab trading posts on the African coast of the Indian Ocean. Catches that will be made by force.', 'uploads/lova34.jpg', 'The culture of Mauritius, a small island country in southern Africa, first refers to the observable cultural practices of its 1,500,000 inhabitants. Mauritian culture is characterized by an astonishing diversity of imaginations, languages ​​and texts. This one is very influenced by Caribbean culture.<br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nThe National Museum of Natural History of Port-Louis.\r\nIndeed, on this island, originally deserted, discovered by the Arabs, visited by the Portuguese and the Dutch, with a lasting phase of French and English colonization, Africans, taken as slaves, rubbed shoulders with coolies or Indians and Chinese, especially traders. A population of mestizos or mulattos developed there, mainly from blacks, also called creoles, and whites, from France.<br><br>These numerous migrations, marked by slavery and indenture, created conflicts and violence that marked the collective unconscious of this small democratic country, which became independent in 1968. However, there remains a potential for encounters, and a miracle of coexistence between Hindus from North and South India, Christians, Muslims , Taoists and Buddhists that deeply mark the visitor.', 'uploads/download (76).jpg'),
(98, 'Sao Tome', 'São Tomé and Príncipe, an African island state near the equator, is part of a volcanic chain with stunning rock and coral formations, rainforests and beaches. The largest island, São Tomé, is home to the lagoon of Lagoa Azul. The Ôbo Natural Park, a jungle protected for its biodiversity, covers most of the territory of São Tomé and is distinguished by the Pico Cão Grande, a volcanic rock similar to a skyscraper.', 'sao-tome', 'Sao Tomé and Principe, São Tomé and Príncipe or Saint Thomas and Prince\'s Island, in long form the Democratic Republic of Sao Tomé and Principe (in Portuguese: São Tomé e Príncipe, A Ilha of São Tomé and Príncipe and República Democrática de São Tomé and Príncipe), is an island state in Central Africa, one of the smallest countries in Africa. It occupies an archipelago in the central South Atlantic located in the Gulf of Guinea, 239 km from the coast of Gabon (São Tomé) and 216 km from Equatorial Guinea (Principe).\r\n\r\nIt is made up of two main islands, São Tomé to the southwest and Principe to the northeast, lying between the two Equatoguinean islands of Bioko to the north and Annobón to the south. The entire territory covers an area of ​​approximately 1,000 km2. The volcanic relief culminates at more than 2,000 m, the climate is of the equatorial type. Agriculture - and in particular the production of cocoa - retains an important place, but the expected exploitation of hydrocarbons and the potential for tourism have given rise to great hopes in a poor country, which remains largely dependent on international aid. Sao Tome and Principe is a former colony of Portugal, independent since 1975, and its official language is Portuguese.', 'The economy of Sao Tome and Principe is that of a small island country in Central Africa, a former Portuguese colony, which the main indicators place among the least developed on the planet and half of whose population lives below the of poverty. The archipelago of Sao Tome and Principe traditionally derives most of its resources from agriculture, and in particular from cocoa production - which has earned it the nickname of \"Chocolate Island\", but founds new hopes on the exploitation of hydrocarbons and tourism.<br><br>Santomean economy has suffered from economic imbalances for many years, characterized by a structurally deficit trade balance (- 132 MUSD in 2021). The crisis caused by the COVID pandemic has aggravated the difficulties encountered by the archipelago: situation of over-indebtedness since 2018 amplified in 2020 and 2021, rise in inflation to 8.2%, decline of 0.2% in GDP per capita , etc.\r\n\r\nHowever, Sao Tome & Principe continues to benefit from the support of international donors and the IMF program currently underway is showing satisfactory results.', 'São Tomé and Príncipe is a member of the Community of Portuguese Language Countries (CPLP). The archipelago belongs to several other regional organizations, including the Economic Community of Central African States (ECCAS) and the Gulf of Guinea Commission. Ties remain strong with Portugal and Sao Tome and Principe has also forged close relations with Brazil and Angola.\r\n\r\nWhile Sao Tome and Principe recognized Taiwan since 1997, the Santomean government announced on December 20, 2016 the severance of diplomatic relations with Taipei and the establishment, on December 26, 2016, of diplomatic relations with the People\'s Republic of China. <br><br>\r\n\r\nA former Portuguese colony, Sao Tome and Principe has been independent since July 12, 1975. President Manuel Pinto da Costa then established a single-party Marxist regime, the Liberation Movement of Sao Tome and Principe (MLSTP).\r\n\r\nUnder the new Constitution of September 1990, the archipelago became a democratic parliamentary republic which opened up to a multiparty system. The first presidential election was won by Miguel Trovoada in 1991. Despite two coup attempts in 2003 and 2009, parliamentary democracy asserted itself and repeatedly allowed an alternation between the two great forces that animate political life: Independent Democratic Action (ADI) of Patrice Trovoada (son of Miguel Trovoada, he was Prime Minister from 2010 to 2012 and from 2014 to 2018) and the Movement for the Liberation of Sao Tome and Principe (MLSTP) of Jorge Bom Jesus .', 'The islands of São Tomé and Príncipe were colonized by the Portuguese in the 16th century and for hundreds of years were an important trading post during the slave trade until its abolition in the 1800s. Contract labor then took the fore, which brought indentured laborers from several African countries to work on the many plantations in the country. Some of these plantations are still active today and can be visited.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThis status quo remained in place for many decades until the post-WWII period changed the international political climate forever. In 1950, the country saw the formation of the Movement for the Liberation of São Tomé and Príncipe (MLSTP). The movement worked for many years to gain independence but was unsuccessful.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe turning point in the country came in 1974 with the overthrow of Portuguese dictator President Salazar by the people of Portugal. The new government was firm on the idea that all nations should be sovereign and granted independence to São Tomé and Príncipe in 1975, appointing the General Secretary of the MLSTP as president.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe year 1990 was an historic year, not only for the country, but for the African continent, as São Tomé e Príncipe was one of the first African countries to introduce a new constitution that embraced democratic reforms. These reforms included a multiparty system and general elections.\r\n\r\nToday, democracy in the country is still strong and economic strides are being made to develop more infrastructures and manufacture more goods.', 'uploads/lova44.jpg', 'As is evidenced by the São Tomé’s history, the main cultural influences are Portuguese – as a result of the country’s long colonial ties with the European nation – and West African – due to the many slaves that were brought from this region to work on plantations during the slave trade. Both of these influences can be seen clearly in such cultural markers as music and cuisine.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe country’s music is a wonderful amalgamation of African rhythms and Portuguese styles. The African beats are particularly West African in nature, boasting such styles as ussua and socope, and relying heavily on drumming and percussion. That said, Portuguese ballroom dancing is a tradition that has remained incredibly popular, with many national competitions being held around the country.<br><br>\r\n\r\nSão Toméan cuisine is based in equal parts on African traditions and Portuguese influence. Common ingredients are roots like cassava, plantains, and bananas. Unsurprisingly, seafood is a favorite here and there are many seafood dishes which speak loudly of the country’s Portuguese heritage. One such dish is a spicier variation of the Portuguese paella.', 'uploads/download (77).jpg'),
(99, 'Seychelles', '\r\nSeychelles officially the Republic of Seychelles (French: République des Seychelles; Creole: La Repiblik Sesel), is an island country and archipelagic state consisting of 115 islands in the Indian Ocean. Its capital and largest city, Victoria, is 1,500 kilometers (800 nautical miles) east of mainland Africa. Nearby island countries and territories include the Comoros, Madagascar, Mauritius, and the French overseas departments of Mayotte and Réunion to the south; and Maldives and the Chagos Archipelago (administered by the United Kingdom as the British Indian Ocean Territory) to the east. Seychelles is the smallest country in Africa as well as the least populated sovereign African country, with an estimated population of 100,600 in 2022 .', 'seychelles', 'Seychelles was uninhabited prior to being encountered by Europeans in the 16th century. It faced competing French and British interests until coming under full British control in the late 18th century. Since proclaiming independence from the United Kingdom in 1976, it has developed from a largely agricultural society to a market-based diversified economy, characterized by rapidly rising service, public sector, and tourism activities. From 1976 to 2015, nominal GDP grew nearly 700%, and purchasing power parity nearly 1600%. Since the late 2010s, the government has taken steps to encourage foreign investment.<br><br>\r\n\r\nAs of the early 21st century, Seychelles has the highest nominal per capita GDP of any African nation. It has the second-highest Human Development Index of any African country after Mauritius.\r\n\r\nSeychellois culture and society is an eclectic mix of French, British, and African influences, with more recent infusions of Chinese and Indian elements. The country is a member of the United Nations, the African Union, the Southern African Development Community, and the Commonwealth of Nations.', 'The Seychelles have been classified since 2015 in the category of high-income countries (10,764 USD per capita in 2022, the highest in Africa). They are the only representatives of Africa in this category.<br><br>\r\n\r\nIn 2022, the country recorded a GDP growth rate of 5.8% due to the rebound in tourism.\r\n\r\nThe UNDP ranks Seychelles in the category of “high human development” countries in 2021 (HDI at 0.785, i.e. 72nd out of 191 countries, down slightly). Seychelles is steadily rising in Transparency International\'s corruption perception ranking (from 45th place in 2014 to 23rd in 2022).<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe Seychelles economy also remains poorly diversified and vulnerable to international shocks. Its first pillar is tourism, the sector of which has been experiencing strong growth for several years (with the exception of the years 2020-2021 due to the pandemic). France was in 2022 the second provider of tourists to the Seychelles, behind Germany. The second pillar of the Seychelles economy is fishing, in particular industrial tuna fishing. Victoria is indeed one of the busiest tuna ports in the world.', '\r\nIndependent since 1976, the Seychelles archipelago suffered a coup in 1977, leading to the establishment of a Marxist-inspired one-party regime led by France Albert René. James Michel, his successor as President of the Republic from 2004 to 2016, manages to consolidate the transition of Seychelles towards a pluralist democracy and a liberal economy.<br><br>\r\n\r\nSeychellois political life is bipolarized between the United Seychelles Party (formerly SPPF at independence - Seychelles People\'s Progressive Front - then Lepep, the people in Creole, from 2009 to 2018), in power from independence until the last elections in October 2020, and the SNP (Seychelles National Party), led by the current president, Wavel Ramkalawan, which was the main opposition party.<br><br>\r\n\r\nSeychelles is a member of several regional and international organizations: the African Union (AU), the Indian Ocean Commission (IOC), COMESA (Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa - the Common Market for Eastern Africa and South Africa), SADC (Southern African Development Community), IORA (Indian Ocean Rim Association), Vanilla Islands Association, Organization internationale de la Francophonie (OIF), the Commonwealth, and the International Criminal Court (ICC).<br><br>\r\n\r\nSeychelles voted in favor of all resolutions passed by the UN General Assembly following the Russian invasion of Ukraine.\r\n\r\nFollowing the eruption of maritime piracy of Somali origin in the Indian Ocean and in the Seychelles exclusive economic zone (EEZ) in 2009, the Seychelles invested in the regional maritime security architecture. They thus support the European Atalanta counter-piracy mission. Victoria is also home to the headquarters of the IOC\'s Regional Center for Operational Cooperation (RCCO), established in 2017 as part of the European Union-funded Maritime Security (MASE) project.', 'Because they are located too far from busy shipping routes, it is almost certain that the Seychelles were not visited by the first Persian and Arab sailors who sailed in the Indian Ocean around the coasts of Asia, Persian Gulf, North Africa and the Red Sea. On the other hand, there is no doubt that they were, much later, the first visitors to the Seychelles, long before its “discovery”. The merchant Al Mas\'eudi, who regularly visited the Maldives in the fourteenth century, spoke in his writings of the \"high islands\" that were on his route. The discovery of graves in 1910 confirmed the presence of Arab sailors on the island. In 14th and 15th century documents, the Seychelles appear as Zarin, the sisters.<br><br>\r\n\r\nThe Portuguese are the first Europeans to venture into the Indian Ocean. In 1498, Vasco da Gama rounds the Cape of Good Hope and is the first European to reach India – with the assistance of an Arab navigator. In March 1503, during a second trip to India, Vasco da Gama reached the islands that today belong to the Seychelles, Silhouette Island and then Desroches Island, according to Thomé Lopes (en) reports by writing of the voyage of the 4th Portuguese Armada to the Indies (Gama, 1502), according to the compilation Delle Navigationi et Viaggi (1550-1559) by Giovanni Battista Ramusio. From 1506, the Seychelles began to appear under different names on Portuguese maps. It is therefore likely that the Portuguese passed several times near these islands and possibly stopped there. There is no evidence to suggest that they founded colonies, the islands serving them above all as a source of food supply, for example with giant tortoises. With the help of Arab navigators, the Portuguese explore the region: Madagascar, the Comoros archipelago, Reunion and Mauritius.', 'uploads/lova46.jpg', 'European and British, African, Indian and even Moorish cultures are intertwined in the traditions of Seychelles people. All these cultures are reflected in the speech of the Creoles and in the art: music, dances, theatre.  <br><br>\r\nIf you want to witness the melting of cultures of different ethnic groups into one place all at the same time, the Creole Festival is something you definitely would not want to miss. Held in October every year, this week-long celebration is an escape from the dull, monotonous life. You can dive into the sea of cultures and explore exotic cuisines, drinks, music and dance and that too with a multi-racial tinge. The festival is organized on the islands of Praslin, La Digue and Mahe. The Creole Festival is a symbolic tribute to the colourful culture, customs, traditions and practices of the Creole lifestyle.', 'uploads/download (78).jpg');

